{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Vg8je3XJxQHFfseh1JkkZD","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t                                       ANL-ART-47\n2\t\n3\t\n4\t\n5\t\n6\tFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the\n7\tAir-based Natural convection Shutdown heat\n8\tremoval Test Facility (NSTF)\n9\t\n10\t\n11\t\n12\t\n13\tNuclear Engineering Division\n14\t\fAbout Argonne National Laboratory\n15\tArgonne is a U.S. Department of Energy laboratory managed by UChicago Argonne, LLC\n16\tunder contract DE-AC02-06CH11357. The Laboratory’s main facility is outside Chicago, at\n17\t9700 South Cass Avenue, Argonne, Illinois 60439. For information about Argonne\n18\tand its pioneering science and technology programs, see www.anl.gov.\n19\t\n20\t\n21\t\n22\t\n23\tDOCUMENT AVAILABILITY\n24\t   Online Access: U.S. Department of Energy (DOE) reports produced after 1991 and a\n25\t   growing number of pre-1991 documents are available free via DOE’s SciTech Connect\n26\t   (http://www.osti.gov/scitech/)\n27\t\n28\tReports not in digital format may be purchased by the public from the\n29\tNational Technical Information Service (NTIS):\n30\t  U.S. Department of Commerce National\n31\t  Technical Information Service 5301\n32\t  Shawnee Rd\n33\t  Alexandria, VA 22312\n34\t  www.ntis.gov\n35\t  Phone: (800) 553-NTIS (6847) or (703) 605-6000\n36\t  Fax: (703) 605-6900\n37\t  Email: orders@ntis.gov\n38\t\n39\tReports not in digital format are available to DOE and DOE contractors from the\n40\tOffice of Scientific and Technical Information (OSTI):\n41\t  U.S. Department of Energy\n42\t  Office of Scientific and Technical Information\n43\t  P.O. Box 62\n44\t  Oak Ridge, TN 37831-0062\n45\t  www.osti.gov\n46\t  Phone: (865) 576-8401\n47\t  Fax: (865) 576-5728\n48\t  Email: reports@osti.gov\n49\t\n50\t\n51\t\n52\t\n53\tDisclaimer\n54\tThis report was prepared as an account of work sponsored by an agency of the United States Government. Neither the United States\n55\tGovernment nor any agency thereof, nor UChicago Argonne, LLC, nor any of their employees or officers, makes any warranty, express or\n56\timplied, or assumes any legal liability or responsibility for the accuracy, completeness, or usefulness of any information, apparatus,\n57\tproduct, or process disclosed, or represents that its use would not infringe privately owned rights. Reference herein to any specific\n58\tcommercial product, process, or service by trade name, trademark, manufacturer, or otherwise, does not necessarily constitute or imply its\n59\tendorsement, recommendation, or favoring by the United States Government or any agency thereof. The views and opinions of document\n60\tauthors expressed herein do not necessarily state or reflect those of the United States Government or any agency thereof, Argonne\n61\tNational Laboratory, or UChicago Argonne, LLC.\n62\t\f                                                                                     ANL-ART-47\n63\t\n64\t\n65\t\n66\t\n67\tFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-\n68\tbased NSTF\n69\t\n70\t\n71\t\n72\t\n73\tprepared by:\n74\tDarius D. Lisowski, Craig D. Gerardi, Dennis J. Kilsdonk, Nathan C. Bremer, Stephen W. Lomperski,\n75\tRui Hu, Adam R. Kraus, Matthew D. Bucknor, Qiuping Lv, Taeseung Lee, and Mitchell. T. Farmer\n76\t\n77\t\n78\t\n79\tNuclear Engineering Division, Argonne National Laboratory\n80\t\n81\t\n82\t\n83\t\n84\tAugust 2016\n85\t\fThis page was intentionally left blank.\n86\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n87\tAugust 2016\n88\t\n89\t\n90\t\n91\t\n92\tExecutive Summary\n93\tThe following report serves as a comprehensive summary of the air-based portion of the Nat-\n94\tural convection Shutdown heat removal Test Facility (NSTF) program at Argonne National\n95\tLaboratory (Argonne). Initiated in 2005 to generate validation data for the Next Genera-\n96\ttion Nuclear Plant (NGNP), the project was centered on an experimental testing program to\n97\tstudy the behavior and bound the performance of Reactor Cavity Cooling System (RCCS)\n98\tconcepts. Parallel modeling and simulation efforts also have been performed to guide the\n99\tdesign, fabrication, and operation of NSTF, as well as to assess the suitability of analysis\n100\tmethods for natural convection systems. The program operates under support from the De-\n101\tpartment of Energy (DOE) Office of Advanced Reactor Technologies (ART), and maintained\n102\tcompliance with NQA-1 2008 with 2009a in both administrative and technical portions of\n103\tprogram activities.\n104\t\n105\t   The test facility constructed at Argonne stands nearly 26-m in total height and has\n106\tbeen designed to represent a 1/2 scale model of the primary features of the General Atomic\n107\t(GA) RCCS design for their Modular High Temperature Gas cooled Reactor (MHTGR).\n108\tThe heated surface of the NSTF was constructed from prototypic, reactor-grade material\n109\tand driven by a heat source originating from a forty-zone array of electric heaters. Sup-\n110\tplying up to 220 kW of electric power, the array was able to accurately mimic the walls\n111\tof a Reactor Pressure Vessel (RPV) through profile shaping to achieve axial or azimuthal\n112\tskews. An integrated suite of data acquisition and high-resolution sensors have guided ex-\n113\tperimental practices and allowed the direct measurement of both system thermal hydraulic\n114\tbehavior and local phenomena. Measurement such as flow rates, gas and wall temperatures,\n115\tand differential pressure by calibrated instrumentation ensured confidence in determining\n116\theat removal capacity and accurately observing system behavior. A weather station has\n117\tcharacterized the ambient and meteorological boundary conditions that have shown to be\n118\t\n119\t                                                i                               ANL-ART-47\n120\t\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n121\t                                                                                      August 2016\n122\t\n123\t\n124\tdominant factors in influencing the sensitive natural circulation phenomena. Additionally,\n125\thigh fidelity sensors including hot-wire probes and distributed temperature sensing fibers\n126\thave introduced an unparalleled data density and insight into local flow and heat transfer\n127\tmodes.\n128\t\n129\t   The testing program, spanning a 33-month period from September 2013 until July 2016,\n130\tcompleted over 2,250 hours of active test operations and 16 successful test runs. Studies of\n131\tscaling, power shaping, flow path configuration, design basis accident conditions, weather in-\n132\tfluences, and off-normal scenarios were performed and compared against routinely repeated\n133\tbaseline test cases. Special considerations were made to include full-scale features and op-\n134\terating conditions, such as adjacent chimney roles, cosine power shaping, and the full time\n135\thistory of one Safety Related Design Condition (SRDC-II). The effects of weather and re-\n136\tpeatability were assessed through regular testing of a baseline test case, scheduling select\n137\toperations to occur during inclement weather, and isothermal testing for facility characteri-\n138\tzation purposes.\n139\t\n140\t   Final observations from the project have indicated that a high level of performance can be\n141\tobtained from the air-RCCS concept design if the as-intended path of the natural circulation\n142\tflow can be maintained. Disruptions of blocked riser channels (50% flow area tested), chimney\n143\tshort-circuit scenarios, strong asymmetries from the heated source, and moderate shifts\n144\tin weather conditions were found to have negligible impacts on the overall heat removal\n145\tperformance. Measured temperature excursions by the RPV surface, an indicator of peak\n146\tfuel temperatures, did not rise above 5% of normal values across the conditions tested.\n147\t\n148\t   However, cases were observed that progressed into severe degradation of heat removal\n149\tperformance and significant rise in heated plate temperatures. The most common condition\n150\tobserved was the downdraft of cold ambient air through one of the chimney stacks, an\n151\tunintended behavior that disrupted test operations and required operator intervention to\n152\tmitigate. The impact of this condition on the RCCS resulted in reduced flow rates by an\n153\taverage of 40%, increased gas temperatures by 15%, and a rise in heated surface temperatures\n154\t\n155\tANL-ART-47                                    ii\n156\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n157\tAugust 2016\n158\t\n159\t\n160\tof over 10%. Strategies were implemented in the later portions of the testing program to\n161\tmitigate these disruptions, which initially entailed operator intervention through the use of\n162\tdamper valves, and later the design and installation of program-specific chimney caps. These\n163\tsolutions proved effective during the majority of testing scenarios, however the project team\n164\twas unable to guarantee complete effectiveness during early start-up periods. The coupling\n165\tof low flow velocities, cold ductwork, large flow areas, and multiple parallel paths create a\n166\tsystem that is readily destabilized with even minor flow disruptions.\n167\t   Given the proximity of proposed HTR installations near chemical processing facilities,\n168\tthe project team examined one hypothetical scenario where heavy-gas (high purity argon)\n169\tis drawn into the inlet of an RCCS. Under these conditions, the NSTF exhibited complete\n170\tstagnation of system flow and subsequent failure of heat removal function. The introduction\n171\tof 1,200 cu-feet of a heavy gas, twice the internal volume of the NSTF flow path, induced flow\n172\tstagnation over a period spanning 19-minutes. Furthermore, re-circulation patterns occurred\n173\twithin the twelve riser channels, a first-of-a-kind observation for the testing program. While\n174\tthe mechanism of recovery is not fully understood and would require further studies, the\n175\tobserved response by the NSTF expanded the list of deficiencies for an air-based RCCS\n176\tconcept.\n177\t   The data generated for the air-based portion of the NSTF project at Argonne was pro-\n178\tduced within a controlled, traceable, and NQA-1 compliant program. The project has di-\n179\trectly supported the DOE mission for developing reliable and safe reactor technologies, and\n180\tthe produced data set is suitable for aiding design choices of future reactor concepts. Ul-\n181\ttimately, the result of the accomplished work is well poised to guide the decision on the\n182\tviability of RCCS concepts for passive decay heat removal in advanced reactors.\n183\t\n184\t\n185\t\n186\t\n187\t                                                iii                               ANL-ART-47\n188\t\fThis page was intentionally left blank.\n189\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n190\tAugust 2016\n191\t\n192\t\n193\t\n194\tContents\n195\t\n196\tExecutive Summary                                                                                           i\n197\t\n198\tForeword                                                                                                    1\n199\t\n200\t1 Introduction                                                                                              3"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"47d9ec1e-27f2-4086-90f4-79a8199340a9","uuid":"b0bf3bec-a6f4-455e-bab6-4cd4948ef2d7","timestamp":"2026-07-02T09:33:00.174Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/root/curator/source/report_full_text.txt","content":"                                       ANL-ART-47\n\n\n\n\nFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the\nAir-based Natural convection Shutdown heat\nremoval Test Facility (NSTF)\n\n\n\n\nNuclear Engineering Division\n\fAbout Argonne National Laboratory\nArgonne is a U.S. Department of Energy laboratory managed by UChicago Argonne, LLC\nunder contract DE-AC02-06CH11357. The Laboratory’s main facility is outside Chicago, at\n9700 South Cass Avenue, Argonne, Illinois 60439. For information about Argonne\nand its pioneering science and technology programs, see www.anl.gov.\n\n\n\n\nDOCUMENT AVAILABILITY\n   Online Access: U.S. Department of Energy (DOE) reports produced after 1991 and a\n   growing number of pre-1991 documents are available free via DOE’s SciTech Connect\n   (http://www.osti.gov/scitech/)\n\nReports not in digital format may be purchased by the public from the\nNational Technical Information Service (NTIS):\n  U.S. Department of Commerce National\n  Technical Information Service 5301\n  Shawnee Rd\n  Alexandria, VA 22312\n  www.ntis.gov\n  Phone: (800) 553-NTIS (6847) or (703) 605-6000\n  Fax: (703) 605-6900\n  Email: orders@ntis.gov\n\nReports not in digital format are available to DOE and DOE contractors from the\nOffice of Scientific and Technical Information (OSTI):\n  U.S. Department of Energy\n  Office of Scientific and Technical Information\n  P.O. Box 62\n  Oak Ridge, TN 37831-0062\n  www.osti.gov\n  Phone: (865) 576-8401\n  Fax: (865) 576-5728\n  Email: reports@osti.gov\n\n\n\n\nDisclaimer\nThis report was prepared as an account of work sponsored by an agency of the United States Government. Neither the United States\nGovernment nor any agency thereof, nor UChicago Argonne, LLC, nor any of their employees or officers, makes any warranty, express or\nimplied, or assumes any legal liability or responsibility for the accuracy, completeness, or usefulness of any information, apparatus,\nproduct, or process disclosed, or represents that its use would not infringe privately owned rights. Reference herein to any specific\ncommercial product, process, or service by trade name, trademark, manufacturer, or otherwise, does not necessarily constitute or imply its\nendorsement, recommendation, or favoring by the United States Government or any agency thereof. The views and opinions of document\nauthors expressed herein do not necessarily state or reflect those of the United States Government or any agency thereof, Argonne\nNational Laboratory, or UChicago Argonne, LLC.\n\f                                                                                     ANL-ART-47\n\n\n\n\nFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-\nbased NSTF\n\n\n\n\nprepared by:\nDarius D. Lisowski, Craig D. Gerardi, Dennis J. Kilsdonk, Nathan C. Bremer, Stephen W. Lomperski,\nRui Hu, Adam R. Kraus, Matthew D. Bucknor, Qiuping Lv, Taeseung Lee, and Mitchell. T. Farmer\n\n\n\nNuclear Engineering Division, Argonne National Laboratory\n\n\n\n\nAugust 2016\n\fThis page was intentionally left blank.\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n\nExecutive Summary\nThe following report serves as a comprehensive summary of the air-based portion of the Nat-\nural convection Shutdown heat removal Test Facility (NSTF) program at Argonne National\nLaboratory (Argonne). Initiated in 2005 to generate validation data for the Next Genera-\ntion Nuclear Plant (NGNP), the project was centered on an experimental testing program to\nstudy the behavior and bound the performance of Reactor Cavity Cooling System (RCCS)\nconcepts. Parallel modeling and simulation efforts also have been performed to guide the\ndesign, fabrication, and operation of NSTF, as well as to assess the suitability of analysis\nmethods for natural convection systems. The program operates under support from the De-\npartment of Energy (DOE) Office of Advanced Reactor Technologies (ART), and maintained\ncompliance with NQA-1 2008 with 2009a in both administrative and technical portions of\nprogram activities.\n\n   The test facility constructed at Argonne stands nearly 26-m in total height and has\nbeen designed to represent a 1/2 scale model of the primary features of the General Atomic\n(GA) RCCS design for their Modular High Temperature Gas cooled Reactor (MHTGR).\nThe heated surface of the NSTF was constructed from prototypic, reactor-grade material\nand driven by a heat source originating from a forty-zone array of electric heaters. Sup-\nplying up to 220 kW of electric power, the array was able to accurately mimic the walls\nof a Reactor Pressure Vessel (RPV) through profile shaping to achieve axial or azimuthal\nskews. An integrated suite of data acquisition and high-resolution sensors have guided ex-\nperimental practices and allowed the direct measurement of both system thermal hydraulic\nbehavior and local phenomena. Measurement such as flow rates, gas and wall temperatures,\nand differential pressure by calibrated instrumentation ensured confidence in determining\nheat removal capacity and accurately observing system behavior. A weather station has\ncharacterized the ambient and meteorological boundary conditions that have shown to be\n\n                                                i                               ANL-ART-47\n\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                      August 2016\n\n\ndominant factors in influencing the sensitive natural circulation phenomena. Additionally,\nhigh fidelity sensors including hot-wire probes and distributed temperature sensing fibers\nhave introduced an unparalleled data density and insight into local flow and heat transfer\nmodes.\n\n   The testing program, spanning a 33-month period from September 2013 until July 2016,\ncompleted over 2,250 hours of active test operations and 16 successful test runs. Studies of\nscaling, power shaping, flow path configuration, design basis accident conditions, weather in-\nfluences, and off-normal scenarios were performed and compared against routinely repeated\nbaseline test cases. Special considerations were made to include full-scale features and op-\nerating conditions, such as adjacent chimney roles, cosine power shaping, and the full time\nhistory of one Safety Related Design Condition (SRDC-II). The effects of weather and re-\npeatability were assessed through regular testing of a baseline test case, scheduling select\noperations to occur during inclement weather, and isothermal testing for facility characteri-\nzation purposes.\n\n   Final observations from the project have indicated that a high level of performance can be\nobtained from the air-RCCS concept design if the as-intended path of the natural circulation\nflow can be maintained. Disruptions of blocked riser channels (50% flow area tested), chimney\nshort-circuit scenarios, strong asymmetries from the heated source, and moderate shifts\nin weather conditions were found to have negligible impacts on the overall heat removal\nperformance. Measured temperature excursions by the RPV surface, an indicator of peak\nfuel temperatures, did not rise above 5% of normal values across the conditions tested.\n\n   However, cases were observed that progressed into severe degradation of heat removal\nperformance and significant rise in heated plate temperatures. The most common condition\nobserved was the downdraft of cold ambient air through one of the chimney stacks, an\nunintended behavior that disrupted test operations and required operator intervention to\nmitigate. The impact of this condition on the RCCS resulted in reduced flow rates by an\naverage of 40%, increased gas temperatures by 15%, and a rise in heated surface temperatures\n\nANL-ART-47                                    ii\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\nof over 10%. Strategies were implemented in the later portions of the testing program to\nmitigate these disruptions, which initially entailed operator intervention through the use of\ndamper valves, and later the design and installation of program-specific chimney caps. These\nsolutions proved effective during the majority of testing scenarios, however the project team\nwas unable to guarantee complete effectiveness during early start-up periods. The coupling\nof low flow velocities, cold ductwork, large flow areas, and multiple parallel paths create a\nsystem that is readily destabilized with even minor flow disruptions.\n   Given the proximity of proposed HTR installations near chemical processing facilities,\nthe project team examined one hypothetical scenario where heavy-gas (high purity argon)\nis drawn into the inlet of an RCCS. Under these conditions, the NSTF exhibited complete\nstagnation of system flow and subsequent failure of heat removal function. The introduction\nof 1,200 cu-feet of a heavy gas, twice the internal volume of the NSTF flow path, induced flow\nstagnation over a period spanning 19-minutes. Furthermore, re-circulation patterns occurred\nwithin the twelve riser channels, a first-of-a-kind observation for the testing program. While\nthe mechanism of recovery is not fully understood and would require further studies, the\nobserved response by the NSTF expanded the list of deficiencies for an air-based RCCS\nconcept.\n   The data generated for the air-based portion of the NSTF project at Argonne was pro-\nduced within a controlled, traceable, and NQA-1 compliant program. The project has di-\nrectly supported the DOE mission for developing reliable and safe reactor technologies, and\nthe produced data set is suitable for aiding design choices of future reactor concepts. Ul-\ntimately, the result of the accomplished work is well poised to guide the decision on the\nviability of RCCS concepts for passive decay heat removal in advanced reactors.\n\n\n\n\n                                                iii                               ANL-ART-47\n\fThis page was intentionally left blank.\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\nContents\n\nExecutive Summary                                                                                           i\n\nForeword                                                                                                    1\n\n1 Introduction                                                                                              3","numLines":200,"startLine":1,"totalLines":8102}}}
