{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_016XAmNrD48b6Q7TCDCSyxP8","type":"tool_result","content":"640\t\n641\tChapter 1\n642\t\n643\tIntroduction\n644\tUnder support of the Department of Energy (DOE) Office of Advanced Reactor Technologies\n645\t(ART), a program was established1 at Argonne National Laboratory (Argonne) to develop\n646\ttechnologies to improve the reliability and safety of new reactor designs. Of the solutions\n647\tunder consideration for passive decay heat removal, the Reactor Cavity Cooling System\n648\t(RCCS) stands as a leading concept. To examine the feasibility of this solution, an experi-\n649\tmental test assembly, the Natural convection Shutdown heat removal Test Facility (NSTF),\n650\twas constructed at Argonne and is the focal point of the content presented in this report.\n651\t   The RCCS concept aims to provide a means of achieving passive decay heat removal and\n652\tsafe reactor shutdown during accident scenarios, with recent designs tailored to the latest\n653\tgeneration of High Temperature Reactors (HTR). The design is appealing given its relatively\n654\tsimplicity, reliance on natural forces, and potential for high levels of performance. However,\n655\tthe inclusion of an RCCS in the safety portfolio of future reactor installations is contingent\n656\ton its ability to guarantee the following requirements [1]:\n657\t\n658\t  1. Maintain the vessel wall at safe limits during normal operation and accident conditions,\n659\t     which in turn must ultimately ensure safe peak core fuel temperatures (i.e. retain a\n660\t     solid form) across all design basis scenarios.\n661\t\n662\t  2. Maintain the reactor cavity concrete and support structures at safe limits during nor-\n663\t     mal operation and accident conditions to prevent concrete materials degradation and\n664\t     possible failure.\n665\t\n666\t  3. Sustain intended function and performance across the 40-year life span of a reactor\n667\t     installation.\n668\t\n669\t  4. Accomplish the above functions without human intervention, active systems (e.g. AC\n670\t     or DC power), at all foreseeable reactor construction sites, domestically and abroad.\n671\t\n672\t   1\n673\t       Office of Advanced Reactor Concepts under contract number DE-AC02-06CH11357\n674\t\n675\t\n676\t                                                  3                                  ANL-ART-47\n677\t\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n678\t                                                                                      August 2016\n679\t\n680\t\n681\t   The top-level objective of the program at Argonne was to obtain experimental data which\n682\tcould be utilized to support licensing of safety features in advanced reactor designs. The\n683\tvalidation data obtained by this program has been collected in compliance with the 2008 /\n684\t2009a Nuclear Quality Assurance (NQA)-1 plan and contains the necessary documentation,\n685\ttraceability, and quality standards to support these licensing purposes. The overarching\n686\tdesign of the NSTF centered on a philosophy of flexibility which facilitated multiple operating\n687\tconditions to best-reflect full scale concepts, along with ease in accommodating alternative\n688\ttest section designs. Ultimately, the project has provided benchmark data for validation\n689\tand verification of safety related codes, and through multi-parameter studies, will aid in the\n690\toptimization of the design concept for passively safe decay heat removal.\n691\t   Construction of the test section was completed in September 2013, after which the fo-\n692\tcus was shifted to facility shakedown and checkout activities which extended through the\n693\tremaining calendar year. Since the start of data collection in early 2014, the NSTF has seen\n694\tover 2,250 hours of active operation over the course of thirty-five scheduled runs. As of July\n695\t1st 2016, experiment based testing with the air-based NSTF has concluded and facility oper-\n696\tations have transitioned to disassembly and long term storage of air-based components. The\n697\tproject has completed the requirements of the air-based testing program including original\n698\tobjectives and those action items identified during the data review meeting held on January\n699\t26th 2016 with participation from the DOE, NRC, INL, AREVA, GA, and US Universities.\n700\t   A review of the test facility and data acquisition will be provided in brief, followed by a\n701\tdescription of the experimental method and procedures used for test operations. The primary\n702\tfocus will then be on the results obtained from the full set of air-based test operations,\n703\tfollowed by a discussion on the feasibility of a full scale RCCS installation.\n704\t\n705\t\n706\t\n707\t\n708\tANL-ART-47                                     4\n709\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n710\tAugust 2016\n711\t\n712\t\n713\t\n714\t1.1      Management of NQA-1 Requirements\n715\tThe Quality Assurance Program Plan (QAPP) is based on the requirements set forth in the\n716\tAmerican Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME) NQA-1-2008 (with 1a 2009 addenda)\n717\tQuality Assurance (QA) requirements for nuclear facility applications [2]. It is consistent\n718\twith QA plans adopted by Argonne [3][4] and the Argonne Nuclear Engineering (NE) di-\n719\tvision [5], and the QAPP for the Next Generation Nuclear Plant Project (NGNP) at the\n720\tIdaho National Laboratory (INL) including INL PLN-2690 [6] and 10 CFR Part 50, App.\n721\tB [7].\n722\t   In accordance with this program, a graded QA approach is desirable and the requirements\n723\tof ASME NQA-1-2008 (with 1a 2009 addenda), Subpart 4.2 [8] may be used as guidance for\n724\tResearch and Development activities. Under this graded approach, current NGNP Research\n725\tand Development (RD) work at the INL is classified as Applied Research. With this general\n726\tbackground and in accordance with the Argonne QAPP , this task is assigned a QA level\n727\tC with a level of detail consistent with the graded approach. The RD activities of this\n728\texperimental program under the control of this QAPP are designed to provide reliable,\n729\treproducible, and timely data on the effects of the reactor cavity cooling system on the heat\n730\tremoval from the reactor vessel wall.\n731\t   All controlled documents within the QAPP are uniquely identified in the following for-\n732\tmat: ANL-NSTF-0000000-CCCCC-XXX(-RYY)(-AZZ), where CCCCC is a maximum five\n733\tcharacter string representing the particular document category, XXX is a three digit num-\n734\tber that uniquely identifies each document, RYY identifies the revision number, and when\n735\trequired, AZZ refers to the addenda documents. A tabulated list of the program’s con-\n736\ttrol records is provided in the Appendx. To maintain compliance with NQA-1, the NSTF\n737\tprogram has regular reviews including external audits, formal internal audits, and informal\n738\tmanagement assessments (MA). An overview of all the audits performed is provided below\n739\tin Table 1.\n740\t\n741\t\n742\t\n743\t                                                5                                ANL-ART-47\n744\t\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n745\t                                                                                      August 2016\n746\t\n747\t         Table 1: Summary of audits performed of the NSTF program at Argonne\n748\t\n749\t Date                   Audit Type       Lead Auditor            Summary\n750\t Mar. 18-20, 2014       External         Kirk Bailey (INL)  Instruction provided to\n751\t                                                            support future compliance,\n752\t                                                            27 recommendations and 4\n753\t                                                            weaknesses\n754\t Feb. 16-18, 2015       M.A.             Roberta Riel (ANL) Verified observations from\n755\t                                                            Bailey audit were effectively\n756\t                                                            implemented\n757\t Jul. 20-23, 2015       Internal         Roberta Riel (ANL) Six observations\n758\t Nov. 3-5, 2015         External         Alan Trost (INL)   Compliance established, 6\n759\t                                                            recommendations\n760\t Jan. 21, 2016          M.A.             Roberta Riel (ANL) Verified recommendations\n761\t                                                            from Trost audit were\n762\t                                                            effectively implemented\n763\t Jun. 29-30, 2016       Internal         Roberta Riel (ANL) One observation\n764\t\n765\t\n766\t\n767\t\n768\t1.2     Legacy NSTF\n769\tOriginally built to study air-side performance of the General Electric (GE) Power Reactor\n770\tInnovative Small Module (PRISM) Reactor Vessel Auxiliary Cooling System (RVACS), the\n771\tfirst NSTF program at Argonne successfully provided experimental data during the later\n772\tportion of the 1980’s [9]. This NSTF was established to examine the performance of an ex-\n773\tvessel, natural circulation driven, decay heat removal system, a purpose closely aligned to the\n774\tcurrent work scope. The last (on-record) test was performed in November of 1988, after which\n775\tthe facility sat idle until 2010. The facility was then revisited as part of the current NSTF\n776\twork scope, aiding the current team through past experience and lessons learned. Some\n777\tdesign choices were re-used, e.g. heated plate thermocouple mounting method, however the\n778\tmajority of the facility was re-designed to better reflect the newer concept for the NGNP. Of\n779\tthe physical components from the original experimental facility, only the heater plates were\n780\tsalvaged while all other component were replaced or re-designed to accommodate advances\n781\tin data acquisition and measurement technology.\n782\t\n783\tANL-ART-47                                    6\n784\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n785\tAugust 2016\n786\t\n787\t\n788\t\n789\t\n790\t                     Figure 1: Original NSTF dimensions and design [9]\n791\t\n792\t\n793\t\n794\t                                                7                        ANL-ART-47\n795\t\f                             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n796\t                                                                               August 2016\n797\t\n798\t\n799\t\n800\t\n801\t             Figure 2: Original NSTF test section cross-section [9]\n802\t\n803\t\n804\t\n805\tANL-ART-47                             8\n806\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n807\tAugust 2016\n808\t\n809\t\n810\t\n811\t1.3      Design Basis\n812\tThe General Atomics (GA) Modular High Temperature Gas cooled Reactor (MHTGR) was\n813\tchosen as the full scale basis for the NSTF. Developed in the United States, this gas-cooled\n814\treactor uses helium as the primary coolant with prismatic fuel elements in a hexagonal core.\n815\tGA proposed a four-unit plant with two steam turbine generators, and a net power output\n816\tof approximately 560 MWe [10]. This reactor was selected primarily on the basis that the\n817\tdesign follows similar characteristics to the more recent NGNP, but moreover the passive\n818\tcooling system received considerable attention and resulted in engineering design details that\n819\tare readily available. Features of the standard MHTGR can be found in Table 2, a graphical\n820\tillustration of a single module and steam generator in Figure 3, and a sketch of the RCCS\n821\tpiping network within the reactor building in Figure 4.\n822\t\n823\t                      Table 2: Features of standard GA-MHTGR [10]\n824\t        Fuel UCO + ThO2               Power per module 140 MWt / 87.5 MWe\n825\t   Moderator Graphite                 Fuel temperature 1,060◦ C (max), 677◦ C (avg)\n826\t     Coolant Helium                 Coolant temperature 259◦ C (in), 687◦ C (out)\n827\t\n828\t\n829\t   Of key interest in the GA-MHTGR design is the Reactor Cavity Cooling System (RCCS),\n830\twhich serves as a fully passive decay heat removal system. Natural convection drives air from\n831\tthe atmosphere, which flows through a series of standpipes that line the concrete containment\n832\tto remove heat from the reactor pressure vessel (RPV) through radiation (primarily) and\n833\tconvection. The design consists of an array of 227 tubes, 2.5 cm wide by 25 cm deep that\n834\tline the concrete containment [10]. A redundant series of concentric chimney ducts allows\n835\tair to be both drawn in and exhausted to the atmosphere, which join via manifolds to\n836\tform plenums near the inlet and outlet of the riser tubes. The supply air rises up through\n837\tthese risers, which surround the exterior of the vessel, and remove heat by a combination\n838\tof convection and radiation before rejecting the heat to the outside environment, Figure 4.\n839\tThis system is attractive since it is completely passive and can remove decay heat indefinitely\n840\twhile maintaining acceptable system temperatures.\n841\t\n842\t                                                9                                  ANL-ART-47\n843\t\f                             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n844\t                                                                               August 2016\n845\t\n846\t\n847\t\n848\t\n849\t             Figure 3: GA-MHTGR concept, single module shown [10]\n850\t\n851\t\n852\t\n853\t\n854\tANL-ART-47                             10\n855\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n856\tAugust 2016\n857\t\n858\t\n859\t\n860\t\n861\t     Figure 4: Sketch of GA-MHTGR reactor building. RCCS highlighted in red [10]\n862\t\n863\t\n864\t                                               11                         ANL-ART-47\n865\t\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n866\t                                                                                      August 2016\n867\t\n868\t\n869\t\n870\t1.4     Scaling\n871\tA scaling evaluation of an air-cooled RCCS system was performed based on openly available\n872\tliterature on the RCCS design for the GA-MHTGR. A top-down scaling approach was used\n873\tfor the non-dimensional conservation equations describing the response of RCCS during\n874\tsteady-state and transient operations. These equations were developed into scaling laws to\n875\tminimize distortions between scaled experiments and prototype operation, Table 3. The\n876\tprimary criterion to the air-cooled RCCS scaling was selecting the cold inlet to the hot riser\n877\tduct as the reference location and that the cold atmosphere air is at the same condition for\n878\tall scales and experiments, thus preserving the temperature rise across the heated section,\n879\t∆TR = 1.0. An overview of primary scaling similarity ratios is provided in Table 3, with a\n880\tfull analytical derivation and accompanying analysis detailed in previous works ?? [11].\n881\t\n882\t\n883\t                     Table 3: Scaling similarity parameters and ratios\n884\t   Parameter                   Scaling Ratio   Similarity Parameter     Values for lR = 0.5\n885\t   Material thickness               δR                   1                       1\n886\t   Area                            AR                    1                       1\n887\t                                                        √\n888\t   Air velocity                    UR                    lR                    0.707\n889\t                                                        √\n890\t   Time ratio                      TR ∗                  lR                    0.707\n891\t   Heated temperature rise         ∆TR                   1                       1\n892\t   Reference temperature           TR                    1                       1\n893\t                                      00\n894\t   Heat flux                       qR                  lR −0.5                 1.414\n895\t                                                        √\n896\t   Integral power                  Q̇R                     lR                  0.707\n897\t                                                           0.4\n898\t   Heat transfer coefficient        hR                  lR                     0.758\n899\t                                                        √\n900\t   Reynolds number                 ReR                     lR                  0.707\n901\t   Richardson number               RiR                    1                      1\n902\t   Stanton number                  StR                  lR 0.9                 0.536\n903\t   Biot number                     BiR                  lR 0.4                 0.758\n904\t\n905\t\n906\t\n907\t\n908\tANL-ART-47                                     12\n909\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n910\tAugust 2016\n911\t\n912\t\n913\t1.4.1     Top-down Scaling\n914\t\n915\tThe top-down scaling approach preserves integral behavior for mass and energy balances,\n916\thowever does not capture local behavior such as 3-dimensional mixing phenomena within\n917\tthe plenum. Furthermore, it does include behavior involving multiple riser ducts and parallel\n918\tchannel interactions. Natural circulation flow patterns, especially at low flow rates and small\n919\tdensity differences (e.g. air driven systems), exhibit complex behavior and are difficult to\n920\tpredict with confidence. However, the discharge of hot jets from the riser ducts can be scaled\n921\tbased on a maximum ceiling height Xm for jet penetration. Turner [12] conducted experi-\n922\tments on a negative buoyant jet for an axisymmetric case, and is a considerable simplification\n923\tover the behavior in an RCCS, which sees an initially positive buoyant jet that eventually\n924\treaches neutral or even negative buoyancy. Based on Turners work, the jet penetration\n925\tdepth, DjR is proportional to the jet Froude number, F rjR , Eqn. 1.\n926\t\n927\t\n928\t                                           Xm\n929\t                                              ∝ Fj 0.5                                     (1)\n930\t                                           Dj\n931\t\n932\t   Using the notation of integral scaling parameters, this can be re-written as Eqn. 2.\n933\t\n934\t\n935\t                                        XmR = DjR 0.5 lR 0.5                               (2)\n936\t\n937\t   For the 1/2 scale test facility at Argonne, where DjR = 1 and lR = 0.5, this yields\n938\tXmR = 0.707. Thus, the elevation of the scaled model hot outlet plenum, or the distance\n939\tbetween the exit of the riser ducts and the ceiling of the exit plenum, was built to the scale\n940\tof 0.707 of the full scale prototype.\n941\t\n942\t\n943\t\n944\t\n945\t                                                13                                 ANL-ART-47\n946\t\f                                           Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n947\t                                                                                             August 2016\n948\t\n949\t\n950\t1.4.2     Scaling Summary\n951\t\n952\tAs built, the NSTF reflects the primary design features of the full scale GA-MHTGR RCCS.\n953\tThe facility features twelve riser ducts at 1/2 axial scale (lR ). Based on the full design basis\n954\tof 227 total riser ducts, the resulting configuration reflects a 19.03◦ sector slice (]). A\n955\tsummary of the geometric and thermal hydraulic scaling parameters as applied to the model\n956\tNSTF in comparison to the full scale GA-MHTGR prototype is provided in Tables 4 and 5,\n957\trespectively.\n958\t\n959\t\n960\t\n961\t    Table 4: Geometric scaling comparison between full GA-MHTGR and model NSTF\n962\t                Parameter               GA RCCS            ANL 1/2 scale     Scaling Ratio\n963\t                  Height Scaling              1:1                2:1               lR\n964\t            Total RCCS Height               55.2 m             26 m                lR\n965\t                   Heated Riser            13.86 m            6.82 m              √lR\n966\t          Outlet Plenum Ceiling             1.83 m            1.47 m                lR\n967\t                    Heated Area            311.2 m2           8.82 m2             ], lR\n968\t              Riser Duct Count               x227               x12                ]\n969\t\n970\t\n971\t  Table 5: Scaling of heat removal specifications for full GA-MHTGR and model NSTF\n972\t      Parameter          Scaling Ratio              Scenario       GA RCCS         ANL 1/2 scale\n973\t                                  √              Peak, accident      1.5 MWt          56.07 kWt\n974\t         Decay Power         ],    lR\n975\t                                                    Normal           700 kWt          26.16 kWt\n976\t\n977\t                                                 Peak, accident 4.82 kW/m2           6.82 kW/m2\n978\t            Heat Flux         lR −0.5\n979\t                                                    Normal      2.25 kW/m2           3.18 kW/m2\n980\t\n981\t                                                 Peak, accident         121◦ C            121◦ C\n982\t          Heated ∆T               1\n983\t                                                    Normal               67◦ C             67◦ C\n984\t\n985\t                                  √              Peak, accident      12.2 kg/s        0.456 kg/s\n986\t   System Flow Rate          ],       lR\n987\t                                                    Normal           10.6 kg/s        0.396 kg/s\n988\t\n989\t\n990\t\n991\t\n992\tANL-ART-47                                            14\n993\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n994\tAugust 2016\n995\t\n996\t\n997\t\n998\t1.5      Testing Program\n999\tAcross a 33-month testing period, performance metrics were assessed by varying parameters\n1000\tof integral power, power profile, chimney configurations, discharge elevations, and inclement\n1001\tweather. Off-normal testing was performed to establish a performance envelope during\n1002\tscenarios of blocked riser channels, chimney by-pass leakages, and non-air gas ingress. Lastly,\n1003\tspecial considerations were made to include full-scale features and operating conditions, such\n1004\tas adjacent chimney roles, cosine power shaping, and the full time history of one Safety\n1005\tRelated Design Condition (SRDC-II).\n1006\t   Each test averaged 82 hours in duration, and testing was performed year-round to capture\n1007\ta wide range of ambient weather conditions. Across the full series, the project examined\n1008\tsystem behavior with ambient outdoor temperatures as low as -18.1◦ C and as high as 32.1◦ C.\n1009\tA total of 2,250 hours of active test operations were conducted and resulted in 16 accepted\n1010\ttest cases. However, not all test cases were successful in meeting the target objectives; out of\n1011\tthe 27 total performed, 11 were unable to meet the full stated objectives. These cases were\n1012\tclassified as either “trending” if usable data could still be preserved, or “failed” if the test\n1013\tas a whole was unable to add any meaningful data to the test records. Failure mechanisms\n1014\tincluded hardware faults, weather induced instabilities, or energy balance deficiencies.\n1015\t   A summary of all the test cases completed by the project conclusion is provided for those\n1016\taccepted in Table 6, and those failed or trending in Table 7.\n1017\t\n1018\t\n1019\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"47d9ec1e-27f2-4086-90f4-79a8199340a9","uuid":"d0207eea-a463-42e6-86a9-b9c8c011fe8c","timestamp":"2026-07-02T09:33:27.011Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/root/curator/source/report_full_text.txt","content":"\nChapter 1\n\nIntroduction\nUnder support of the Department of Energy (DOE) Office of Advanced Reactor Technologies\n(ART), a program was established1 at Argonne National Laboratory (Argonne) to develop\ntechnologies to improve the reliability and safety of new reactor designs. Of the solutions\nunder consideration for passive decay heat removal, the Reactor Cavity Cooling System\n(RCCS) stands as a leading concept. To examine the feasibility of this solution, an experi-\nmental test assembly, the Natural convection Shutdown heat removal Test Facility (NSTF),\nwas constructed at Argonne and is the focal point of the content presented in this report.\n   The RCCS concept aims to provide a means of achieving passive decay heat removal and\nsafe reactor shutdown during accident scenarios, with recent designs tailored to the latest\ngeneration of High Temperature Reactors (HTR). The design is appealing given its relatively\nsimplicity, reliance on natural forces, and potential for high levels of performance. However,\nthe inclusion of an RCCS in the safety portfolio of future reactor installations is contingent\non its ability to guarantee the following requirements [1]:\n\n  1. Maintain the vessel wall at safe limits during normal operation and accident conditions,\n     which in turn must ultimately ensure safe peak core fuel temperatures (i.e. retain a\n     solid form) across all design basis scenarios.\n\n  2. Maintain the reactor cavity concrete and support structures at safe limits during nor-\n     mal operation and accident conditions to prevent concrete materials degradation and\n     possible failure.\n\n  3. Sustain intended function and performance across the 40-year life span of a reactor\n     installation.\n\n  4. Accomplish the above functions without human intervention, active systems (e.g. AC\n     or DC power), at all foreseeable reactor construction sites, domestically and abroad.\n\n   1\n       Office of Advanced Reactor Concepts under contract number DE-AC02-06CH11357\n\n\n                                                  3                                  ANL-ART-47\n\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                      August 2016\n\n\n   The top-level objective of the program at Argonne was to obtain experimental data which\ncould be utilized to support licensing of safety features in advanced reactor designs. The\nvalidation data obtained by this program has been collected in compliance with the 2008 /\n2009a Nuclear Quality Assurance (NQA)-1 plan and contains the necessary documentation,\ntraceability, and quality standards to support these licensing purposes. The overarching\ndesign of the NSTF centered on a philosophy of flexibility which facilitated multiple operating\nconditions to best-reflect full scale concepts, along with ease in accommodating alternative\ntest section designs. Ultimately, the project has provided benchmark data for validation\nand verification of safety related codes, and through multi-parameter studies, will aid in the\noptimization of the design concept for passively safe decay heat removal.\n   Construction of the test section was completed in September 2013, after which the fo-\ncus was shifted to facility shakedown and checkout activities which extended through the\nremaining calendar year. Since the start of data collection in early 2014, the NSTF has seen\nover 2,250 hours of active operation over the course of thirty-five scheduled runs. As of July\n1st 2016, experiment based testing with the air-based NSTF has concluded and facility oper-\nations have transitioned to disassembly and long term storage of air-based components. The\nproject has completed the requirements of the air-based testing program including original\nobjectives and those action items identified during the data review meeting held on January\n26th 2016 with participation from the DOE, NRC, INL, AREVA, GA, and US Universities.\n   A review of the test facility and data acquisition will be provided in brief, followed by a\ndescription of the experimental method and procedures used for test operations. The primary\nfocus will then be on the results obtained from the full set of air-based test operations,\nfollowed by a discussion on the feasibility of a full scale RCCS installation.\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47                                     4\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n1.1      Management of NQA-1 Requirements\nThe Quality Assurance Program Plan (QAPP) is based on the requirements set forth in the\nAmerican Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME) NQA-1-2008 (with 1a 2009 addenda)\nQuality Assurance (QA) requirements for nuclear facility applications [2]. It is consistent\nwith QA plans adopted by Argonne [3][4] and the Argonne Nuclear Engineering (NE) di-\nvision [5], and the QAPP for the Next Generation Nuclear Plant Project (NGNP) at the\nIdaho National Laboratory (INL) including INL PLN-2690 [6] and 10 CFR Part 50, App.\nB [7].\n   In accordance with this program, a graded QA approach is desirable and the requirements\nof ASME NQA-1-2008 (with 1a 2009 addenda), Subpart 4.2 [8] may be used as guidance for\nResearch and Development activities. Under this graded approach, current NGNP Research\nand Development (RD) work at the INL is classified as Applied Research. With this general\nbackground and in accordance with the Argonne QAPP , this task is assigned a QA level\nC with a level of detail consistent with the graded approach. The RD activities of this\nexperimental program under the control of this QAPP are designed to provide reliable,\nreproducible, and timely data on the effects of the reactor cavity cooling system on the heat\nremoval from the reactor vessel wall.\n   All controlled documents within the QAPP are uniquely identified in the following for-\nmat: ANL-NSTF-0000000-CCCCC-XXX(-RYY)(-AZZ), where CCCCC is a maximum five\ncharacter string representing the particular document category, XXX is a three digit num-\nber that uniquely identifies each document, RYY identifies the revision number, and when\nrequired, AZZ refers to the addenda documents. A tabulated list of the program’s con-\ntrol records is provided in the Appendx. To maintain compliance with NQA-1, the NSTF\nprogram has regular reviews including external audits, formal internal audits, and informal\nmanagement assessments (MA). An overview of all the audits performed is provided below\nin Table 1.\n\n\n\n                                                5                                ANL-ART-47\n\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                      August 2016\n\n         Table 1: Summary of audits performed of the NSTF program at Argonne\n\n Date                   Audit Type       Lead Auditor            Summary\n Mar. 18-20, 2014       External         Kirk Bailey (INL)  Instruction provided to\n                                                            support future compliance,\n                                                            27 recommendations and 4\n                                                            weaknesses\n Feb. 16-18, 2015       M.A.             Roberta Riel (ANL) Verified observations from\n                                                            Bailey audit were effectively\n                                                            implemented\n Jul. 20-23, 2015       Internal         Roberta Riel (ANL) Six observations\n Nov. 3-5, 2015         External         Alan Trost (INL)   Compliance established, 6\n                                                            recommendations\n Jan. 21, 2016          M.A.             Roberta Riel (ANL) Verified recommendations\n                                                            from Trost audit were\n                                                            effectively implemented\n Jun. 29-30, 2016       Internal         Roberta Riel (ANL) One observation\n\n\n\n\n1.2     Legacy NSTF\nOriginally built to study air-side performance of the General Electric (GE) Power Reactor\nInnovative Small Module (PRISM) Reactor Vessel Auxiliary Cooling System (RVACS), the\nfirst NSTF program at Argonne successfully provided experimental data during the later\nportion of the 1980’s [9]. This NSTF was established to examine the performance of an ex-\nvessel, natural circulation driven, decay heat removal system, a purpose closely aligned to the\ncurrent work scope. The last (on-record) test was performed in November of 1988, after which\nthe facility sat idle until 2010. The facility was then revisited as part of the current NSTF\nwork scope, aiding the current team through past experience and lessons learned. Some\ndesign choices were re-used, e.g. heated plate thermocouple mounting method, however the\nmajority of the facility was re-designed to better reflect the newer concept for the NGNP. Of\nthe physical components from the original experimental facility, only the heater plates were\nsalvaged while all other component were replaced or re-designed to accommodate advances\nin data acquisition and measurement technology.\n\nANL-ART-47                                    6\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n\n                     Figure 1: Original NSTF dimensions and design [9]\n\n\n\n                                                7                        ANL-ART-47\n\f                             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                               August 2016\n\n\n\n\n             Figure 2: Original NSTF test section cross-section [9]\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47                             8\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n1.3      Design Basis\nThe General Atomics (GA) Modular High Temperature Gas cooled Reactor (MHTGR) was\nchosen as the full scale basis for the NSTF. Developed in the United States, this gas-cooled\nreactor uses helium as the primary coolant with prismatic fuel elements in a hexagonal core.\nGA proposed a four-unit plant with two steam turbine generators, and a net power output\nof approximately 560 MWe [10]. This reactor was selected primarily on the basis that the\ndesign follows similar characteristics to the more recent NGNP, but moreover the passive\ncooling system received considerable attention and resulted in engineering design details that\nare readily available. Features of the standard MHTGR can be found in Table 2, a graphical\nillustration of a single module and steam generator in Figure 3, and a sketch of the RCCS\npiping network within the reactor building in Figure 4.\n\n                      Table 2: Features of standard GA-MHTGR [10]\n        Fuel UCO + ThO2               Power per module 140 MWt / 87.5 MWe\n   Moderator Graphite                 Fuel temperature 1,060◦ C (max), 677◦ C (avg)\n     Coolant Helium                 Coolant temperature 259◦ C (in), 687◦ C (out)\n\n\n   Of key interest in the GA-MHTGR design is the Reactor Cavity Cooling System (RCCS),\nwhich serves as a fully passive decay heat removal system. Natural convection drives air from\nthe atmosphere, which flows through a series of standpipes that line the concrete containment\nto remove heat from the reactor pressure vessel (RPV) through radiation (primarily) and\nconvection. The design consists of an array of 227 tubes, 2.5 cm wide by 25 cm deep that\nline the concrete containment [10]. A redundant series of concentric chimney ducts allows\nair to be both drawn in and exhausted to the atmosphere, which join via manifolds to\nform plenums near the inlet and outlet of the riser tubes. The supply air rises up through\nthese risers, which surround the exterior of the vessel, and remove heat by a combination\nof convection and radiation before rejecting the heat to the outside environment, Figure 4.\nThis system is attractive since it is completely passive and can remove decay heat indefinitely\nwhile maintaining acceptable system temperatures.\n\n                                                9                                  ANL-ART-47\n\f                             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                               August 2016\n\n\n\n\n             Figure 3: GA-MHTGR concept, single module shown [10]\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47                             10\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n\n     Figure 4: Sketch of GA-MHTGR reactor building. RCCS highlighted in red [10]\n\n\n                                               11                         ANL-ART-47\n\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                      August 2016\n\n\n\n1.4     Scaling\nA scaling evaluation of an air-cooled RCCS system was performed based on openly available\nliterature on the RCCS design for the GA-MHTGR. A top-down scaling approach was used\nfor the non-dimensional conservation equations describing the response of RCCS during\nsteady-state and transient operations. These equations were developed into scaling laws to\nminimize distortions between scaled experiments and prototype operation, Table 3. The\nprimary criterion to the air-cooled RCCS scaling was selecting the cold inlet to the hot riser\nduct as the reference location and that the cold atmosphere air is at the same condition for\nall scales and experiments, thus preserving the temperature rise across the heated section,\n∆TR = 1.0. An overview of primary scaling similarity ratios is provided in Table 3, with a\nfull analytical derivation and accompanying analysis detailed in previous works ?? [11].\n\n\n                     Table 3: Scaling similarity parameters and ratios\n   Parameter                   Scaling Ratio   Similarity Parameter     Values for lR = 0.5\n   Material thickness               δR                   1                       1\n   Area                            AR                    1                       1\n                                                        √\n   Air velocity                    UR                    lR                    0.707\n                                                        √\n   Time ratio                      TR ∗                  lR                    0.707\n   Heated temperature rise         ∆TR                   1                       1\n   Reference temperature           TR                    1                       1\n                                      00\n   Heat flux                       qR                  lR −0.5                 1.414\n                                                        √\n   Integral power                  Q̇R                     lR                  0.707\n                                                           0.4\n   Heat transfer coefficient        hR                  lR                     0.758\n                                                        √\n   Reynolds number                 ReR                     lR                  0.707\n   Richardson number               RiR                    1                      1\n   Stanton number                  StR                  lR 0.9                 0.536\n   Biot number                     BiR                  lR 0.4                 0.758\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47                                     12\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n1.4.1     Top-down Scaling\n\nThe top-down scaling approach preserves integral behavior for mass and energy balances,\nhowever does not capture local behavior such as 3-dimensional mixing phenomena within\nthe plenum. Furthermore, it does include behavior involving multiple riser ducts and parallel\nchannel interactions. Natural circulation flow patterns, especially at low flow rates and small\ndensity differences (e.g. air driven systems), exhibit complex behavior and are difficult to\npredict with confidence. However, the discharge of hot jets from the riser ducts can be scaled\nbased on a maximum ceiling height Xm for jet penetration. Turner [12] conducted experi-\nments on a negative buoyant jet for an axisymmetric case, and is a considerable simplification\nover the behavior in an RCCS, which sees an initially positive buoyant jet that eventually\nreaches neutral or even negative buoyancy. Based on Turners work, the jet penetration\ndepth, DjR is proportional to the jet Froude number, F rjR , Eqn. 1.\n\n\n                                           Xm\n                                              ∝ Fj 0.5                                     (1)\n                                           Dj\n\n   Using the notation of integral scaling parameters, this can be re-written as Eqn. 2.\n\n\n                                        XmR = DjR 0.5 lR 0.5                               (2)\n\n   For the 1/2 scale test facility at Argonne, where DjR = 1 and lR = 0.5, this yields\nXmR = 0.707. Thus, the elevation of the scaled model hot outlet plenum, or the distance\nbetween the exit of the riser ducts and the ceiling of the exit plenum, was built to the scale\nof 0.707 of the full scale prototype.\n\n\n\n\n                                                13                                 ANL-ART-47\n\f                                           Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                             August 2016\n\n\n1.4.2     Scaling Summary\n\nAs built, the NSTF reflects the primary design features of the full scale GA-MHTGR RCCS.\nThe facility features twelve riser ducts at 1/2 axial scale (lR ). Based on the full design basis\nof 227 total riser ducts, the resulting configuration reflects a 19.03◦ sector slice (]). A\nsummary of the geometric and thermal hydraulic scaling parameters as applied to the model\nNSTF in comparison to the full scale GA-MHTGR prototype is provided in Tables 4 and 5,\nrespectively.\n\n\n\n    Table 4: Geometric scaling comparison between full GA-MHTGR and model NSTF\n                Parameter               GA RCCS            ANL 1/2 scale     Scaling Ratio\n                  Height Scaling              1:1                2:1               lR\n            Total RCCS Height               55.2 m             26 m                lR\n                   Heated Riser            13.86 m            6.82 m              √lR\n          Outlet Plenum Ceiling             1.83 m            1.47 m                lR\n                    Heated Area            311.2 m2           8.82 m2             ], lR\n              Riser Duct Count               x227               x12                ]\n\n\n  Table 5: Scaling of heat removal specifications for full GA-MHTGR and model NSTF\n      Parameter          Scaling Ratio              Scenario       GA RCCS         ANL 1/2 scale\n                                  √              Peak, accident      1.5 MWt          56.07 kWt\n         Decay Power         ],    lR\n                                                    Normal           700 kWt          26.16 kWt\n\n                                                 Peak, accident 4.82 kW/m2           6.82 kW/m2\n            Heat Flux         lR −0.5\n                                                    Normal      2.25 kW/m2           3.18 kW/m2\n\n                                                 Peak, accident         121◦ C            121◦ C\n          Heated ∆T               1\n                                                    Normal               67◦ C             67◦ C\n\n                                  √              Peak, accident      12.2 kg/s        0.456 kg/s\n   System Flow Rate          ],       lR\n                                                    Normal           10.6 kg/s        0.396 kg/s\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47                                            14\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n1.5      Testing Program\nAcross a 33-month testing period, performance metrics were assessed by varying parameters\nof integral power, power profile, chimney configurations, discharge elevations, and inclement\nweather. Off-normal testing was performed to establish a performance envelope during\nscenarios of blocked riser channels, chimney by-pass leakages, and non-air gas ingress. Lastly,\nspecial considerations were made to include full-scale features and operating conditions, such\nas adjacent chimney roles, cosine power shaping, and the full time history of one Safety\nRelated Design Condition (SRDC-II).\n   Each test averaged 82 hours in duration, and testing was performed year-round to capture\na wide range of ambient weather conditions. Across the full series, the project examined\nsystem behavior with ambient outdoor temperatures as low as -18.1◦ C and as high as 32.1◦ C.\nA total of 2,250 hours of active test operations were conducted and resulted in 16 accepted\ntest cases. However, not all test cases were successful in meeting the target objectives; out of\nthe 27 total performed, 11 were unable to meet the full stated objectives. These cases were\nclassified as either “trending” if usable data could still be preserved, or “failed” if the test\nas a whole was unable to add any meaningful data to the test records. Failure mechanisms\nincluded hardware faults, weather induced instabilities, or energy balance deficiencies.\n   A summary of all the test cases completed by the project conclusion is provided for those\naccepted in Table 6, and those failed or trending in Table 7.\n\n\n","numLines":380,"startLine":640,"totalLines":8102}}}
