{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01VYqpQ3CjLMrsjpdnt3CvCc","type":"tool_result","content":"1293\tChapter 3\n1294\t\n1295\tTest Assembly Description\n1296\tThe following sections detail the engineering specifications, design features, and dimensions\n1297\tof the test facility at Argonne. Details of structural and mechanical systems will be presented\n1298\tfirst, followed by ducting components, heated cavity, and finally a stand alone section on the\n1299\tvarious insulating materials used. Relevant engineering drawings have been included after\n1300\teach section in their original format.\n1301\t\n1302\t\n1303\t3.1      Base Support and Cavity Framework\n1304\tThe structural base assembly that supports the primary test assembly components was\n1305\tmanufactured from W12x65 I-beam sections and weighs approximately 30,000 lbs. Base\n1306\tsupports, six in total, extend to the concrete floor and are secured by four 1.25” bolts. The\n1307\ttotal height of the assembly is 6’ tall, Figure 5.\n1308\t   Resting on top of the base support is a U-channel framework that serves as the structural\n1309\tsupport for the heavy steel assemblies that make up the heated cavity, Figure 6. Built in\n1310\ttwo sections; each is constructed of ASTM A36 channels, four MC12x45 and two MC6x18,\n1311\tthat join onto 1” steel plates to makeup the skeletal framework.\n1312\t\n1313\t\n1314\t\n1315\t\n1316\t                                               25                                  ANL-ART-47\n1317\t\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1318\t                                                               August 2016\n1319\t                                                            Figure 6: Lower skeleton framework\n1320\t                                                            Figure 5: Base support\n1321\tANL-ART-47             26\n1322\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1323\tAugust 2016\n1324\t\n1325\t\n1326\t\n1327\t3.2      Flow Path Ducting\n1328\t\n1329\t3.2.1        Inlet Downcomer\n1330\t\n1331\tThe air supply to the NSTF enters through an inlet downcomer, an uninsulated 24” diameter\n1332\tduct that provides a means to stabilize and measure the incoming flow, Figure 7. The inlet\n1333\tdowncomer begins with a vertical straight length, 90◦ elbow, and finally horizontal straight,\n1334\twhich combined span an equivalent length (distance along centerline of ducting segments)\n1335\tof 184.5”.\n1336\t\n1337\t\n1338\t\n1339\t\n1340\t             Figure 7: Inlet downcomer (front view) and equivalent segment lengths\n1341\t\n1342\t\n1343\t\n1344\t   We have positioned a Sierra flow conditioner, Figures 8 - 9, which sits at the top edge of\n1345\tthe duct and extends 24” deep as a means to establish a fully developed inlet flow profile.\n1346\tAlong with the entrance and exit lengths, these design choices are driven by an experimental\n1347\trequirement to accurately measure the inlet flow conditions.\n1348\t\n1349\t\n1350\t\n1351\t\n1352\t                                               27                                ANL-ART-47\n1353\t\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1354\t                                                               August 2016\n1355\t                                                 Figure 9: Geometric dimensions (plan view)\n1356\t                                                                                              Figure 8: Flow conditioner\n1357\tANL-ART-47             28\n1358\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1359\tAugust 2016\n1360\t\n1361\t\n1362\t3.2.2     Inlet Plenum\n1363\t\n1364\tThe inlet plenum is a large volume that provides an essentially zero pressure boundary\n1365\tcondition for the incoming air from the downcomer to distribute among the twelve riser\n1366\tchannels, Figure 10. The assembly is constructed from 1/8” thick aluminum alloy 3003. The\n1367\ttotal available volume of the inlet plenum is 78 ft3 (2.21 m3 ). A divider plate reduces the\n1368\tavailable area for air flow to 41.7 ft3 (1.18 m3 ). The unused back cavity is insulated and\n1369\tavailable for access should maintenance be required.\n1370\t   The configuration of the inlet plenum mates the downcomer ducting to the center of the\n1371\twest plenum wall. There are also two additional potential inlet ports, one each on the North\n1372\tand South walls of the inlet plenum. These are blanked off in the current configuration. The\n1373\tcenterline of each of the three inlet ports measures 16” from the bottom, and all are centered\n1374\talong their respective widths (33” for the north and south ports, 52” for the primary west\n1375\tport).\n1376\t   To facilitate instrument placement for measurement of the inlet flow conditions into\n1377\ttwelve riser tubes, the ducts extend 7” below the ceiling of the inlet plenum. The inlet\n1378\tplenum ceiling contains twelve slots for this purpose, and the slotted joint is sealed against\n1379\tair leakage by a Kevlar wrap. The purpose of this slotted design is to allow unconstrained\n1380\tmovement due to thermal expansion, as a fixed support would induce significant stress onto\n1381\tthe steel riser ducts. During steady-state experimental operating temperatures the riser\n1382\tducts will expand upwards approximately 1-cm.\n1383\t\n1384\t\n1385\t\n1386\t\n1387\t                                               29                                 ANL-ART-47\n1388\t\fANL-ART-47\n1389\t\n1390\t\n1391\t\n1392\t\n1393\t                                                                                                                                                   Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1394\t30\n1395\t\n1396\t\n1397\t\n1398\t\n1399\t                                                                                                                                                                                                     August 2016\n1400\t             Figure 10: Inlet plenum. Duct stub shown connects to inlet downcomer, rectangular slotted holes connect to riser ducts. Interior\n1401\t             volume measures 44” tall, 51.75 width (parallel to riser slots), and 59.75” deep, of which only 31.75” is available for the working\n1402\t             gas due to the present of the false back wall.\n1403\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1404\tAugust 2016\n1405\t\n1406\t\n1407\t3.2.3     Riser Ducts\n1408\t\n1409\tThe NSTF houses twelve riser ducts as the primary flow area test section, and are constructed\n1410\tfrom welded structural rectangular steel tubing, ASTM A 500 Grade B. The cross-section\n1411\tdimensions are duplicate of the full scale GA-MHTGR design, and measure 10”x2”x0.188”,\n1412\tat an approximate weight of 385 lbs / riser, Figure 11. The length of each duct measures\n1413\t295”; however, only 272” resides within the heated cavity due to the 7” extension below into\n1414\tthe inlet plenum and 16” above into the outlet plenum.\n1415\t   The combined weight of the twelve tubes totals 4,620 lbs and required creative mounting\n1416\tmethods to omit the need for rigging the full assembly. Each riser tube features a 3/8” plate\n1417\tthat has been welded 16” below the top lip as a means to support the individual tubes.\n1418\tThe installation process required hoisting above the outlet plenum, and dropping each duct\n1419\tthrough a slotted support plate into the heated cavity. The plate, manufactured from 1”\n1420\tthick ASTM A 36 steel and weighing approximately 1,820 lbs, bears the full load of the ducts\n1421\tand is secured to the support structure, Figure 12.\n1422\t\n1423\t\n1424\t\n1425\t\n1426\t                                               31                                ANL-ART-47\n1427\t\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1428\t                                                               August 2016\n1429\t                                                             Figure 11: Cross section of riser ducts (dimensional drawing above, picture below)\n1430\tANL-ART-47             32\n1431\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1432\tAugust 2016\n1433\t                                                                  Figure 12: Top plate which bears the weight of the twelve riser ducts\n1434\t                                               33              ANL-ART-47\n1435\t\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1436\t                                                                                      August 2016\n1437\t\n1438\t\n1439\t3.2.4     Outlet Plenum\n1440\t\n1441\tUpon exiting the riser individual riser ducts, heated gases combine in the upper plenum and\n1442\texhaust into the dual symmetric chimneys, Figure 13. The riser tubes protrude 16” past the\n1443\tfloor of the outlet, allowing access to the instrumentation ports. Additionally, this extended\n1444\tlength reduces the effort when installing a false-floor, since the riser tubes can be kept in\n1445\ttheir position without reconfiguration.\n1446\t\n1447\t\n1448\t\n1449\t\n1450\tFigure 13: View into the outlet plenum from opened east wall. False west wall visible behind\n1451\triser tubes\n1452\t\n1453\t\n1454\t\n1455\t   The plenum interior measures 74” tall, 87” east/west, and 64” north/south. The plenum\n1456\tfeatures adjustable false-floors and walls as a means to adjust the inside volume. The as-built\n1457\tdesign consists a false wall on the westward side, reducing width (west - east) from 87” to\n1458\t74”. The interior volume measures 203.8-ft3 (5.77-m3 ), which is reduced by the false west\n1459\twall from the total available volume of 240-ft3 (6.79-m3 ). The 24” diameter ports, which\n1460\t\n1461\tANL-ART-47                                    34\n1462\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1463\tAugust 2016\n1464\t\n1465\t\n1466\tserve as the entrance into the chimney ductwork on the north and south facing walls, are\n1467\tpositioned at the plenum centerline (east-west) and elevated 56.5” from the plenum floor,\n1468\tor 40.5” above the top surface of the riser tube end. The centerline of the riser tubes is\n1469\toffset westward by 16.5” from the chimney ports center. With the added 3” of insulation,\n1470\tthe riser ducts exit face extend 13”, and the centerline of the chimney ports 53.5”, above the\n1471\tinsulated floor.\n1472\t   The exterior paneling on the outlet plenum consists of five similarly designed sub-assemblies,\n1473\twhich are constructed in the same fashion as the heated cavity west wall panels: a steel angle\n1474\t(L3x2x1/4”) framework that contains 6” of insulation, and is protected on both inside and\n1475\toutside facing walls by 1/8” thick aluminum sheets. Each panel weighs approximately 800\n1476\tlbs., and has mounting provisions for hoisting and lifting operations. An exploded view of\n1477\tthe north and south panels is shown below in Figure 14, and an east-west cross section of\n1478\tthe entire outlet plenum and paneling in Figure 15.\n1479\t\n1480\t\n1481\t\n1482\t\n1483\t             Figure 14: Exploded view of north/south panels on outlet plenum\n1484\t\n1485\t\n1486\t\n1487\t\n1488\t                                               35                                 ANL-ART-47\n1489\t\fANL-ART-47\n1490\t\n1491\t\n1492\t\n1493\t\n1494\t                                                                                                       Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1495\t36\n1496\t\n1497\t\n1498\t\n1499\t\n1500\t                                                                                                                                                         August 2016\n1501\t             Figure 15: Cross section (east/west) of outlet plenum and surrounding insulation panels\n1502\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1503\tAugust 2016\n1504\t\n1505\t\n1506\t3.2.5     Chimney Stacks\n1507\t\n1508\tThe chimney in the NSTF consists of dual ductwork assemblies that provide the necessary\n1509\tdriving head and chimney effect to transport the heated gases to the outside environment.\n1510\tThe ducts, constructed from 24” diameter, 14 gauge galvanized steel, and are wrapped in 3”\n1511\tof mineral wool followed by a 0.016” protective aluminum jacket. The ductwork model was\n1512\tdesigned to preserve the thermal hydraulic flow patterns observed in full scale simulations\n1513\twhile also catering to the physical requirements of the building space. Thus, the end product\n1514\tis an intricate flow path that includes multiple elbows of varying degrees, vertical, horizontal,\n1515\tand sloped duct runs. A design priority was placed on flexibility in forming alternative\n1516\tnetworks for varying flow path configurations. Included are five butterfly valves (loafers)\n1517\tand two forced fan loft blowers for isothermal testing, Figure 16.\n1518\t\n1519\t\n1520\t\n1521\t\n1522\tFigure 16: Variable component locations on chimney ducting. Five butterfly valves and dual\n1523\tforced blowers\n1524\t\n1525\t\n1526\t\n1527\t\n1528\t                                               37                                   ANL-ART-47\n1529\t\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1530\t                                                                                      August 2016\n1531\t\n1532\t\n1533\t   The five butterfly valves are mounted with electronic actuators, Honeywell MS7520A2205,\n1534\tto allow remote positioning of the valves by an operator. The actuator units receive a 2 - 10\n1535\tvolt DC control signal and proportionally adjust the position of the damper blade within the\n1536\tvalve. They are able to control positions between 0 and 90◦ in 3◦ increments, and require 90\n1537\tseconds to traverse a full rotation. The flow area as a function of actuator position is shown\n1538\tin Figure 17.\n1539\t\n1540\t\n1541\t\n1542\t\n1543\t                Figure 17: Valve position and resulting chimney duct flow area\n1544\t\n1545\t\n1546\t\n1547\t\n1548\tANL-ART-47                                    38\n1549\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1550\tAugust 2016\n1551\t\n1552\t\n1553\tVertical and Horizontal Exhaust Configurations\n1554\t\n1555\tThe standard or baseline configuration for the chimney duct work removes the heated gas\n1556\tvia both north and south segments along the full elevation of the network piping, ultimately\n1557\texiting from the vertical stacks extending through the building’s roof. The alternative config-\n1558\turation, which is used during isothermal benchmarks or at a reduced atmospheric discharge,\n1559\tcloses the vertical stack dampers and vents air through the building’s east wall. Either flow\n1560\tpath runs through a network of segments, comprised of elbows, straight lengths, bellows,\n1561\tdamper valves, and etc..\n1562\t   The equivalent flow paths, as measured from the exit of the outlet plenum, measures\n1563\t826.13” for the vertical and 470.37” for the horizontal configurations. A detailed breakdown\n1564\tof the various network segments for both configurations is provided in Table 8.\n1565\t\n1566\t Table 8: Ducting segment types and equiv. lengths for horizontal and vertical flow paths\n1567\t Seg. #   Radius    Eqv. Run      Seg. Type                Seg. #   Radius Eqv. Run     Seg. Type\n1568\t     1     36” in    56.55”    90◦ elbow                      1      36”    56.55”    90◦ elbow\n1569\t     2      36in      28.27    45◦ elbow                      2       36     28.27    45◦ elbow\n1570\t     3      n/a       22.00    Straight                       3      n/a     22.00    Straight\n1571\t     4       36       28.27    45◦ elbow                      4       36     28.27    45◦ elbow\n1572\t     5      n/a       13.75    Bellows                        5      n/a     13.75    Bellows\n1573\t     6       36       56.55    90◦ elbow                      6       36     56.55    90◦ elbow\n1574\t     7      n/a       13.75    Bellows                        7      n/a     13.75    Bellows\n1575\t     8      n/a       42.00    4-way                          8      n/a     42.00    4-way\n1576\t     9      n/a       40.00    Tee (straight thru.)           9       20     31.42    Tee (side port)\n1577\t    10      n/a       12.00    Valve                         10      n/a     12.00    Valve\n1578\t    11      n/a       13.75    Bellows                       11      n/a     43.00    Straight\n1579\t    12       36       44.61    90◦ elbow                     12      n/a     13.75    Bellows\n1580\t    13      n/a       36.13    Straight                      13      n/a     31.06    Fan blower\n1581\t    14      n/a       13.75    Bellows                       14      n/a     30.00    Straight\n1582\t    15      n/a       36.13    Straight                      15      n/a     48.00    Tapered straight\n1583\t    16       36       44.61    90◦ elbow                                    470.37    inch total\n1584\t    17      n/a      324.00    Straight\n1585\t                     826.13    inch total\n1586\t\n1587\t\n1588\t\n1589\t\n1590\t                                                      39                                  ANL-ART-47\n1591\t\f                                   Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1592\t                                                                                     August 2016\n1593\t\n1594\t\n1595\t3.2.6    Forced Blower Fans\n1596\t\n1597\tTwo fan loft blowers, model 24 AFB-H purchased from Air Products Equipment Co., are\n1598\tpowered by 3-phase 460VAC power and controlled by a variable frequency drive (VFD) up\n1599\tto 1,725 RPM. They are able to withstand temperatures up to 500◦ F, and thus suitable for\n1600\tactive heating operation in the NSTF. The primary purpose of these blowers is to obtain\n1601\tisothermal flow to benchmark and verify the working state of instrumentation. They also\n1602\tprovide a safety mechanism in the event of an overheated temperature condition. A relation\n1603\tto the flow rate and driven frequency of the twin fan loft blowers is provided in Figure 18.\n1604\t\n1605\t\n1606\t\n1607\t\n1608\t                   Figure 18: Flow vs frequency for dual fan loft blowers\n1609\t\n1610\t\n1611\t\n1612\t\n1613\tANL-ART-47                                   40\n1614\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1615\tAugust 2016\n1616\t\n1617\t\n1618\t\n1619\t3.3      Heated cavity\n1620\tThe primary test section of the NSTF is an insulated enclosure that provides a means of heat\n1621\ttransfer from the radiant heater source (simulated reactor vessel) to the twelve riser ducts,\n1622\tand is built around the U-channel structural framework. The other three sides are adiabatic.\n1623\tThis heated enclosure has an overall height of 22-ft (6.7-m), a width of 52” (132-cm)and has\n1624\tan adjustable cavity depth that can range from 17.7” to 59” (45 to 150-cm) in increments of\n1625\t1” (2.5-cm), Figure 19. The spacing between the front facing surfaces of the riser tubes and\n1626\theated plate used for the first round of test operations measures 27.82” (706.55 mm), and\n1627\tthe area for heat transfer off the primary heated plate measures 109.6 ft2 (10.18 m2 ).\n1628\t\n1629\t\n1630\t\n1631\t\n1632\tFigure 19: Plan view of NSTF heated cavity and test section. Heater surface is shown in"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"47d9ec1e-27f2-4086-90f4-79a8199340a9","uuid":"df1be536-cc5f-4123-894e-15cfc62f5f40","timestamp":"2026-07-02T09:33:48.060Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/root/curator/source/report_full_text.txt","content":"Chapter 3\n\nTest Assembly Description\nThe following sections detail the engineering specifications, design features, and dimensions\nof the test facility at Argonne. Details of structural and mechanical systems will be presented\nfirst, followed by ducting components, heated cavity, and finally a stand alone section on the\nvarious insulating materials used. Relevant engineering drawings have been included after\neach section in their original format.\n\n\n3.1      Base Support and Cavity Framework\nThe structural base assembly that supports the primary test assembly components was\nmanufactured from W12x65 I-beam sections and weighs approximately 30,000 lbs. Base\nsupports, six in total, extend to the concrete floor and are secured by four 1.25” bolts. The\ntotal height of the assembly is 6’ tall, Figure 5.\n   Resting on top of the base support is a U-channel framework that serves as the structural\nsupport for the heavy steel assemblies that make up the heated cavity, Figure 6. Built in\ntwo sections; each is constructed of ASTM A36 channels, four MC12x45 and two MC6x18,\nthat join onto 1” steel plates to makeup the skeletal framework.\n\n\n\n\n                                               25                                  ANL-ART-47\n\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                               August 2016\n                                                            Figure 6: Lower skeleton framework\n                                                            Figure 5: Base support\nANL-ART-47             26\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n3.2      Flow Path Ducting\n\n3.2.1        Inlet Downcomer\n\nThe air supply to the NSTF enters through an inlet downcomer, an uninsulated 24” diameter\nduct that provides a means to stabilize and measure the incoming flow, Figure 7. The inlet\ndowncomer begins with a vertical straight length, 90◦ elbow, and finally horizontal straight,\nwhich combined span an equivalent length (distance along centerline of ducting segments)\nof 184.5”.\n\n\n\n\n             Figure 7: Inlet downcomer (front view) and equivalent segment lengths\n\n\n\n   We have positioned a Sierra flow conditioner, Figures 8 - 9, which sits at the top edge of\nthe duct and extends 24” deep as a means to establish a fully developed inlet flow profile.\nAlong with the entrance and exit lengths, these design choices are driven by an experimental\nrequirement to accurately measure the inlet flow conditions.\n\n\n\n\n                                               27                                ANL-ART-47\n\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                               August 2016\n                                                 Figure 9: Geometric dimensions (plan view)\n                                                                                              Figure 8: Flow conditioner\nANL-ART-47             28\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n3.2.2     Inlet Plenum\n\nThe inlet plenum is a large volume that provides an essentially zero pressure boundary\ncondition for the incoming air from the downcomer to distribute among the twelve riser\nchannels, Figure 10. The assembly is constructed from 1/8” thick aluminum alloy 3003. The\ntotal available volume of the inlet plenum is 78 ft3 (2.21 m3 ). A divider plate reduces the\navailable area for air flow to 41.7 ft3 (1.18 m3 ). The unused back cavity is insulated and\navailable for access should maintenance be required.\n   The configuration of the inlet plenum mates the downcomer ducting to the center of the\nwest plenum wall. There are also two additional potential inlet ports, one each on the North\nand South walls of the inlet plenum. These are blanked off in the current configuration. The\ncenterline of each of the three inlet ports measures 16” from the bottom, and all are centered\nalong their respective widths (33” for the north and south ports, 52” for the primary west\nport).\n   To facilitate instrument placement for measurement of the inlet flow conditions into\ntwelve riser tubes, the ducts extend 7” below the ceiling of the inlet plenum. The inlet\nplenum ceiling contains twelve slots for this purpose, and the slotted joint is sealed against\nair leakage by a Kevlar wrap. The purpose of this slotted design is to allow unconstrained\nmovement due to thermal expansion, as a fixed support would induce significant stress onto\nthe steel riser ducts. During steady-state experimental operating temperatures the riser\nducts will expand upwards approximately 1-cm.\n\n\n\n\n                                               29                                 ANL-ART-47\n\fANL-ART-47\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                                                                                   Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n30\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                                                                                                                                     August 2016\n             Figure 10: Inlet plenum. Duct stub shown connects to inlet downcomer, rectangular slotted holes connect to riser ducts. Interior\n             volume measures 44” tall, 51.75 width (parallel to riser slots), and 59.75” deep, of which only 31.75” is available for the working\n             gas due to the present of the false back wall.\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n3.2.3     Riser Ducts\n\nThe NSTF houses twelve riser ducts as the primary flow area test section, and are constructed\nfrom welded structural rectangular steel tubing, ASTM A 500 Grade B. The cross-section\ndimensions are duplicate of the full scale GA-MHTGR design, and measure 10”x2”x0.188”,\nat an approximate weight of 385 lbs / riser, Figure 11. The length of each duct measures\n295”; however, only 272” resides within the heated cavity due to the 7” extension below into\nthe inlet plenum and 16” above into the outlet plenum.\n   The combined weight of the twelve tubes totals 4,620 lbs and required creative mounting\nmethods to omit the need for rigging the full assembly. Each riser tube features a 3/8” plate\nthat has been welded 16” below the top lip as a means to support the individual tubes.\nThe installation process required hoisting above the outlet plenum, and dropping each duct\nthrough a slotted support plate into the heated cavity. The plate, manufactured from 1”\nthick ASTM A 36 steel and weighing approximately 1,820 lbs, bears the full load of the ducts\nand is secured to the support structure, Figure 12.\n\n\n\n\n                                               31                                ANL-ART-47\n\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                               August 2016\n                                                             Figure 11: Cross section of riser ducts (dimensional drawing above, picture below)\nANL-ART-47             32\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n                                                                  Figure 12: Top plate which bears the weight of the twelve riser ducts\n                                               33              ANL-ART-47\n\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                      August 2016\n\n\n3.2.4     Outlet Plenum\n\nUpon exiting the riser individual riser ducts, heated gases combine in the upper plenum and\nexhaust into the dual symmetric chimneys, Figure 13. The riser tubes protrude 16” past the\nfloor of the outlet, allowing access to the instrumentation ports. Additionally, this extended\nlength reduces the effort when installing a false-floor, since the riser tubes can be kept in\ntheir position without reconfiguration.\n\n\n\n\nFigure 13: View into the outlet plenum from opened east wall. False west wall visible behind\nriser tubes\n\n\n\n   The plenum interior measures 74” tall, 87” east/west, and 64” north/south. The plenum\nfeatures adjustable false-floors and walls as a means to adjust the inside volume. The as-built\ndesign consists a false wall on the westward side, reducing width (west - east) from 87” to\n74”. The interior volume measures 203.8-ft3 (5.77-m3 ), which is reduced by the false west\nwall from the total available volume of 240-ft3 (6.79-m3 ). The 24” diameter ports, which\n\nANL-ART-47                                    34\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\nserve as the entrance into the chimney ductwork on the north and south facing walls, are\npositioned at the plenum centerline (east-west) and elevated 56.5” from the plenum floor,\nor 40.5” above the top surface of the riser tube end. The centerline of the riser tubes is\noffset westward by 16.5” from the chimney ports center. With the added 3” of insulation,\nthe riser ducts exit face extend 13”, and the centerline of the chimney ports 53.5”, above the\ninsulated floor.\n   The exterior paneling on the outlet plenum consists of five similarly designed sub-assemblies,\nwhich are constructed in the same fashion as the heated cavity west wall panels: a steel angle\n(L3x2x1/4”) framework that contains 6” of insulation, and is protected on both inside and\noutside facing walls by 1/8” thick aluminum sheets. Each panel weighs approximately 800\nlbs., and has mounting provisions for hoisting and lifting operations. An exploded view of\nthe north and south panels is shown below in Figure 14, and an east-west cross section of\nthe entire outlet plenum and paneling in Figure 15.\n\n\n\n\n             Figure 14: Exploded view of north/south panels on outlet plenum\n\n\n\n\n                                               35                                 ANL-ART-47\n\fANL-ART-47\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                                       Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n36\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                                                                                         August 2016\n             Figure 15: Cross section (east/west) of outlet plenum and surrounding insulation panels\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n3.2.5     Chimney Stacks\n\nThe chimney in the NSTF consists of dual ductwork assemblies that provide the necessary\ndriving head and chimney effect to transport the heated gases to the outside environment.\nThe ducts, constructed from 24” diameter, 14 gauge galvanized steel, and are wrapped in 3”\nof mineral wool followed by a 0.016” protective aluminum jacket. The ductwork model was\ndesigned to preserve the thermal hydraulic flow patterns observed in full scale simulations\nwhile also catering to the physical requirements of the building space. Thus, the end product\nis an intricate flow path that includes multiple elbows of varying degrees, vertical, horizontal,\nand sloped duct runs. A design priority was placed on flexibility in forming alternative\nnetworks for varying flow path configurations. Included are five butterfly valves (loafers)\nand two forced fan loft blowers for isothermal testing, Figure 16.\n\n\n\n\nFigure 16: Variable component locations on chimney ducting. Five butterfly valves and dual\nforced blowers\n\n\n\n\n                                               37                                   ANL-ART-47\n\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                      August 2016\n\n\n   The five butterfly valves are mounted with electronic actuators, Honeywell MS7520A2205,\nto allow remote positioning of the valves by an operator. The actuator units receive a 2 - 10\nvolt DC control signal and proportionally adjust the position of the damper blade within the\nvalve. They are able to control positions between 0 and 90◦ in 3◦ increments, and require 90\nseconds to traverse a full rotation. The flow area as a function of actuator position is shown\nin Figure 17.\n\n\n\n\n                Figure 17: Valve position and resulting chimney duct flow area\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47                                    38\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\nVertical and Horizontal Exhaust Configurations\n\nThe standard or baseline configuration for the chimney duct work removes the heated gas\nvia both north and south segments along the full elevation of the network piping, ultimately\nexiting from the vertical stacks extending through the building’s roof. The alternative config-\nuration, which is used during isothermal benchmarks or at a reduced atmospheric discharge,\ncloses the vertical stack dampers and vents air through the building’s east wall. Either flow\npath runs through a network of segments, comprised of elbows, straight lengths, bellows,\ndamper valves, and etc..\n   The equivalent flow paths, as measured from the exit of the outlet plenum, measures\n826.13” for the vertical and 470.37” for the horizontal configurations. A detailed breakdown\nof the various network segments for both configurations is provided in Table 8.\n\n Table 8: Ducting segment types and equiv. lengths for horizontal and vertical flow paths\n Seg. #   Radius    Eqv. Run      Seg. Type                Seg. #   Radius Eqv. Run     Seg. Type\n     1     36” in    56.55”    90◦ elbow                      1      36”    56.55”    90◦ elbow\n     2      36in      28.27    45◦ elbow                      2       36     28.27    45◦ elbow\n     3      n/a       22.00    Straight                       3      n/a     22.00    Straight\n     4       36       28.27    45◦ elbow                      4       36     28.27    45◦ elbow\n     5      n/a       13.75    Bellows                        5      n/a     13.75    Bellows\n     6       36       56.55    90◦ elbow                      6       36     56.55    90◦ elbow\n     7      n/a       13.75    Bellows                        7      n/a     13.75    Bellows\n     8      n/a       42.00    4-way                          8      n/a     42.00    4-way\n     9      n/a       40.00    Tee (straight thru.)           9       20     31.42    Tee (side port)\n    10      n/a       12.00    Valve                         10      n/a     12.00    Valve\n    11      n/a       13.75    Bellows                       11      n/a     43.00    Straight\n    12       36       44.61    90◦ elbow                     12      n/a     13.75    Bellows\n    13      n/a       36.13    Straight                      13      n/a     31.06    Fan blower\n    14      n/a       13.75    Bellows                       14      n/a     30.00    Straight\n    15      n/a       36.13    Straight                      15      n/a     48.00    Tapered straight\n    16       36       44.61    90◦ elbow                                    470.37    inch total\n    17      n/a      324.00    Straight\n                     826.13    inch total\n\n\n\n\n                                                      39                                  ANL-ART-47\n\f                                   Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                     August 2016\n\n\n3.2.6    Forced Blower Fans\n\nTwo fan loft blowers, model 24 AFB-H purchased from Air Products Equipment Co., are\npowered by 3-phase 460VAC power and controlled by a variable frequency drive (VFD) up\nto 1,725 RPM. They are able to withstand temperatures up to 500◦ F, and thus suitable for\nactive heating operation in the NSTF. The primary purpose of these blowers is to obtain\nisothermal flow to benchmark and verify the working state of instrumentation. They also\nprovide a safety mechanism in the event of an overheated temperature condition. A relation\nto the flow rate and driven frequency of the twin fan loft blowers is provided in Figure 18.\n\n\n\n\n                   Figure 18: Flow vs frequency for dual fan loft blowers\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47                                   40\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n3.3      Heated cavity\nThe primary test section of the NSTF is an insulated enclosure that provides a means of heat\ntransfer from the radiant heater source (simulated reactor vessel) to the twelve riser ducts,\nand is built around the U-channel structural framework. The other three sides are adiabatic.\nThis heated enclosure has an overall height of 22-ft (6.7-m), a width of 52” (132-cm)and has\nan adjustable cavity depth that can range from 17.7” to 59” (45 to 150-cm) in increments of\n1” (2.5-cm), Figure 19. The spacing between the front facing surfaces of the riser tubes and\nheated plate used for the first round of test operations measures 27.82” (706.55 mm), and\nthe area for heat transfer off the primary heated plate measures 109.6 ft2 (10.18 m2 ).\n\n\n\n\nFigure 19: Plan view of NSTF heated cavity and test section. Heater surface is shown in","numLines":340,"startLine":1293,"totalLines":8102}}}
