{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011j53QE7os8DnJ3tSz6LL4B","type":"tool_result","content":"1632\tFigure 19: Plan view of NSTF heated cavity and test section. Heater surface is shown in\n1633\tred, riser ducts in blue. Hatched perimeter denotes insulated areas\n1634\t\n1635\t\n1636\t\n1637\t\n1638\t                                               41                                ANL-ART-47\n1639\t\f                                       Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1640\t                                                                                         August 2016\n1641\t\n1642\t\n1643\t3.3.1     Unheated Paneling\n1644\t\n1645\tThe insulated panels on the north and south walls are placed on hinges that facilitate removal\n1646\tand access without needing to perform a major disassembly. Twenty-four panel assemblies\n1647\tare required to cover the full area of the north and south walls. Each panel measures\n1648\t67”x21”, and is constructed from 6” of insulation (facing inward), and protected by 16 gauge\n1649\taluminum alloy #3000, on the outward surface. The hook and groove mounting channels\n1650\tsecure to 1/2”-13 steel spacing studs placed across the width of each U-channel, and when\n1651\tfully installed allow for complete enclosure and isolation of the heated interior from the\n1652\tambient surroundings.\n1653\t   The four panels on the west wall are constructed from a steel angle (L3x2x1/4”) frame-\n1654\twork that contains 6” of insulation, and is protected on both inside and outside facing walls\n1655\tby 1/8” aluminum. Each panel weighs approximately 267 lbs., and has mounting provisions\n1656\tfor hoisting and lifting operations.\n1657\t\n1658\t3.3.2     Heated Wall\n1659\t\n1660\tThe heated east wall comprises a nine-layer composite to provide the necessary structurally\n1661\tsupport for the massive steel plate, provide an efficient means for heat transfer, and also\n1662\tinsulate the system from parasitic heat losses. These nine layers were constructed and\n1663\tinstalled as three separate sub-assemblies: two vertical primary plates, four rows of heater\n1664\tsub-panels, and four rows of outside insulation panels. An air gap separates the 1st and 2nd ,\n1665\tand a thin buffer layer of insulation separate the 2nd and 3rd .\n1666\t\n1667\t\n1668\t\n1669\t\n1670\tANL-ART-47                                       42\n1671\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1672\tAugust 2016\n1673\t\n1674\t\n1675\t3.3.3     Primary Heated Plate\n1676\t\n1677\tTo accurately represent the heat flux condition off the walls of a prototypic RPV, the primary\n1678\theat source in the NSTF (electrically powered radiant heaters, detailed in later sections) are\n1679\tplaced behind a 1” steel plate as a means to smooth any sharp temperature gradients from\n1680\tthe hot coils while also providing the necessary emissivity for radiation heat transfer to\n1681\tthe riser tubes. Figure 20 shows the lower plate in preparation for installation, including\n1682\ttemporary eye bolts needed to hoist the 2,230 lb plate onto the structural framework.\n1683\t   This plate is fabricated from SAE 1020 low carbon steel which has stated ladle composi-\n1684\ttion limits given as 0.18% - 0.23% C, 0.30% - 0.60% Mn, 0.040% Pmax , 0.50% Smax , and Fe\n1685\tbeing the remaining constituent. The surface condition of the back plate is mill scale oxidized\n1686\tso that its emissivity was initially in the 0.7 to 0.9 range. This emissivity was measured prior\n1687\tto test operations and was found to average 0.78 - 0.79 [14] The same plates were used from\n1688\tthe early PRISM/RVACS work, a project at ANL which investigated a similar concept for\n1689\tpassive decay heat removal. Early reports have mentioned that the researchers hand selected\n1690\tthese plates based on uniformity and surface condition which had a thin surface scale that\n1691\twas an electrically nonconducting oxide with a dull dark-purple coloration. Furthermore,\n1692\tthey add that surface deformation by grinding for welding and thermocouple spot welding\n1693\twas kept at a minimum.\n1694\t   The primary heated plate has enlarged mounting holes to allow for thermal expansion\n1695\tin all directions. The plate is hung to structural support structure, separated by 2” spacers\n1696\tand insulation, so that the heater plate subassembly is allowed to expand horizontally and\n1697\tvertically. Figure 21 shows dimensions and mounting points for the lower plate.\n1698\t\n1699\t\n1700\t\n1701\t\n1702\t                                               43                                  ANL-ART-47\n1703\t\fANL-ART-47\n1704\t\n1705\t\n1706\t\n1707\t\n1708\t                                                                                                                                            Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1709\t44\n1710\t\n1711\t\n1712\t\n1713\t\n1714\t                                                                                                                                                                                              August 2016\n1715\t             Figure 20: Lower heated plate prior to installation. Eye hooks were temporarily installed for lifting, thermocouples visible\n1716\t\f                                                                                                          Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1717\t\n1718\t\n1719\t\n1720\t\n1721\t                                                                                                          August 2016\n1722\t45\n1723\t\n1724\t\n1725\t\n1726\t\n1727\t             Figure 21: Dimensions and mounting hole specifications of primary heated plate (top shown)\n1728\t\n1729\t\n1730\tANL-ART-47\n1731\t\f                                     Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1732\t                                                                                       August 2016\n1733\t\n1734\t\n1735\t3.3.4     Heater Subpanels\n1736\t\n1737\tThe heater sub-panels, ten in total, serve as the primary area for power control, heat transfer,\n1738\tand insulation for the 220 ceramic heater plates. The mounting system, Figure 23, positions\n1739\tthe radiant coils of the heaters away from the test section as a means to provide uniformity\n1740\tin the heat flux across the plate. This setup also minimized the risk of electrically shorting\n1741\tout the heater coils against any neighboring conductive materials.\n1742\t   The stainless steel sheets were sandblasted and then heat treated to 1900◦ F to relieve\n1743\tinternal and surface stresses. The sandblasting process was performed to enhance the surface\n1744\temissivity of the sheets from about 0.25 to about 0.90 uniformly over both sides of the sheets,\n1745\tsignificantly improving heat transfer and temperature uniformity, and thereby reducing the\n1746\tchance of warping the stainless steel sheet. The ceramic heaters (detailed in the following\n1747\tsection) are fastened to the steel sheet with 10-32 size studs that are welded to the steel\n1748\tsheets. Each heater subassembly contains twenty ceramic plate electric heater elements (6-\n1749\tin x 12-in). The 16 central heater elements are one heater zone, and the four edge heater\n1750\telements compose the second heater zone on the 2-ft x 5-ft heater plate subassembly.\n1751\t\n1752\t\n1753\t\n1754\t\n1755\t                     Figure 22: Heated wall, heater subpanel assembly\n1756\t\n1757\t\n1758\t\n1759\t\n1760\tANL-ART-47                                     46\n1761\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1762\tAugust 2016\n1763\t                                                                  Figure 23: AutoCAD drawing of heater subpanel with ceramic heaters outlined\n1764\t                                               47              ANL-ART-47\n1765\t\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1766\t                                                                                      August 2016\n1767\t\n1768\t\n1769\t3.3.5     Ceramic Heaters\n1770\t\n1771\tThe heat source within the NSTF comprises an array of radiant heaters powered by 480\n1772\tand 240 VAC. 200 individual ceramic heaters, each measuring 6”x12”x0.5”, are capable of\n1773\tsupplying up to 1,100 W each, totaling a maximum available power of 220 kWe . These 200\n1774\tindividual plates are grouped into 40 control zones, 20 designated as the “main” and 20 as\n1775\tthe “guard” zones. Each “main” consists of 8 ceramic heater plates, while each “guard”\n1776\tconsists of two ceramic heater plates, Figure 24. The parallel series connections of each\n1777\tMain and Guard result in 120 VAC across any individual heater element.\n1778\t   These 40 control zones produce a power distribution that provides 80% of the total from\n1779\tthe Main and the remaining 20% from the Guard zones. For the purposes of test operations,\n1780\tpower is primarily supplied to the Main zones while the Guards are adjusted to maintain a\n1781\tuniform temperature distribution across the heated plate, minimizing thermal gradients and\n1782\treducing stresses.\n1783\t\n1784\t3.3.6     Heated Wall Insulation Panels\n1785\t\n1786\tThe outside insulation panels on the heated wall, installed in four vertical rows, are con-\n1787\tstructed from framed assembly that is similar to the opposing cold wall insulation panels. A\n1788\tsheet metal framework houses two stacks of of 3” insulation (6” in total), and is protected on\n1789\tthe exterior surface by 1/8” aluminum sheet metal panel. Each panel weighs approximately\n1790\t270 lbs., and has mounting provisions for hoisting and lifting operations.\n1791\t\n1792\t\n1793\t\n1794\t\n1795\tANL-ART-47                                    48\n1796\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1797\tAugust 2016\n1798\t                                                                   Figure 24: Electrical detail of Main and Guard heating zones\n1799\t                                               49              ANL-ART-47\n1800\t\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1801\t                                                                                      August 2016\n1802\t\n1803\t\n1804\t\n1805\t3.4     Insulation\n1806\tIn an effort to reduce heat losses to the ambient surroundings, the NSTF is heavily insulated\n1807\tin primary control areas at or after the heat source. Non-insulated areas include the inlet\n1808\tdowncomer, inlet plenum, and horizontal chimney ducts. SuperIsol® was used on all test\n1809\tsection insulated panels and walls. Duraboard LD® was used as the backing for the ceramic\n1810\theaters. Enerywrap 80® was used for the chimney ductwork. Durablanket S® was used as\n1811\tfiller and patchwork in smaller areas throughout. Thermal specifications and properties of\n1812\tthe insulation materials used are provided in Table 9.\n1813\t\n1814\t             Table 9: Material and thermal specifications for NSTF insulation\n1815\t\n1816\t        Name          Thickness     Max Temp        Density     Thermal Conductivity\n1817\t                                                                 (BTU-in/hr-ft2 -◦ F)\n1818\t   Super Isol®             3”         1,800 ◦ F      16 pcf     400 ◦ F 750 ◦ F 1100 ◦ F\n1819\t                                                                 0.416   0.554    0.693\n1820\t   Duraboard LD®           2”         2,300 ◦ F      16 pcf     400 ◦ F 1000 ◦ F 1600 ◦ F\n1821\t                                                                  0.55   0.847    1.339\n1822\t   Durablanket S®          1”         2,150 ◦ F       8 pcf     600 F 1000 F 1600 ◦ F\n1823\t                                                                     ◦        ◦\n1824\t\n1825\t                                                                  0.56   0.977    2.003\n1826\t   Enerywrap 80®           3”         1,200 ◦ F       8 pcf     200 F 400 F 600 ◦ F\n1827\t                                                                     ◦       ◦\n1828\t\n1829\t                                                                  0.30    0.42     0.59\n1830\t\n1831\t\n1832\t\n1833\t   Figure 25 shows a north facing cross section of the heated cavity, which identifies the\n1834\tvarious types of insulation and thicknesses used to retain thermal energy within the enclosure.\n1835\tThe north and south walls (not shown) are of similar construction to the west wall, and\n1836\tultimately include the same 6” thickness of Duraboard LD® insulation. The east (heated)\n1837\twall comprises a matrix of different materials, which was necessary to ensure compliance\n1838\twith the elevated temperatures found nearest the ceramic heaters. Insulation on the 24”\n1839\tductwork is included for all duct length with the exception of the inlet piping and horizontal\n1840\tfan loft forced blower segments. Nominally 24” inner diameter, a layer of 3” thick mineral\n1841\twool insulation surrounds the bare ducts, which is covered by a 0.016” aluminum jacket.\n1842\t\n1843\t\n1844\tANL-ART-47                                    50\n1845\t\f                                                                                                                               Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1846\t\n1847\t\n1848\t\n1849\t\n1850\t                                                                                                                               August 2016\n1851\t51\n1852\t\n1853\t\n1854\t\n1855\t\n1856\tANL-ART-47\n1857\t             Figure 25: Cross section of heated cavity outlining areas of insulation. Viewed from a north facing perspective\n1858\t\f                                   Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1859\t                                                                                     August 2016\n1860\t\n1861\t\n1862\t\n1863\t3.5     Operating Flexibility\n1864\tThe initial design philosophy of the NSTF has resulted in a high level of flexibility in the\n1865\tavailable configurations for testing. Since a final design for an air-based RCCS has not\n1866\tyet been constructed on a full scale, nor has an exact design been decided upon by US\n1867\tvendors, this flexibility has allowed the project to maintain relevance as the RCCS design\n1868\tand technology matures. Furthermore, it has allowed the project to create a diverse range\n1869\tof testing conditions. In addition to the normal boundary conditions of power and spatial\n1870\tprofiling of the heater surface, other areas for reconfiguration include the floor and wall\n1871\tspacing of the outlet plenum, heated plate to riser setback depth, chimney flow routing,\n1872\tamong others.\n1873\t   Arrays of valves allow for an experiment operator to introduce alternative flow path\n1874\trouting. Across the testing performed, the NSTF saw four primary configurations: baseline,\n1875\treduced discharge, single chimney, and adjacent chimney roles. A summary of the compo-\n1876\tnents or features that can be adjusted to alter the configuration are summarized below in\n1877\tTable 10, along with a diagram depicting the possible chimney flow paths in Figure 26.\n1878\t\n1879\t                 Table 10: Summary of adjustable features on the NSTF\n1880\t\n1881\t        Component                                 Ranges            Baseline Value\n1882\t        Heater Power                         0 - 220 kW e                78 kW e\n1883\t        Heater Profile                Arbitrary across 40 zones           Linear\n1884\t        Flow operation                     Natural, forced               Natural\n1885\t        Forced flow                           0 - 1 kg/s                    n/a\n1886\t        Riser - heater spacing               0.45 - 1.5 m                0.71 m\n1887\t        Riser flow area                    0.078 - 0.155 m               0.155 m\n1888\t        Outlet plenum floor spacing           0 - 0.41 m                  0.41 m\n1889\t        Outlet plenum depth                  1.88 - 2.2 m                 1.88 m\n1890\t        Chimney discharge height             7.7 - 19.6 m                19.6 m\n1891\t        Chimney flow area                    0 - 0.58 m2                 0.58 m2\n1892\t\n1893\t\n1894\t\n1895\t\n1896\tANL-ART-47                                   52\n1897\t\f                                                                                                                                               Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1898\t\n1899\t\n1900\t\n1901\t\n1902\t                                                                                                                                               August 2016\n1903\t53\n1904\t\n1905\t\n1906\t\n1907\t\n1908\tANL-ART-47\n1909\t             Figure 26: Facility configurations of chimney ductwork, arrow denotes air inlet. Blue (left): baseline, dual vertical, Red\n1910\t             (left,center): reduced chimney discharge, Orange (right-center): single chimney vertical, Purple (right): adjacent inlet/outlet\n1911\t\f                                     Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1912\t                                                                                       August 2016\n1913\t\n1914\t\n1915\t\n1916\t3.6      As-built Summary\n1917\tDescribed in sections above, the NSTF is a highly flexible experimental apparatus that can be\n1918\tre-configured to different testing states with minimal or reduced effort. The areas that have\n1919\tbeen designed specifically for reconfiguration include the heated wall to riser tube horizontal\n1920\tspacing, the extension of the riser ducts into the outlet plenum, and the presence of false\n1921\twalls on both the inlet and outlet plenum. These four areas are the primary variables that\n1922\twill be reconfigured in future test operations, but in their present state define the ‘as-built’\n1923\tconfiguration of the NSTF, Figure 27.\n1924\t\n1925\t\n1926\t\n1927\t\n1928\t   Figure 27: Primary areas of flexibility, dimensions shown for ‘as-built’ configuration\n1929\t\n1930\t\n1931\tANL-ART-47                                     54\n1932\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1933\tAugust 2016\n1934\t\n1935\t\n1936\t\n1937\t\n1938\tChapter 4\n1939\t\n1940\tTest Assembly Sensors & Control\n1941\t\n1942\tThe NSTF features a sophisticated suite of data acquisition and instrumentation for test\n1943\toperations in a dedicated control room, Figure 28. The data acquisition boards are placed\n1944\tat four points alongside the test section and routed to the central control station.\n1945\t\n1946\t\n1947\t\n1948\t\n1949\t              Figure 28: Plan view of Building 308 and NSTF test operations\n1950\t\n1951\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"47d9ec1e-27f2-4086-90f4-79a8199340a9","uuid":"bf905a93-de25-4fd2-9ff4-474e5964b102","timestamp":"2026-07-02T09:33:52.065Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/root/curator/source/report_full_text.txt","content":"Figure 19: Plan view of NSTF heated cavity and test section. Heater surface is shown in\nred, riser ducts in blue. Hatched perimeter denotes insulated areas\n\n\n\n\n                                               41                                ANL-ART-47\n\f                                       Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                         August 2016\n\n\n3.3.1     Unheated Paneling\n\nThe insulated panels on the north and south walls are placed on hinges that facilitate removal\nand access without needing to perform a major disassembly. Twenty-four panel assemblies\nare required to cover the full area of the north and south walls. Each panel measures\n67”x21”, and is constructed from 6” of insulation (facing inward), and protected by 16 gauge\naluminum alloy #3000, on the outward surface. The hook and groove mounting channels\nsecure to 1/2”-13 steel spacing studs placed across the width of each U-channel, and when\nfully installed allow for complete enclosure and isolation of the heated interior from the\nambient surroundings.\n   The four panels on the west wall are constructed from a steel angle (L3x2x1/4”) frame-\nwork that contains 6” of insulation, and is protected on both inside and outside facing walls\nby 1/8” aluminum. Each panel weighs approximately 267 lbs., and has mounting provisions\nfor hoisting and lifting operations.\n\n3.3.2     Heated Wall\n\nThe heated east wall comprises a nine-layer composite to provide the necessary structurally\nsupport for the massive steel plate, provide an efficient means for heat transfer, and also\ninsulate the system from parasitic heat losses. These nine layers were constructed and\ninstalled as three separate sub-assemblies: two vertical primary plates, four rows of heater\nsub-panels, and four rows of outside insulation panels. An air gap separates the 1st and 2nd ,\nand a thin buffer layer of insulation separate the 2nd and 3rd .\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47                                       42\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n3.3.3     Primary Heated Plate\n\nTo accurately represent the heat flux condition off the walls of a prototypic RPV, the primary\nheat source in the NSTF (electrically powered radiant heaters, detailed in later sections) are\nplaced behind a 1” steel plate as a means to smooth any sharp temperature gradients from\nthe hot coils while also providing the necessary emissivity for radiation heat transfer to\nthe riser tubes. Figure 20 shows the lower plate in preparation for installation, including\ntemporary eye bolts needed to hoist the 2,230 lb plate onto the structural framework.\n   This plate is fabricated from SAE 1020 low carbon steel which has stated ladle composi-\ntion limits given as 0.18% - 0.23% C, 0.30% - 0.60% Mn, 0.040% Pmax , 0.50% Smax , and Fe\nbeing the remaining constituent. The surface condition of the back plate is mill scale oxidized\nso that its emissivity was initially in the 0.7 to 0.9 range. This emissivity was measured prior\nto test operations and was found to average 0.78 - 0.79 [14] The same plates were used from\nthe early PRISM/RVACS work, a project at ANL which investigated a similar concept for\npassive decay heat removal. Early reports have mentioned that the researchers hand selected\nthese plates based on uniformity and surface condition which had a thin surface scale that\nwas an electrically nonconducting oxide with a dull dark-purple coloration. Furthermore,\nthey add that surface deformation by grinding for welding and thermocouple spot welding\nwas kept at a minimum.\n   The primary heated plate has enlarged mounting holes to allow for thermal expansion\nin all directions. The plate is hung to structural support structure, separated by 2” spacers\nand insulation, so that the heater plate subassembly is allowed to expand horizontally and\nvertically. Figure 21 shows dimensions and mounting points for the lower plate.\n\n\n\n\n                                               43                                  ANL-ART-47\n\fANL-ART-47\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                                                                            Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n44\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                                                                                                                              August 2016\n             Figure 20: Lower heated plate prior to installation. Eye hooks were temporarily installed for lifting, thermocouples visible\n\f                                                                                                          Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                                          August 2016\n45\n\n\n\n\n             Figure 21: Dimensions and mounting hole specifications of primary heated plate (top shown)\n\n\nANL-ART-47\n\f                                     Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                       August 2016\n\n\n3.3.4     Heater Subpanels\n\nThe heater sub-panels, ten in total, serve as the primary area for power control, heat transfer,\nand insulation for the 220 ceramic heater plates. The mounting system, Figure 23, positions\nthe radiant coils of the heaters away from the test section as a means to provide uniformity\nin the heat flux across the plate. This setup also minimized the risk of electrically shorting\nout the heater coils against any neighboring conductive materials.\n   The stainless steel sheets were sandblasted and then heat treated to 1900◦ F to relieve\ninternal and surface stresses. The sandblasting process was performed to enhance the surface\nemissivity of the sheets from about 0.25 to about 0.90 uniformly over both sides of the sheets,\nsignificantly improving heat transfer and temperature uniformity, and thereby reducing the\nchance of warping the stainless steel sheet. The ceramic heaters (detailed in the following\nsection) are fastened to the steel sheet with 10-32 size studs that are welded to the steel\nsheets. Each heater subassembly contains twenty ceramic plate electric heater elements (6-\nin x 12-in). The 16 central heater elements are one heater zone, and the four edge heater\nelements compose the second heater zone on the 2-ft x 5-ft heater plate subassembly.\n\n\n\n\n                     Figure 22: Heated wall, heater subpanel assembly\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47                                     46\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n                                                                  Figure 23: AutoCAD drawing of heater subpanel with ceramic heaters outlined\n                                               47              ANL-ART-47\n\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                      August 2016\n\n\n3.3.5     Ceramic Heaters\n\nThe heat source within the NSTF comprises an array of radiant heaters powered by 480\nand 240 VAC. 200 individual ceramic heaters, each measuring 6”x12”x0.5”, are capable of\nsupplying up to 1,100 W each, totaling a maximum available power of 220 kWe . These 200\nindividual plates are grouped into 40 control zones, 20 designated as the “main” and 20 as\nthe “guard” zones. Each “main” consists of 8 ceramic heater plates, while each “guard”\nconsists of two ceramic heater plates, Figure 24. The parallel series connections of each\nMain and Guard result in 120 VAC across any individual heater element.\n   These 40 control zones produce a power distribution that provides 80% of the total from\nthe Main and the remaining 20% from the Guard zones. For the purposes of test operations,\npower is primarily supplied to the Main zones while the Guards are adjusted to maintain a\nuniform temperature distribution across the heated plate, minimizing thermal gradients and\nreducing stresses.\n\n3.3.6     Heated Wall Insulation Panels\n\nThe outside insulation panels on the heated wall, installed in four vertical rows, are con-\nstructed from framed assembly that is similar to the opposing cold wall insulation panels. A\nsheet metal framework houses two stacks of of 3” insulation (6” in total), and is protected on\nthe exterior surface by 1/8” aluminum sheet metal panel. Each panel weighs approximately\n270 lbs., and has mounting provisions for hoisting and lifting operations.\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47                                    48\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n                                                                   Figure 24: Electrical detail of Main and Guard heating zones\n                                               49              ANL-ART-47\n\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                      August 2016\n\n\n\n3.4     Insulation\nIn an effort to reduce heat losses to the ambient surroundings, the NSTF is heavily insulated\nin primary control areas at or after the heat source. Non-insulated areas include the inlet\ndowncomer, inlet plenum, and horizontal chimney ducts. SuperIsol® was used on all test\nsection insulated panels and walls. Duraboard LD® was used as the backing for the ceramic\nheaters. Enerywrap 80® was used for the chimney ductwork. Durablanket S® was used as\nfiller and patchwork in smaller areas throughout. Thermal specifications and properties of\nthe insulation materials used are provided in Table 9.\n\n             Table 9: Material and thermal specifications for NSTF insulation\n\n        Name          Thickness     Max Temp        Density     Thermal Conductivity\n                                                                 (BTU-in/hr-ft2 -◦ F)\n   Super Isol®             3”         1,800 ◦ F      16 pcf     400 ◦ F 750 ◦ F 1100 ◦ F\n                                                                 0.416   0.554    0.693\n   Duraboard LD®           2”         2,300 ◦ F      16 pcf     400 ◦ F 1000 ◦ F 1600 ◦ F\n                                                                  0.55   0.847    1.339\n   Durablanket S®          1”         2,150 ◦ F       8 pcf     600 F 1000 F 1600 ◦ F\n                                                                     ◦        ◦\n\n                                                                  0.56   0.977    2.003\n   Enerywrap 80®           3”         1,200 ◦ F       8 pcf     200 F 400 F 600 ◦ F\n                                                                     ◦       ◦\n\n                                                                  0.30    0.42     0.59\n\n\n\n   Figure 25 shows a north facing cross section of the heated cavity, which identifies the\nvarious types of insulation and thicknesses used to retain thermal energy within the enclosure.\nThe north and south walls (not shown) are of similar construction to the west wall, and\nultimately include the same 6” thickness of Duraboard LD® insulation. The east (heated)\nwall comprises a matrix of different materials, which was necessary to ensure compliance\nwith the elevated temperatures found nearest the ceramic heaters. Insulation on the 24”\nductwork is included for all duct length with the exception of the inlet piping and horizontal\nfan loft forced blower segments. Nominally 24” inner diameter, a layer of 3” thick mineral\nwool insulation surrounds the bare ducts, which is covered by a 0.016” aluminum jacket.\n\n\nANL-ART-47                                    50\n\f                                                                                                                               Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                                                               August 2016\n51\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47\n             Figure 25: Cross section of heated cavity outlining areas of insulation. Viewed from a north facing perspective\n\f                                   Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                     August 2016\n\n\n\n3.5     Operating Flexibility\nThe initial design philosophy of the NSTF has resulted in a high level of flexibility in the\navailable configurations for testing. Since a final design for an air-based RCCS has not\nyet been constructed on a full scale, nor has an exact design been decided upon by US\nvendors, this flexibility has allowed the project to maintain relevance as the RCCS design\nand technology matures. Furthermore, it has allowed the project to create a diverse range\nof testing conditions. In addition to the normal boundary conditions of power and spatial\nprofiling of the heater surface, other areas for reconfiguration include the floor and wall\nspacing of the outlet plenum, heated plate to riser setback depth, chimney flow routing,\namong others.\n   Arrays of valves allow for an experiment operator to introduce alternative flow path\nrouting. Across the testing performed, the NSTF saw four primary configurations: baseline,\nreduced discharge, single chimney, and adjacent chimney roles. A summary of the compo-\nnents or features that can be adjusted to alter the configuration are summarized below in\nTable 10, along with a diagram depicting the possible chimney flow paths in Figure 26.\n\n                 Table 10: Summary of adjustable features on the NSTF\n\n        Component                                 Ranges            Baseline Value\n        Heater Power                         0 - 220 kW e                78 kW e\n        Heater Profile                Arbitrary across 40 zones           Linear\n        Flow operation                     Natural, forced               Natural\n        Forced flow                           0 - 1 kg/s                    n/a\n        Riser - heater spacing               0.45 - 1.5 m                0.71 m\n        Riser flow area                    0.078 - 0.155 m               0.155 m\n        Outlet plenum floor spacing           0 - 0.41 m                  0.41 m\n        Outlet plenum depth                  1.88 - 2.2 m                 1.88 m\n        Chimney discharge height             7.7 - 19.6 m                19.6 m\n        Chimney flow area                    0 - 0.58 m2                 0.58 m2\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47                                   52\n\f                                                                                                                                               Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                                                                               August 2016\n53\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47\n             Figure 26: Facility configurations of chimney ductwork, arrow denotes air inlet. Blue (left): baseline, dual vertical, Red\n             (left,center): reduced chimney discharge, Orange (right-center): single chimney vertical, Purple (right): adjacent inlet/outlet\n\f                                     Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                       August 2016\n\n\n\n3.6      As-built Summary\nDescribed in sections above, the NSTF is a highly flexible experimental apparatus that can be\nre-configured to different testing states with minimal or reduced effort. The areas that have\nbeen designed specifically for reconfiguration include the heated wall to riser tube horizontal\nspacing, the extension of the riser ducts into the outlet plenum, and the presence of false\nwalls on both the inlet and outlet plenum. These four areas are the primary variables that\nwill be reconfigured in future test operations, but in their present state define the ‘as-built’\nconfiguration of the NSTF, Figure 27.\n\n\n\n\n   Figure 27: Primary areas of flexibility, dimensions shown for ‘as-built’ configuration\n\n\nANL-ART-47                                     54\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n\nChapter 4\n\nTest Assembly Sensors & Control\n\nThe NSTF features a sophisticated suite of data acquisition and instrumentation for test\noperations in a dedicated control room, Figure 28. The data acquisition boards are placed\nat four points alongside the test section and routed to the central control station.\n\n\n\n\n              Figure 28: Plan view of Building 308 and NSTF test operations\n\n","numLines":320,"startLine":1632,"totalLines":8102}}}
