{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01FB35RaUfpuN1Gf1GvUmrsN","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01WDU3k25qRuACHyCM9sSLUh","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/root/curator/source/report_full_text.txt","offset":1951,"limit":340},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6431,"cache_read_input_tokens":71128,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":6431},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"47d9ec1e-27f2-4086-90f4-79a8199340a9","uuid":"f3fd77d1-0214-4392-8902-7ab28bc8e56c","request_id":"req_011Ccd12xBEpjXLfb5rohDHH"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WDU3k25qRuACHyCM9sSLUh","type":"tool_result","content":"1951\t\n1952\t\n1953\t\n1954\t                                               55                                 ANL-ART-47\n1955\t\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1956\t                                                                                      August 2016\n1957\t\n1958\t\n1959\t\n1960\t4.1     Data Acquisition\n1961\tThe data acquisition and control suite comprises several individual devices that have all been\n1962\tlinked to the primary control computer via TCP/IP and a central switch, Figure 29. This\n1963\tnetwork was created to facilitate data logging and ensure synchronization across disparate\n1964\tdevices. The control software is LabVIEW 2012, which interacts with all devices except\n1965\tthe LUNA fiber optic system. The computational demands of the fiber hardware require a\n1966\tdedicated system, although remote viewing, control, and data file access are still possible\n1967\tduring test operations.\n1968\t\n1969\t\n1970\t\n1971\t\n1972\t                           Figure 29: Communications overview\n1973\t\n1974\t\n1975\t\n1976\t   The core of the data acquisition system is four A/D converters housed in cDAQ chassis\n1977\t(cDAQ-9188 from National Instruments) which provide access to all the thermocouples,\n1978\theat flux sensors, and analogue flow transmitters installed on the NSTF. Each cDAQ can\n1979\tbe filled with up to eight cards for various analogue input/output requirements. The NSTF\n1980\t\n1981\tANL-ART-47                                    56\n1982\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n1983\tAugust 2016\n1984\t\n1985\t\n1986\tis currently fitted with twenty-six NI-9214 cards, each able to read sixteen high-resolution\n1987\tthermocouple input channels. Additionally, two NI-9205 cards provide sixteen -10-10 VDC\n1988\tanalogue input channels, and one NI-9265 provides four analogue output (4-20 mA) for\n1989\tcontrol of the chimney damper actuators. To measure temperatures along the chimney\n1990\tduct work, we have installed four wireless thermocouple transmitters, National Instruments\n1991\tmodel WSN-3212, which can monitor and relay a total of eight thermocouples back to a\n1992\twireless receiver and read into the primary LabVIEW software. A summary of these National\n1993\tInstrument devices is provided in Table 11.\n1994\t\n1995\t            Table 11: Summary of National Instruments data acquisition devices\n1996\t\n1997\t  Qty.      Model                                    Description\n1998\t  x4      cDAQ-9188      8 slot cDAQ chassis\n1999\t  x26     NI-9214        16-Channel Isothermal Thermocouple Input Module\n2000\t  x2      NI-9205        32-Ch ±200 mV to ±10 V, 16-Bit, 250 kS/s Analog Input Module\n2001\t  x4      WSN-3212       4 Ch, 24-Bit, Programmable Thermocouple Input Node\n2002\t  x1      NI-9265        4-Channel, 100 kS/s, 16-Bit, 0 to 20 mA Analog Output Module\n2003\t\n2004\t\n2005\t\n2006\t4.2      Sensors\n2007\tSensors positioned along the test assembly measure local surface temperatures, local and\n2008\tbulk air temperatures, air volumetric and mass flow rates, the total normal radiative and\n2009\tconvective components of the total heat flux, the electric power input to the heaters, and\n2010\tthe local and total or bulk heat flux. These data will be used to evaluate the heat removal\n2011\tperformance for particular configurations and testing conditions. The primary measurement\n2012\tobjective is to determine the local and bulk heat flux transport rates and associated heat\n2013\ttransfer coefficients.\n2014\t   The following sections will supply detailed information about the instrumentation, which\n2015\tconsists of thermocouples, differential pressure transducers, radiation and heat flux trans-\n2016\tducers, mass flow meters, and the wind monitor and humidity instrumentation. An overview\n2017\tsummary is provided in Table 12.\n2018\t\n2019\t                                               57                               ANL-ART-47\n2020\t\f                                     Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2021\t                                                                                       August 2016\n2022\t\n2023\t\n2024\t\n2025\t\n2026\t             Table 12: Summary of NTSF instrumentation with listed accuracy\n2027\t    Measurement             Instrument               #        Range              Accuracy\n2028\t\n2029\t Power                  Eurotherm EPower            x40      0 - 12 kW              ±1%\n2030\t Heat flux              iTi Inc., model BHT         x16    0 - 300 kW/m2            ±5%\n2031\t                        Gas space                   x34     0 - 1,250◦ C      ± 1.1◦ C or 0.4%\n2032\t                        Riser wall                  x32     0 - 1,250◦ C      ± 1.1◦ C or 0.4%\n2033\t Temperature            Heated plate                x125    0 - 1,250◦ C      ± 1.1◦ C or 0.4%\n2034\t (Type-K TC)            Insul. wall                 x193    0 - 1,250◦ C      ± 2.2◦ C or 1.1%\n2035\t                        Ceramic heater              x40     0 - 1,250◦ C      ± 2.2◦ C or 1.1%\n2036\t Mass flow rate         Sierra 640s                 x1       0 - 1 kg/s      ±1% + 0.3kg/min\n2037\t Chimney velocity       Dwyer 160F                  x2      ±0 − 45m/s             ±8.3%\n2038\t Riser ∆P               Dwyer 668-11                x8        ±64P a                ±1%\n2039\t Chimney ∆P             Dwyer 607-0B                x2        ±24P a               ±0.5%\n2040\t Humidity               Dwyer RHP                   x1      3 - 95 %RH              ±2%\n2041\t Wind speed             Davis Vantage Vue           x1      1 - 80 m/s              ±5%\n2042\t Wind direction         Davis Vantage Vue           x1        0 - 360◦               ±3◦\n2043\t Outdoor humidity       Davis Vantage Vue           x1     1 - 100 %RH              ±3%\n2044\t Outdoor temperature    Davis Vantage Vue           x1      -40◦ - +65◦ C          ±0.5◦ C\n2045\t Rainfall               Davis Vantage Vue           x1      0 - 6553 mm             ±4%\n2046\t Barometric pressure    Davis Vantage Vue           x1     410-820 mmHg         ±0.8mmHg\n2047\t\n2048\t\n2049\t\n2050\t\n2051\tANL-ART-47                                     58\n2052\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2053\tAugust 2016\n2054\t\n2055\t\n2056\t4.2.1     Wall Thermocouples\n2057\t\n2058\tThe NSTF thermocouples (a total of 424) are type-K with an accuracy of ±2.2◦ C or 0.75%\n2059\tof measured temperature. Others, such as the riser inlet and outlet gas temperature, along\n2060\twith the heated plate surface temperature, are calibrated to special limits of error (SLE)\n2061\tand have an accuracy of ±1.1◦ C or 0.4%. The vast majority of these sensors are located on\n2062\tthe heated plates and surrounding insulated panels. Sensors are flush-mounted for accurate\n2063\tmeasurement of surface temperatures without disruption of the flow field.\n2064\t\n2065\t   Figure 30 shows the installation method used for the heated plate TCs. Sensor wires\n2066\twere passed through the plates from the opposite side of the 1-in thick steel plates through\n2067\ta 5/32-in. dia. hole that is countersunk 90◦ to a 1/4-in. opening. A high-temperature\n2068\tthermal cement is used to bond junctions to the plate. Note that the wires are not joined at\n2069\tthe junction and so the electrical circuit is completed through the steel plate. This allows\n2070\tdetachment of the wire from the plate to be detected as an open circuit, which is not the\n2071\tcase if the wires are bonded together at the junction as in conventional configurations.\n2072\t\n2073\t\n2074\t\n2075\t\n2076\t                  Figure 30: Heated plate thermocouple mounting method\n2077\t\n2078\t\n2079\t                                               59                                ANL-ART-47\n2080\t\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2081\t                                                               August 2016\n2082\t\n2083\t\n2084\t\n2085\t\n2086\tANL-ART-47             60\n2087\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2088\tAugust 2016\n2089\t\n2090\t\n2091\t\n2092\t\n2093\t                                               61              ANL-ART-47\n2094\t\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2095\t                                                               August 2016\n2096\t\n2097\t\n2098\t\n2099\t\n2100\tANL-ART-47             62\n2101\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2102\tAugust 2016\n2103\t\n2104\t\n2105\t\n2106\t\n2107\t                                               63              ANL-ART-47\n2108\t\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2109\t                                                               August 2016\n2110\t\n2111\t\n2112\t\n2113\t\n2114\tANL-ART-47             64\n2115\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2116\tAugust 2016\n2117\t\n2118\t\n2119\t\n2120\t\n2121\t                                               65              ANL-ART-47\n2122\t\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2123\t                                                               August 2016\n2124\t\n2125\t\n2126\t\n2127\t\n2128\tANL-ART-47             66\n2129\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2130\tAugust 2016\n2131\t\n2132\t\n2133\t\n2134\t\n2135\t                                               67              ANL-ART-47\n2136\t\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2137\t                                                               August 2016\n2138\t\n2139\t\n2140\t\n2141\t\n2142\tANL-ART-47             68\n2143\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2144\tAugust 2016\n2145\t\n2146\t\n2147\t\n2148\t\n2149\t                                               69              ANL-ART-47\n2150\t\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2151\t                                                               August 2016\n2152\t\n2153\t\n2154\t\n2155\t\n2156\tANL-ART-47             70\n2157\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2158\tAugust 2016\n2159\t\n2160\t\n2161\t\n2162\t\n2163\t                                               71              ANL-ART-47\n2164\t\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2165\t                                                               August 2016\n2166\t\n2167\t\n2168\t\n2169\t\n2170\tANL-ART-47             72\n2171\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2172\tAugust 2016\n2173\t\n2174\t\n2175\t4.2.2     Heat Flux Sensors\n2176\t\n2177\tHeat flux meters are used to measure the heat transfer from the heated plate to the riser\n2178\tducts, and have been positioned along various riser tubes on both the cold and hot facing\n2179\twalls. The principle of the measurement is the same as that for a pair of thermocouples\n2180\tmeasuring the temperature difference across a conductor with a known thermal conductivity.\n2181\tInstead of thermocouples, the heat flux sensor uses a pair of thermopiles, which greatly\n2182\tamplifies the signal generated by the temperature difference. The relationship between the\n2183\tsignal and heat flux is obtained through NIST traceable calibration.\n2184\t   Sixteen sensors were purchased from iTi Inc, and are of Model BHT with additional\n2185\tpolyimide HFT, NIST-calibrated for 5% accuracy, rated for a maximum temperature of\n2186\t300◦ C, Figure 31.\n2187\t\n2188\t\n2189\t\n2190\t\n2191\t                     Figure 31: iTi model BHT, 300 ◦ C Polyimide HFT\n2192\t\n2193\t\n2194\t\n2195\t\n2196\t                                               73                             ANL-ART-47\n2197\t\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2198\t                                                                                      August 2016\n2199\t\n2200\t\n2201\t     Two types of sensors were purchased: one featuring a matte black surface, and the other\n2202\ta high reflectivity golden surface by means of a polyimide HFT coating. The combination\n2203\tof separate matte black surfacing (ε ≈ 1.0) and silver reflective surfacing (ε << 1.0) allows\n2204\textraction of the split between convective and radiative heat transfer modes from the heated\n2205\twall. Specific sensitivities and description of locations are provided below in Table 13, and\n2206\treference drawings on the following pages.\n2207\t\n2208\t     Across the life of the heat flux sensors, performance of the “shiny” or convective-only\n2209\tunits were found to degrade with time. Given their mode of operation strongly depends on\n2210\tmaintaining a low surface emissivity, gradual oxidation of the surfaces (an observed phe-\n2211\tnomenon) can alter the output signals and provide readings outside of the original tolerance\n2212\tand calibration. Quantification of this degradation is in-progress by in-house calibrations\n2213\tand will be published in supplemental reports by the project team.\n2214\t\n2215\t\n2216\t  Table 13: Summary of heat flux sensors on risers. Procured from iTi Inc., model BHT\n2217\t\n2218\t #     Sensor ID   Kradiative (W/m2 , mV)    Surface finish   Location\n2219\t 1        950              20.20                 matte        Hot side of duct 1 at 100 mm\n2220\t 2        951              65.72               reflective     Hot side of duct 1 at 100 mm\n2221\t 3        948              21.59                 matte        Hot side of duct 1 at 3500 mm\n2222\t 4       1358              15.92                 matte        Hot side of duct 1 at 7000 mm\n2223\t 5        933              21.73                 matte        Cold side of duct 1 at 7000 mm\n2224\t 6        939              18.15                 matte        Cold side of duct 1 at 7000 mm\n2225\t 7       1360              15.12                 matte        Hot side of duct 7 at 3500 mm\n2226\t 8       1362              41.07               reflective     Hot side of duct 7 at 3500 mm\n2227\t 9        946              19.11                 matte        Hot side of duct 7 at 7000 mm\n2228\t 10       942              18.55                 matte        Cold side of duct 7 at 3500 mm\n2229\t 11       935              52.97               reflective     Cold side of duct 7 at 3500 mm\n2230\t 12       940              24.68                 matte        Hot side of duct 11 at 3500 mm\n2231\t 13       941              22.07                 matte        Hot side of duct 11 at 7000 mm\n2232\t 14       936              62.43               reflective     Hot side of duct 11 at 7000 mm\n2233\t 15       932              19.77                 matte        Cold side of duct 11 at 350 mm\n2234\t 16       938              22.88                 matte        Cold side of duct 11 at 700 mm\n2235\t 17      1355              15.54                 matte        South side of duct 7 at 3500 mm\n2236\t 18      1356              15.24                 matte        North side of duct 7 at 3500 mm\n2237\t 19      1359              44.62               reflective     Hot side of duct 1 at 7000 mm\n2238\t\n2239\t\n2240\t\n2241\tANL-ART-47                                     74\n2242\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2243\tAugust 2016\n2244\t\n2245\t\n2246\t\n2247\t\n2248\t                                               75              ANL-ART-47\n2249\t\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2250\t                                                               August 2016\n2251\t\n2252\t\n2253\t\n2254\t\n2255\tANL-ART-47             76\n2256\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2257\tAugust 2016\n2258\t\n2259\t\n2260\t4.2.3     Meteorological\n2261\t\n2262\tAmbient conditions can have a significant effect on RCCS performance and so it is necessary\n2263\tto monitor meteorological conditions near the stack outlet. A weather station, model Davis\n2264\tVantageVue, was selected for this purpose, providing barometric pressure, temperature, hu-\n2265\tmidity, wind speed, and wind direction. All measurements except wind direction have been\n2266\tcalibrated to NIST standards.\n2267\t\n2268\t   The weather station is mounted on the building roof and linked to a console station\n2269\tin the control room via wireless transmissions. The console is able to store up to 2,560\n2270\trecords on internal storage before it begins overwriting the oldest data. The console has\n2271\tbeen configured to poll and store 1 data record every minute, which limits its total capacity\n2272\tto 1.75 days or 42 hours. To work around this, given the three day or longer test operations,\n2273\tthe software has been configured to automatically download and store all available records\n2274\tevery 24 hours. Time synchronization across the devices is routinely performed to ensure\n2275\taccurate data. Details of the different meteorological measurements for the Davis VantageVue\n2276\tweather station are provided below in Table 14, and a reference to its physical mounting\n2277\tlocation in Figures 32 and 33.\n2278\t\n2279\t\n2280\t\n2281\t           Table 14: Device specifications for Davis VantageVue weather station\n2282\t        Function                   Resolution       Range            Accuracy (±)\n2283\t        Barometric Pressure        0.1 mmHg         410 - 820 mmHg   0.8 mmHg\n2284\t        Humidity                   0.01             1 - 100%         0.03\n2285\t        Rainfall                   0.2 mm           0 - 6553 mm      0.04\n2286\t        Temperature                0.1 ◦ C          -40 to 60 ◦ C    0.5 ◦ C\n2287\t        Wind direction             1◦               0 - 360◦         3◦\n2288\t        Wind speed                 0.1 m/s          1 - 80 m/s       0.05\n2289\t        Wind run                   0.01 km          unlimited        0.05\n2290\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"47d9ec1e-27f2-4086-90f4-79a8199340a9","uuid":"dc8cbf35-7b4f-4fbb-bf8a-9c6daacd11da","timestamp":"2026-07-02T09:33:57.471Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/root/curator/source/report_full_text.txt","content":"\n\n\n                                               55                                 ANL-ART-47\n\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                      August 2016\n\n\n\n4.1     Data Acquisition\nThe data acquisition and control suite comprises several individual devices that have all been\nlinked to the primary control computer via TCP/IP and a central switch, Figure 29. This\nnetwork was created to facilitate data logging and ensure synchronization across disparate\ndevices. The control software is LabVIEW 2012, which interacts with all devices except\nthe LUNA fiber optic system. The computational demands of the fiber hardware require a\ndedicated system, although remote viewing, control, and data file access are still possible\nduring test operations.\n\n\n\n\n                           Figure 29: Communications overview\n\n\n\n   The core of the data acquisition system is four A/D converters housed in cDAQ chassis\n(cDAQ-9188 from National Instruments) which provide access to all the thermocouples,\nheat flux sensors, and analogue flow transmitters installed on the NSTF. Each cDAQ can\nbe filled with up to eight cards for various analogue input/output requirements. The NSTF\n\nANL-ART-47                                    56\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\nis currently fitted with twenty-six NI-9214 cards, each able to read sixteen high-resolution\nthermocouple input channels. Additionally, two NI-9205 cards provide sixteen -10-10 VDC\nanalogue input channels, and one NI-9265 provides four analogue output (4-20 mA) for\ncontrol of the chimney damper actuators. To measure temperatures along the chimney\nduct work, we have installed four wireless thermocouple transmitters, National Instruments\nmodel WSN-3212, which can monitor and relay a total of eight thermocouples back to a\nwireless receiver and read into the primary LabVIEW software. A summary of these National\nInstrument devices is provided in Table 11.\n\n            Table 11: Summary of National Instruments data acquisition devices\n\n  Qty.      Model                                    Description\n  x4      cDAQ-9188      8 slot cDAQ chassis\n  x26     NI-9214        16-Channel Isothermal Thermocouple Input Module\n  x2      NI-9205        32-Ch ±200 mV to ±10 V, 16-Bit, 250 kS/s Analog Input Module\n  x4      WSN-3212       4 Ch, 24-Bit, Programmable Thermocouple Input Node\n  x1      NI-9265        4-Channel, 100 kS/s, 16-Bit, 0 to 20 mA Analog Output Module\n\n\n\n4.2      Sensors\nSensors positioned along the test assembly measure local surface temperatures, local and\nbulk air temperatures, air volumetric and mass flow rates, the total normal radiative and\nconvective components of the total heat flux, the electric power input to the heaters, and\nthe local and total or bulk heat flux. These data will be used to evaluate the heat removal\nperformance for particular configurations and testing conditions. The primary measurement\nobjective is to determine the local and bulk heat flux transport rates and associated heat\ntransfer coefficients.\n   The following sections will supply detailed information about the instrumentation, which\nconsists of thermocouples, differential pressure transducers, radiation and heat flux trans-\nducers, mass flow meters, and the wind monitor and humidity instrumentation. An overview\nsummary is provided in Table 12.\n\n                                               57                               ANL-ART-47\n\f                                     Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                       August 2016\n\n\n\n\n             Table 12: Summary of NTSF instrumentation with listed accuracy\n    Measurement             Instrument               #        Range              Accuracy\n\n Power                  Eurotherm EPower            x40      0 - 12 kW              ±1%\n Heat flux              iTi Inc., model BHT         x16    0 - 300 kW/m2            ±5%\n                        Gas space                   x34     0 - 1,250◦ C      ± 1.1◦ C or 0.4%\n                        Riser wall                  x32     0 - 1,250◦ C      ± 1.1◦ C or 0.4%\n Temperature            Heated plate                x125    0 - 1,250◦ C      ± 1.1◦ C or 0.4%\n (Type-K TC)            Insul. wall                 x193    0 - 1,250◦ C      ± 2.2◦ C or 1.1%\n                        Ceramic heater              x40     0 - 1,250◦ C      ± 2.2◦ C or 1.1%\n Mass flow rate         Sierra 640s                 x1       0 - 1 kg/s      ±1% + 0.3kg/min\n Chimney velocity       Dwyer 160F                  x2      ±0 − 45m/s             ±8.3%\n Riser ∆P               Dwyer 668-11                x8        ±64P a                ±1%\n Chimney ∆P             Dwyer 607-0B                x2        ±24P a               ±0.5%\n Humidity               Dwyer RHP                   x1      3 - 95 %RH              ±2%\n Wind speed             Davis Vantage Vue           x1      1 - 80 m/s              ±5%\n Wind direction         Davis Vantage Vue           x1        0 - 360◦               ±3◦\n Outdoor humidity       Davis Vantage Vue           x1     1 - 100 %RH              ±3%\n Outdoor temperature    Davis Vantage Vue           x1      -40◦ - +65◦ C          ±0.5◦ C\n Rainfall               Davis Vantage Vue           x1      0 - 6553 mm             ±4%\n Barometric pressure    Davis Vantage Vue           x1     410-820 mmHg         ±0.8mmHg\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47                                     58\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n4.2.1     Wall Thermocouples\n\nThe NSTF thermocouples (a total of 424) are type-K with an accuracy of ±2.2◦ C or 0.75%\nof measured temperature. Others, such as the riser inlet and outlet gas temperature, along\nwith the heated plate surface temperature, are calibrated to special limits of error (SLE)\nand have an accuracy of ±1.1◦ C or 0.4%. The vast majority of these sensors are located on\nthe heated plates and surrounding insulated panels. Sensors are flush-mounted for accurate\nmeasurement of surface temperatures without disruption of the flow field.\n\n   Figure 30 shows the installation method used for the heated plate TCs. Sensor wires\nwere passed through the plates from the opposite side of the 1-in thick steel plates through\na 5/32-in. dia. hole that is countersunk 90◦ to a 1/4-in. opening. A high-temperature\nthermal cement is used to bond junctions to the plate. Note that the wires are not joined at\nthe junction and so the electrical circuit is completed through the steel plate. This allows\ndetachment of the wire from the plate to be detected as an open circuit, which is not the\ncase if the wires are bonded together at the junction as in conventional configurations.\n\n\n\n\n                  Figure 30: Heated plate thermocouple mounting method\n\n\n                                               59                                ANL-ART-47\n\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                               August 2016\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47             60\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n\n                                               61              ANL-ART-47\n\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                               August 2016\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47             62\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n\n                                               63              ANL-ART-47\n\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                               August 2016\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47             64\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n\n                                               65              ANL-ART-47\n\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                               August 2016\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47             66\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n\n                                               67              ANL-ART-47\n\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                               August 2016\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47             68\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n\n                                               69              ANL-ART-47\n\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                               August 2016\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47             70\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n\n                                               71              ANL-ART-47\n\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                               August 2016\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47             72\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n4.2.2     Heat Flux Sensors\n\nHeat flux meters are used to measure the heat transfer from the heated plate to the riser\nducts, and have been positioned along various riser tubes on both the cold and hot facing\nwalls. The principle of the measurement is the same as that for a pair of thermocouples\nmeasuring the temperature difference across a conductor with a known thermal conductivity.\nInstead of thermocouples, the heat flux sensor uses a pair of thermopiles, which greatly\namplifies the signal generated by the temperature difference. The relationship between the\nsignal and heat flux is obtained through NIST traceable calibration.\n   Sixteen sensors were purchased from iTi Inc, and are of Model BHT with additional\npolyimide HFT, NIST-calibrated for 5% accuracy, rated for a maximum temperature of\n300◦ C, Figure 31.\n\n\n\n\n                     Figure 31: iTi model BHT, 300 ◦ C Polyimide HFT\n\n\n\n\n                                               73                             ANL-ART-47\n\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                      August 2016\n\n\n     Two types of sensors were purchased: one featuring a matte black surface, and the other\na high reflectivity golden surface by means of a polyimide HFT coating. The combination\nof separate matte black surfacing (ε ≈ 1.0) and silver reflective surfacing (ε << 1.0) allows\nextraction of the split between convective and radiative heat transfer modes from the heated\nwall. Specific sensitivities and description of locations are provided below in Table 13, and\nreference drawings on the following pages.\n\n     Across the life of the heat flux sensors, performance of the “shiny” or convective-only\nunits were found to degrade with time. Given their mode of operation strongly depends on\nmaintaining a low surface emissivity, gradual oxidation of the surfaces (an observed phe-\nnomenon) can alter the output signals and provide readings outside of the original tolerance\nand calibration. Quantification of this degradation is in-progress by in-house calibrations\nand will be published in supplemental reports by the project team.\n\n\n  Table 13: Summary of heat flux sensors on risers. Procured from iTi Inc., model BHT\n\n #     Sensor ID   Kradiative (W/m2 , mV)    Surface finish   Location\n 1        950              20.20                 matte        Hot side of duct 1 at 100 mm\n 2        951              65.72               reflective     Hot side of duct 1 at 100 mm\n 3        948              21.59                 matte        Hot side of duct 1 at 3500 mm\n 4       1358              15.92                 matte        Hot side of duct 1 at 7000 mm\n 5        933              21.73                 matte        Cold side of duct 1 at 7000 mm\n 6        939              18.15                 matte        Cold side of duct 1 at 7000 mm\n 7       1360              15.12                 matte        Hot side of duct 7 at 3500 mm\n 8       1362              41.07               reflective     Hot side of duct 7 at 3500 mm\n 9        946              19.11                 matte        Hot side of duct 7 at 7000 mm\n 10       942              18.55                 matte        Cold side of duct 7 at 3500 mm\n 11       935              52.97               reflective     Cold side of duct 7 at 3500 mm\n 12       940              24.68                 matte        Hot side of duct 11 at 3500 mm\n 13       941              22.07                 matte        Hot side of duct 11 at 7000 mm\n 14       936              62.43               reflective     Hot side of duct 11 at 7000 mm\n 15       932              19.77                 matte        Cold side of duct 11 at 350 mm\n 16       938              22.88                 matte        Cold side of duct 11 at 700 mm\n 17      1355              15.54                 matte        South side of duct 7 at 3500 mm\n 18      1356              15.24                 matte        North side of duct 7 at 3500 mm\n 19      1359              44.62               reflective     Hot side of duct 1 at 7000 mm\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47                                     74\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n\n                                               75              ANL-ART-47\n\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                               August 2016\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47             76\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n4.2.3     Meteorological\n\nAmbient conditions can have a significant effect on RCCS performance and so it is necessary\nto monitor meteorological conditions near the stack outlet. A weather station, model Davis\nVantageVue, was selected for this purpose, providing barometric pressure, temperature, hu-\nmidity, wind speed, and wind direction. All measurements except wind direction have been\ncalibrated to NIST standards.\n\n   The weather station is mounted on the building roof and linked to a console station\nin the control room via wireless transmissions. The console is able to store up to 2,560\nrecords on internal storage before it begins overwriting the oldest data. The console has\nbeen configured to poll and store 1 data record every minute, which limits its total capacity\nto 1.75 days or 42 hours. To work around this, given the three day or longer test operations,\nthe software has been configured to automatically download and store all available records\nevery 24 hours. Time synchronization across the devices is routinely performed to ensure\naccurate data. Details of the different meteorological measurements for the Davis VantageVue\nweather station are provided below in Table 14, and a reference to its physical mounting\nlocation in Figures 32 and 33.\n\n\n\n           Table 14: Device specifications for Davis VantageVue weather station\n        Function                   Resolution       Range            Accuracy (±)\n        Barometric Pressure        0.1 mmHg         410 - 820 mmHg   0.8 mmHg\n        Humidity                   0.01             1 - 100%         0.03\n        Rainfall                   0.2 mm           0 - 6553 mm      0.04\n        Temperature                0.1 ◦ C          -40 to 60 ◦ C    0.5 ◦ C\n        Wind direction             1◦               0 - 360◦         3◦\n        Wind speed                 0.1 m/s          1 - 80 m/s       0.05\n        Wind run                   0.01 km          unlimited        0.05\n","numLines":340,"startLine":1951,"totalLines":8102}}}
