{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01KAj7SQLUdmUFEu7whhhXum","type":"tool_result","content":"2290\t\n2291\t\n2292\t\n2293\t\n2294\t                                               77                                ANL-ART-47\n2295\t\f                                Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2296\t                                                                                  August 2016\n2297\t\n2298\t\n2299\t\n2300\t\n2301\t             Figure 32: Position of weather station of Bldg. 308 roof top\n2302\t\n2303\t\n2304\t\n2305\t\n2306\t             Figure 33: Picture of weather station of Bldg. 308 roof top\n2307\t\n2308\t\n2309\t\n2310\t\n2311\tANL-ART-47                                78\n2312\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2313\tAugust 2016\n2314\t\n2315\t\n2316\t\n2317\t\n2318\t                                               79              ANL-ART-47\n2319\t\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2320\t                                                                                      August 2016\n2321\t\n2322\t\n2323\t4.2.4    Differential Pressure\n2324\t\n2325\tDifferential pressure transmitters are installed across eight of the riser ducts (3, 5, 8, and\n2326\t10 omitted), and across both chimney networks. The total pressure drop can be defined\n2327\tby the sum of frictional, gravitational, and minor losses. To separate the gravitational\n2328\t(density) influences, thermocouples are positioned alongside each tap point and references\n2329\tto isothermal baseline measurements. Influences from ambient temperature gradients are\n2330\tminimized by tightly bundling impulse lines, selecting bundle runs that avoid surfaces at\n2331\televated temperatures, and shielding the transmitters from large temperature swings. Eight\n2332\tof the transmitters positioned across the riser ducts were purchased from Dwyer, model 668\n2333\twhich features bidirectional capabilities with a span of ±0.25” H2 O (64 Pa). Two additional\n2334\ttransmitters across the chimney segments were also purchased from Dwyer, but high accuracy\n2335\tand resolution model 607 were selected, which features bidirectional capabilities with a span\n2336\tof ±0.1” H2 O (24 Pa).\n2337\t\n2338\t\n2339\t\n2340\t                    Table 15: Differential pressure device specifications\n2341\t\n2342\t                             Dwyer 668-11                       Dwyer 607-0B\n2343\t     NSTF Location           Riser tubes                        Chimney ducts\n2344\t              Range          0 to ±0.25” w.c.                   0 to ±0.10” w.c.\n2345\t           Accuracy          ±1% of full scale (RSS)            ±0.5% F.S.\n2346\t Long Term Stability         not rated                          ±0.5% F.S.O./yr\n2347\t Temperature Limits          0 to 150◦ F (-18 to 65◦ C)         -20 to 160◦ F (-29 to 71◦ C)\n2348\t     Pressure Limits         10 psig (0.69 bar)                 10 psig (0.69 bar)\n2349\t   Operating Temp.           0 to 150◦ F (-18 to 65◦ C).        35 to 135◦ F (2 to 57◦ C)\n2350\t    Thermal Effects          0.033% FS/◦ F (0.18% FS/◦ C)       ±0.015% F.S./◦ F\n2351\t     Supply Voltage          12-30 VDC                          12-36 VDC\n2352\t             Output          4 to 20 mA, 2-wire                 4 to 20 mA DC, 2-wire\n2353\t     Response Time           <60 msec                           250 msec max\n2354\t    Loop Resistance          0-800 ohms                         0 to 1045 ohms\n2355\t            Housing          Fire retardant glass polyester     300 Series stainless (NEMA 2)\n2356\t             Weight          3 oz (85 g)                        1.04 lb (472 g)\n2357\t   Agency Approval           CE                                 CE\n2358\t\n2359\t\n2360\t\n2361\tANL-ART-47                                    80\n2362\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2363\tAugust 2016\n2364\t\n2365\t\n2366\t\n2367\t\n2368\t                                               81              ANL-ART-47\n2369\t\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2370\t                                                               August 2016\n2371\t\n2372\t\n2373\t\n2374\t\n2375\tANL-ART-47             82\n2376\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2377\tAugust 2016\n2378\t\n2379\t\n2380\t4.2.5     Inlet Flow and Humidity\n2381\t\n2382\tA Sierra 640S thermal mass flow meter is located 24” past the end of the flow conditioner and\n2383\textends to the centerline of the duct. This instrument provides measurement of temperature\n2384\tcompensated mass flow rates and is the first measurement parameter of the incoming air\n2385\tsupply. Measurement of bulk humidity is made by a single humidity probe, Dwyer RHP-\n2386\t2O11, which is positioned 24” above and at the centerline of the 24” diameter entrance\n2387\tarea.\n2388\t\n2389\t\n2390\t                        Table 16: Inlet mass flow meter specifications\n2391\t\n2392\t                                   Sierra 640S\n2393\t    NSTF Location                  Inlet downcomer\n2394\t    Accuracy of Point Velocity     ±1% of reading + 0.5% of full scale\n2395\t    Repeatability                  ±0.2% of full scale\n2396\t    Temperature Coef.              ±0.06% per ◦ C within ±25◦ C to 50◦ C of calibration\n2397\t    Pressure Coef.                 0.02% per psi for air, consult factory for other gases\n2398\t    Response Time                  One second to 63% of final velocity value\n2399\t    Pressure Drop                  Negligible for pipes three inches in diameter or larger\n2400\t\n2401\t\n2402\t\n2403\t\n2404\t                    Table 17: Inlet plenum humidity probe specifications\n2405\t\n2406\t                                                 Dwyer RHP 2O-11\n2407\t                   NSTF location           Inlet plenum\n2408\t                   Relative Humidity Range 0 to 100% RH\n2409\t                   Temperature Range       -40 to 140◦ F (-40 to 60◦ C)\n2410\t                   Accuracy                ±2% 10-90% RH @ 25◦ C\n2411\t                   Hysteresis              ±1%\n2412\t                   Repeatability           ±0.1% typical\n2413\t                   Temperature Limits      -40 to 140◦ F (-40 to 60◦ C)\n2414\t                   Response Time           15 seconds\n2415\t                   Drift                   < 1% RH/year\n2416\t\n2417\t\n2418\t\n2419\t                                               83                                 ANL-ART-47\n2420\t\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2421\t                                                               August 2016\n2422\t\n2423\t\n2424\t\n2425\t\n2426\tANL-ART-47             84\n2427\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2428\tAugust 2016\n2429\t\n2430\t\n2431\t\n2432\t\n2433\t                                               85              ANL-ART-47\n2434\t\f                                     Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2435\t                                                                                       August 2016\n2436\t\n2437\t\n2438\t4.2.6    Hot-wire Probes\n2439\t\n2440\tA suite of Dantec hot-wire, or constant temperature anemometer (CTA) probes have been\n2441\tprocured and added to the NSTF. The probes are miniature straight-wires with a 3-mm\n2442\tOD body and 10-µm tungsten wire, Figure 34, capable of measuring velocities between 0.2\n2443\tand 500 m/s at a maximum process temperature of 300◦ C. Each probe is calibrated to a\n2444\trange of known velocities prior to test operations to obtain a 5th order polynomial fit curve,\n2445\tand operate at a constant wire temperature of 242◦ C. Probes are simultaneously sampled at\n2446\t50 kHz, and feature a co-located thermocouple to allow for temperature correction during\n2447\tpost-processing [15].\n2448\t\n2449\t\n2450\t\n2451\t\n2452\t               Figure 34: Diagram of miniature hot-wire probe, units in mm\n2453\t\n2454\t\n2455\t\n2456\t   The turbulence intensity was calculated from RMS velocity measurements [16] from the\n2457\thot-wire probes, Eqns. 3 - 5. The numbers of samples per acquisition totaled 250,000 points\n2458\tand were taken at a rate of 50 kHz.\n2459\t\n2460\t\n2461\t                                                1 N\n2462\t                                                  X\n2463\t                                      Umean =       Ui                                        (3)\n2464\t                                                N 1\n2465\t\n2466\t                                           N\n2467\t                                                                !0.5\n2468\t                                        1 X\n2469\t                            Urms =           (Ui − Umean )2                                   (4)\n2470\t                                      N −1 1\n2471\t\n2472\t                                               Urms\n2473\t                                          I=                                                  (5)\n2474\t                                               Umean\n2475\t\n2476\tANL-ART-47                                     86\n2477\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2478\tAugust 2016\n2479\t\n2480\t\n2481\t\n2482\t\n2483\t                                               87              ANL-ART-47\n2484\t\f                                     Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2485\t                                                                                       August 2016\n2486\t\n2487\t\n2488\t4.2.7     Pitot Tubes\n2489\t\n2490\tTesting performed during 2014 produced high-quality measurements of the differential pres-\n2491\tsure drop within the riser ducts. However, measurements within the chimney region were\n2492\tdominated by gravitational effects and thus provided little insight into the frictional effects.\n2493\tTo isolate the effects of friction only, two pitot tubes, Model 160F from Dwyer instruments,\n2494\tFigure 35 were added to the suite of instrumentation and served as replacements for the\n2495\tchimney differential pressure measurements. While convention recommends a minimum flow\n2496\tlength of 10 L/D, this was not possible within the current chimney configuration. Thus, their\n2497\tinstallation position will require their output signals to be treated as relative flow velocities\n2498\tbetween the dual chimney ducts, and not as absolute measurements of the flow velocity.\n2499\t\n2500\t\n2501\t\n2502\t\n2503\tFigure 35: Dwyer 160F pitot tubes installed along chimney ductwork. Right figure shows\n2504\tair ports that translate air velocity into fluid pressure\n2505\t\n2506\t   The pitot tubes are constructed from 304 SS, are characterized by a K-factor, Kp of 0.81,\n2507\tand claim an accuracy of ±2% of the full scale range, from 0 - 45 m/s. The full uncertainty,\n2508\thowever, requires a propagation of error from their defining velocity correlation, Eqn. 6. As\n2509\tan example for baseline testing conditions, where measured differential pressures average 1.5\n2510\tPa and gas temperatures of 100 ◦ C, the calculated velocity would be 1.44 ± 0.12 m/s, or\n2511\t±8.3%.\n2512\t\n2513\t                                                    s\n2514\t                                                        2∆P\n2515\t                                      Vpitot = Kp                                             (6)\n2516\t                                                         ρ\n2517\t\n2518\tANL-ART-47                                     88\n2519\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2520\tAugust 2016\n2521\t\n2522\t\n2523\t4.2.8     Gas Temperature\n2524\t\n2525\t\n2526\tWithin each riser, Type-K thermocouples are placed and extend to the length wise (10”)\n2527\tduct centerline, Figure 36. These thermocouples were purchased from ARI industries, and\n2528\tare of model T-22N-12BK8A-96(MOD). The inlet thermocouple is placed 0.75” from the\n2529\tbottom lip on the cold side, and the outlet placed 4.0” below the top lip from the hot side.\n2530\t\n2531\t\n2532\t\n2533\t\n2534\t               Figure 36: Placement of inlet and outlet instruments for riser\n2535\t\n2536\t\n2537\t\n2538\t\n2539\t   The outlet plenum features five instrumented insulation panels. The four adjacent ver-\n2540\ttical sides (north, south, east, and west) contain six embedded interior wall thermocouples,\n2541\twhile the fifth top ceiling panel contains identical wall thermocouples in addition to seven\n2542\tthermocouple rakes for gas temperature measurements within the bulk volume of the plenum.\n2543\tEach rake measures six junctions along its length, extending a 170-cm along the total 188-cm\n2544\theight of the plenum.\n2545\t\n2546\t                                               89                               ANL-ART-47\n2547\t\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2548\t                                                               August 2016\n2549\t\n2550\t\n2551\t\n2552\t\n2553\tANL-ART-47             90\n2554\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2555\tAugust 2016\n2556\t\n2557\t\n2558\t\n2559\t\n2560\t                                               91              ANL-ART-47\n2561\t\f                                 Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2562\t                                                                                   August 2016\n2563\t\n2564\t\n2565\t\n2566\t\n2567\tFigure 37: Typical rake junction locations, placed along upper plenum top panel and ex-\n2568\ttending downward\n2569\t\n2570\t\n2571\tANL-ART-47                                 92\n2572\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2573\tAugust 2016\n2574\t\n2575\t\n2576\t4.2.9      Luna Fiber Optic Temperature\n2577\t\n2578\tThe NSTF is outfitted for fiber optics, notably a distributed sensing system by Luna Tech-\n2579\tnologies that can provide the necessary data density for validation of CFD tools. Distributed\n2580\tfiber optic temperature sensing is a technique based upon distributed strain sensing and en-\n2581\tables the acquisition of thousands of temperature measurements from a single optical fiber\n2582\t[17]. The fiber temperature sensors used here exploit Rayleigh scattering losses from struc-\n2583\ttural inhomogeneities and impurities at the molecular level of ordinary telecom fibers [18].\n2584\tThe ODiSi A-10 from Luna Technologies has been used at other facilities at Argonne [19],\n2585\tand also was used for measurements in the NSTF.\n2586\t\n2587\t\n2588\t                            Table 18: Specifications of Luna ODiSi A-10\n2589\t                                    Parameter                       Specification\n2590\t                       Model                                               A10\n2591\t                       Maximum Sensing Length                             10 m\n2592\t                       Acquisition Rate1                                  5 Hz\n2593\t                       Minimum Sensor Spacing                            0.4 mm\n2594\t                       Minimum Gage Length2                               1 mm\n2595\t                       Wavelength Accuracy3                              1.5 pm\n2596\t                       Strain\n2597\t                        Range                                      ±13,000 µStrain\n2598\t                        Single Scan Pepeatability1 4 5               ±2 µStrain\n2599\t                       Temperature\n2600\t                        Range6                                       -50 to 300 ◦ C\n2601\t                        Single Scan Pepeatability1 4 5                  ±0.2 ◦ C\n2602\t\n2603\t\n2604\t\n2605\t\n2606\t   1\n2607\t       For the default measurement range of ±1,250 µStrain or ±200 ◦ C\n2608\t   2\n2609\t       Minimum gage length is achievable using the largest measurement range, having a single scan repeata-\n2610\tbility of ±17.0 µStrain or ±2.0 ◦ C\n2611\t     3\n2612\t       Accuracy maintained by an internal NIST - traceable HCN gas cell\n2613\t     4\n2614\t       Temperature and strain measurements are calculated from the spectral shift of scattered laser light.\n2615\tUsing the default conversion coefficients of 1 GHz = 0.8 ◦ C = 6.58 µStrain , the accuracy of temperature\n2616\tand strain are 0.15 ◦ C and 1.25 µStrain\n2617\t     5\n2618\t       For the default gage length of 1 cm\n2619\t     6\n2620\t       Based on material properties of the standard sensor: polyimide - coated, low - bend - loss optical fiber\n2621\t\n2622\t\n2623\t                                                      93                                         ANL-ART-47\n2624\t\f                                      Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2625\t                                                                                        August 2016\n2626\t\n2627\t\n2628\t   The fibers are made of 155 µm polyimide-coated single-mode commercial telecom fiber\n2629\t(Specialty Photonics CL POLY 1310) that has been tested for accuracy and repeatability"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"47d9ec1e-27f2-4086-90f4-79a8199340a9","uuid":"1e910c1d-ad3f-4751-b36f-0ae1ccc906a3","timestamp":"2026-07-02T09:34:07.001Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/root/curator/source/report_full_text.txt","content":"\n\n\n\n                                               77                                ANL-ART-47\n\f                                Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                  August 2016\n\n\n\n\n             Figure 32: Position of weather station of Bldg. 308 roof top\n\n\n\n\n             Figure 33: Picture of weather station of Bldg. 308 roof top\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47                                78\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n\n                                               79              ANL-ART-47\n\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                      August 2016\n\n\n4.2.4    Differential Pressure\n\nDifferential pressure transmitters are installed across eight of the riser ducts (3, 5, 8, and\n10 omitted), and across both chimney networks. The total pressure drop can be defined\nby the sum of frictional, gravitational, and minor losses. To separate the gravitational\n(density) influences, thermocouples are positioned alongside each tap point and references\nto isothermal baseline measurements. Influences from ambient temperature gradients are\nminimized by tightly bundling impulse lines, selecting bundle runs that avoid surfaces at\nelevated temperatures, and shielding the transmitters from large temperature swings. Eight\nof the transmitters positioned across the riser ducts were purchased from Dwyer, model 668\nwhich features bidirectional capabilities with a span of ±0.25” H2 O (64 Pa). Two additional\ntransmitters across the chimney segments were also purchased from Dwyer, but high accuracy\nand resolution model 607 were selected, which features bidirectional capabilities with a span\nof ±0.1” H2 O (24 Pa).\n\n\n\n                    Table 15: Differential pressure device specifications\n\n                             Dwyer 668-11                       Dwyer 607-0B\n     NSTF Location           Riser tubes                        Chimney ducts\n              Range          0 to ±0.25” w.c.                   0 to ±0.10” w.c.\n           Accuracy          ±1% of full scale (RSS)            ±0.5% F.S.\n Long Term Stability         not rated                          ±0.5% F.S.O./yr\n Temperature Limits          0 to 150◦ F (-18 to 65◦ C)         -20 to 160◦ F (-29 to 71◦ C)\n     Pressure Limits         10 psig (0.69 bar)                 10 psig (0.69 bar)\n   Operating Temp.           0 to 150◦ F (-18 to 65◦ C).        35 to 135◦ F (2 to 57◦ C)\n    Thermal Effects          0.033% FS/◦ F (0.18% FS/◦ C)       ±0.015% F.S./◦ F\n     Supply Voltage          12-30 VDC                          12-36 VDC\n             Output          4 to 20 mA, 2-wire                 4 to 20 mA DC, 2-wire\n     Response Time           <60 msec                           250 msec max\n    Loop Resistance          0-800 ohms                         0 to 1045 ohms\n            Housing          Fire retardant glass polyester     300 Series stainless (NEMA 2)\n             Weight          3 oz (85 g)                        1.04 lb (472 g)\n   Agency Approval           CE                                 CE\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47                                    80\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n\n                                               81              ANL-ART-47\n\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                               August 2016\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47             82\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n4.2.5     Inlet Flow and Humidity\n\nA Sierra 640S thermal mass flow meter is located 24” past the end of the flow conditioner and\nextends to the centerline of the duct. This instrument provides measurement of temperature\ncompensated mass flow rates and is the first measurement parameter of the incoming air\nsupply. Measurement of bulk humidity is made by a single humidity probe, Dwyer RHP-\n2O11, which is positioned 24” above and at the centerline of the 24” diameter entrance\narea.\n\n\n                        Table 16: Inlet mass flow meter specifications\n\n                                   Sierra 640S\n    NSTF Location                  Inlet downcomer\n    Accuracy of Point Velocity     ±1% of reading + 0.5% of full scale\n    Repeatability                  ±0.2% of full scale\n    Temperature Coef.              ±0.06% per ◦ C within ±25◦ C to 50◦ C of calibration\n    Pressure Coef.                 0.02% per psi for air, consult factory for other gases\n    Response Time                  One second to 63% of final velocity value\n    Pressure Drop                  Negligible for pipes three inches in diameter or larger\n\n\n\n\n                    Table 17: Inlet plenum humidity probe specifications\n\n                                                 Dwyer RHP 2O-11\n                   NSTF location           Inlet plenum\n                   Relative Humidity Range 0 to 100% RH\n                   Temperature Range       -40 to 140◦ F (-40 to 60◦ C)\n                   Accuracy                ±2% 10-90% RH @ 25◦ C\n                   Hysteresis              ±1%\n                   Repeatability           ±0.1% typical\n                   Temperature Limits      -40 to 140◦ F (-40 to 60◦ C)\n                   Response Time           15 seconds\n                   Drift                   < 1% RH/year\n\n\n\n                                               83                                 ANL-ART-47\n\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                               August 2016\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47             84\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n\n                                               85              ANL-ART-47\n\f                                     Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                       August 2016\n\n\n4.2.6    Hot-wire Probes\n\nA suite of Dantec hot-wire, or constant temperature anemometer (CTA) probes have been\nprocured and added to the NSTF. The probes are miniature straight-wires with a 3-mm\nOD body and 10-µm tungsten wire, Figure 34, capable of measuring velocities between 0.2\nand 500 m/s at a maximum process temperature of 300◦ C. Each probe is calibrated to a\nrange of known velocities prior to test operations to obtain a 5th order polynomial fit curve,\nand operate at a constant wire temperature of 242◦ C. Probes are simultaneously sampled at\n50 kHz, and feature a co-located thermocouple to allow for temperature correction during\npost-processing [15].\n\n\n\n\n               Figure 34: Diagram of miniature hot-wire probe, units in mm\n\n\n\n   The turbulence intensity was calculated from RMS velocity measurements [16] from the\nhot-wire probes, Eqns. 3 - 5. The numbers of samples per acquisition totaled 250,000 points\nand were taken at a rate of 50 kHz.\n\n\n                                                1 N\n                                                  X\n                                      Umean =       Ui                                        (3)\n                                                N 1\n\n                                           N\n                                                                !0.5\n                                        1 X\n                            Urms =           (Ui − Umean )2                                   (4)\n                                      N −1 1\n\n                                               Urms\n                                          I=                                                  (5)\n                                               Umean\n\nANL-ART-47                                     86\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n\n                                               87              ANL-ART-47\n\f                                     Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                       August 2016\n\n\n4.2.7     Pitot Tubes\n\nTesting performed during 2014 produced high-quality measurements of the differential pres-\nsure drop within the riser ducts. However, measurements within the chimney region were\ndominated by gravitational effects and thus provided little insight into the frictional effects.\nTo isolate the effects of friction only, two pitot tubes, Model 160F from Dwyer instruments,\nFigure 35 were added to the suite of instrumentation and served as replacements for the\nchimney differential pressure measurements. While convention recommends a minimum flow\nlength of 10 L/D, this was not possible within the current chimney configuration. Thus, their\ninstallation position will require their output signals to be treated as relative flow velocities\nbetween the dual chimney ducts, and not as absolute measurements of the flow velocity.\n\n\n\n\nFigure 35: Dwyer 160F pitot tubes installed along chimney ductwork. Right figure shows\nair ports that translate air velocity into fluid pressure\n\n   The pitot tubes are constructed from 304 SS, are characterized by a K-factor, Kp of 0.81,\nand claim an accuracy of ±2% of the full scale range, from 0 - 45 m/s. The full uncertainty,\nhowever, requires a propagation of error from their defining velocity correlation, Eqn. 6. As\nan example for baseline testing conditions, where measured differential pressures average 1.5\nPa and gas temperatures of 100 ◦ C, the calculated velocity would be 1.44 ± 0.12 m/s, or\n±8.3%.\n\n                                                    s\n                                                        2∆P\n                                      Vpitot = Kp                                             (6)\n                                                         ρ\n\nANL-ART-47                                     88\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n4.2.8     Gas Temperature\n\n\nWithin each riser, Type-K thermocouples are placed and extend to the length wise (10”)\nduct centerline, Figure 36. These thermocouples were purchased from ARI industries, and\nare of model T-22N-12BK8A-96(MOD). The inlet thermocouple is placed 0.75” from the\nbottom lip on the cold side, and the outlet placed 4.0” below the top lip from the hot side.\n\n\n\n\n               Figure 36: Placement of inlet and outlet instruments for riser\n\n\n\n\n   The outlet plenum features five instrumented insulation panels. The four adjacent ver-\ntical sides (north, south, east, and west) contain six embedded interior wall thermocouples,\nwhile the fifth top ceiling panel contains identical wall thermocouples in addition to seven\nthermocouple rakes for gas temperature measurements within the bulk volume of the plenum.\nEach rake measures six junctions along its length, extending a 170-cm along the total 188-cm\nheight of the plenum.\n\n                                               89                               ANL-ART-47\n\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                               August 2016\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47             90\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n\n                                               91              ANL-ART-47\n\f                                 Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                   August 2016\n\n\n\n\nFigure 37: Typical rake junction locations, placed along upper plenum top panel and ex-\ntending downward\n\n\nANL-ART-47                                 92\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n4.2.9      Luna Fiber Optic Temperature\n\nThe NSTF is outfitted for fiber optics, notably a distributed sensing system by Luna Tech-\nnologies that can provide the necessary data density for validation of CFD tools. Distributed\nfiber optic temperature sensing is a technique based upon distributed strain sensing and en-\nables the acquisition of thousands of temperature measurements from a single optical fiber\n[17]. The fiber temperature sensors used here exploit Rayleigh scattering losses from struc-\ntural inhomogeneities and impurities at the molecular level of ordinary telecom fibers [18].\nThe ODiSi A-10 from Luna Technologies has been used at other facilities at Argonne [19],\nand also was used for measurements in the NSTF.\n\n\n                            Table 18: Specifications of Luna ODiSi A-10\n                                    Parameter                       Specification\n                       Model                                               A10\n                       Maximum Sensing Length                             10 m\n                       Acquisition Rate1                                  5 Hz\n                       Minimum Sensor Spacing                            0.4 mm\n                       Minimum Gage Length2                               1 mm\n                       Wavelength Accuracy3                              1.5 pm\n                       Strain\n                        Range                                      ±13,000 µStrain\n                        Single Scan Pepeatability1 4 5               ±2 µStrain\n                       Temperature\n                        Range6                                       -50 to 300 ◦ C\n                        Single Scan Pepeatability1 4 5                  ±0.2 ◦ C\n\n\n\n\n   1\n       For the default measurement range of ±1,250 µStrain or ±200 ◦ C\n   2\n       Minimum gage length is achievable using the largest measurement range, having a single scan repeata-\nbility of ±17.0 µStrain or ±2.0 ◦ C\n     3\n       Accuracy maintained by an internal NIST - traceable HCN gas cell\n     4\n       Temperature and strain measurements are calculated from the spectral shift of scattered laser light.\nUsing the default conversion coefficients of 1 GHz = 0.8 ◦ C = 6.58 µStrain , the accuracy of temperature\nand strain are 0.15 ◦ C and 1.25 µStrain\n     5\n       For the default gage length of 1 cm\n     6\n       Based on material properties of the standard sensor: polyimide - coated, low - bend - loss optical fiber\n\n\n                                                      93                                         ANL-ART-47\n\f                                      Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                        August 2016\n\n\n   The fibers are made of 155 µm polyimide-coated single-mode commercial telecom fiber\n(Specialty Photonics CL POLY 1310) that has been tested for accuracy and repeatability","numLines":340,"startLine":2290,"totalLines":8102}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_0131WoWrsS3gsZMueg7QapJU","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6380,"cache_read_input_tokens":84189,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":6380},"output_tokens":5,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"47d9ec1e-27f2-4086-90f4-79a8199340a9","uuid":"c7697302-2c5e-43ce-816b-9f915fe44981","request_id":"req_011Ccd143i9bJeZfhGoiHEcE"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_0131WoWrsS3gsZMueg7QapJU","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01GrMozAK5FJ8QAAsb56bZXt","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/root/curator/source/report_full_text.txt","offset":2629,"limit":200},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6380,"cache_read_input_tokens":84189,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":6380},"output_tokens":5,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"47d9ec1e-27f2-4086-90f4-79a8199340a9","uuid":"83c4b950-0b41-45a1-bf08-966a8f3494f9","request_id":"req_011Ccd143i9bJeZfhGoiHEcE"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01GrMozAK5FJ8QAAsb56bZXt","type":"tool_result","content":"2629\t(Specialty Photonics CL POLY 1310) that has been tested for accuracy and repeatability\n2630\tto 150◦ C [17]. The system can generate temperature measurements every 10-mm at 1 Hz\n2631\tfor a total of 9,750 data point/s along each 7.5 m fiber. This initial installation has been\n2632\tlimited in facility inclusion because the measurement technique is relatively new; this is the\n2633\tfirst time it has been used in a large-scale test facility.\n2634\t\n2635\t\n2636\t\n2637\t\n2638\t          Figure 38: Luna fiber setup, near base mount and fed from inlet plenum\n2639\t\n2640\t\n2641\t\n2642\t\n2643\tANL-ART-47                                      94\n2644\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2645\tAugust 2016\n2646\t\n2647\t\n2648\t   Inherent in their design, these sensors are unable to distinguish between strain and tem-\n2649\tperature: either will influence the measured signal. To overcome this, fibers were installed\n2650\twithin 1/16” OD x 0.030 ID stainless steel capillaries, and secured (via heat shrink tubing)\n2651\tto only the head, nearest the insertion point, Figure 39.\n2652\t\n2653\t\n2654\t\n2655\t\n2656\t    Figure 39: Method of Luna fiber optic cables securement to capillary support tubes\n2657\t\n2658\t   This configuration allows the fiber to freely expand up the capillary when heated, thus\n2659\tpreventing any internal strain. Two riser ducts, #6 and #9, have been outfitted with these\n2660\tfibers: 6 on the outside wall and 5 within the gas space. These capillaries have been secured\n2661\tto the duct wall with spot welded bands, and within the gas space by routing through 8-32\n2662\tbrass fillister head screws.\n2663\t\n2664\t   The Luna fiber optic temperature measurement system requires a baseline calibration, as\n2665\tthe actual measurements are in the form of a temperature difference from a known baseline,\n2666\tand not an absolute value themselves. Thus, sixteen (x16) NIST-calibrated Type-K wall\n2667\tthermocouples have been positioned along the duct walls for purposes of calibrating the\n2668\tLUNA fiber optic cables during baselines. These have been placed in a similar fashion to the\n2669\twall capillaries - they extend along the length and are secured with spot welded bands to the\n2670\triser tubes. Furthermore, an in-house calibration was performed to derive a polynomial fit for\n2671\tas-measured LUNA temperature to actual physical temperatures (as reference to a calibrated\n2672\tthermocouple), Figure 40. Details of this calibration procedure have been published in earlier\n2673\tworks by the authors [19].\n2674\t\n2675\t                                               95                                 ANL-ART-47\n2676\t\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2677\t                                                                                      August 2016\n2678\t\n2679\t\n2680\t   Given the relatively recent introduction of these sensors to the industry, they cannot be\n2681\ttreated with the same maturity and reliability as conventional thermocouples. The successful\n2682\tinstallation and use requires a number of unique considerations. These are discussed briefly\n2683\tin Table 19, with further details available in other works by the authors [20].\n2684\t\n2685\t\n2686\t                      Table 19: Unique requirements for LUNA fibers\n2687\t\n2688\t       Practice              Remarks\n2689\t\n2690\t       Thermal expansion     For measurement of temperature, the installation\n2691\t                             method shall be free from mechanical induced strain\n2692\t                             caused by thermal expansion. Thus, the fibers must be\n2693\t                             positioned in a manner that allows free expansion and\n2694\t                             contraction without restriction\n2695\t       Calibration           A representative sample fiber, construction from the\n2696\t                             same fiber type and termination connectors, must be\n2697\t                             calibrated against a known reference to obtain reference\n2698\t                             curves\n2699\t       Humidity              Changes in humidity influence fiber performance, and\n2700\t                             must be accounted for during post-processing. Observa-\n2701\t                             tions from the NSTF testing program found, on average,\n2702\t                             a 0.15◦ C shift per % change in RH. This influence can\n2703\t                             be avoided if the fibers are housed in capillaries, purged\n2704\t                             with an inert gas and then sealed\n2705\t       Annealing             Upon final installation, the fibers must be annealed or\n2706\t                             cycled from room temperature, to the maximum antic-\n2707\t                             ipated operating point, and back to room temperature.\n2708\t                             This step is critical for collection of reliable, repeatable,\n2709\t                             and accurate data\n2710\t\n2711\t\n2712\t\n2713\t\n2714\tANL-ART-47                                    96\n2715\t\f                                                                                                          Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2716\t\n2717\t\n2718\t\n2719\t\n2720\t                                                                                                          August 2016\n2721\t97\n2722\t\n2723\t\n2724\t\n2725\t\n2726\t             Figure 40: Calibration curve for polyimide LUNA fibers, reference to thermocouple standard\n2727\t\n2728\t\n2729\t\n2730\t\n2731\tANL-ART-47\n2732\t\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2733\t                                                               August 2016\n2734\t\n2735\t\n2736\t\n2737\t\n2738\tANL-ART-47             98\n2739\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2740\tAugust 2016\n2741\t\n2742\t\n2743\t\n2744\t\n2745\t                                               99              ANL-ART-47\n2746\t\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2747\t                                                               August 2016\n2748\t\n2749\t\n2750\t\n2751\t\n2752\tANL-ART-47            100\n2753\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2754\tAugust 2016\n2755\t\n2756\t\n2757\t\n2758\t4.3      Heater Power Control\n2759\t\n2760\tThe heated section can be operated in one of three different modes: i) constant heat flux\n2761\t(21.6 kW/m2 maximum), ii) constant temperature (677◦ C maximum), or iii) an arbitrary\n2762\tcombination of these two modes. The 220 radiant heaters have been zoned into 40 control\n2763\tzones, 20 designated as the main and 20 as the guard zones, and produce a power distribution\n2764\tthat provides 80% of the total from the main and the remaining 20% from the guard zones.\n2765\tThe temperature and/or heat flux can be spatially controlled due to the fact that the heaters\n2766\tare zoned; the overall height is broken down into ten 67-cm long axial segments, while there\n2767\tare four azimuthal control zones at each axial elevation (two central zones plus two guard\n2768\theater zones) yielding 40 control zones in total.\n2769\t\n2770\t   The zones are powered by 40 Eurotherm EPower controllers, rated for 600 VAC at 50A.\n2771\tThe units maintain target power within ±1% of full scale during any moderate variations\n2772\tin line voltage, load impedance, and ambient temperature. Controllers perform real time\n2773\tmeasurements of actual delivered power via internal measurements of supply voltage and\n2774\tcurrent, which are both accurate to within ±1%. These have been configured in 5 primary\n2775\tbanks, each with 4 substations, and communicate directly with the central control station via\n2776\tthe iTools control software. Each of the 40 Eurotherm controllers and accompanying heated\n2777\tzones is hard wired to a Mini8 temperature controller that is programmed to a prescribed\n2778\ttemperature set point. Should the thermocouple at this zone reach the safety trip set points\n2779\tit will automatically trigger a signal to deactivate the related contactor and thus shut off all\n2780\tmain power to the individual zone. A top-level wiring diagram of the heater power system\n2781\tand control is provided in Figure 42.\n2782\t\n2783\t   The forty Eurotherm power controllers were initially configured for a Phase Angle mode\n2784\tof power control, which varies the amount of each cycle which is applied to the load by\n2785\tswitching the controller thermistor on part-way through the cycle. However, this method\n2786\tcomes with a number of drawbacks. First, high order harmonics are often introduced that\n2787\t\n2788\t                                               101                                 ANL-ART-47\n2789\t\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2790\t                                                                                      August 2016\n2791\t\n2792\t\n2793\tcan create noise on nearby signals. Furthermore, it can deliver high dI/dt (current spikes)\n2794\twhich may reduce the life of a heater. Thus, later portions of the testing program switched\n2795\tto a Burst Firing mode of power control. This is the ideal mode of control since it provides a\n2796\tstable and smooth means of power delivery. To allow accurate measurement and calibrated\n2797\tverification of the power controllers, a NIST calibrated oscilloscope was procured as part\n2798\tof the testing program. Modifications were made to the heater calibration panel which\n2799\tallows measurement of each of the forty circuits and monitoring of the waveform by the\n2800\toscilloscope, Figure 41. These waveforms can be readily read into LabVIEW and true power\n2801\tmeasurements calculated. The oscilloscope is Keysight model DSOX2004A, and features\n2802\t4-channels capable of sampling at rates up to 70MHz. The AC/DC current probe, model\n2803\tKeysight 1146B, allows measurement of amperage ranging from 0.5 - 40 amp, while the\n2804\tvoltage probe, model Keysight N2791A, allows measurement of voltages up to 700VAC.\n2805\t\n2806\t\n2807\t\n2808\t\n2809\t    Figure 41: Voltage (yellow) and current (green) phases from 480VAC heater circuit\n2810\t\n2811\t\n2812\t\n2813\t\n2814\tANL-ART-47                                   102\n2815\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2816\tAugust 2016\n2817\t                                                               Figure 42: Eurotherm power and Mini electrical wiring\n2818\t                                               103                                                                     ANL-ART-47\n2819\t\fThis page was intentionally left blank.\n2820\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n2821\tAugust 2016\n2822\t\n2823\t\n2824\t\n2825\t\n2826\tChapter 5\n2827\t\n2828\tTest Assembly Characterization"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"47d9ec1e-27f2-4086-90f4-79a8199340a9","uuid":"fcfa5638-5323-4548-a2da-d7a780476822","timestamp":"2026-07-02T09:34:11.342Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/root/curator/source/report_full_text.txt","content":"(Specialty Photonics CL POLY 1310) that has been tested for accuracy and repeatability\nto 150◦ C [17]. The system can generate temperature measurements every 10-mm at 1 Hz\nfor a total of 9,750 data point/s along each 7.5 m fiber. This initial installation has been\nlimited in facility inclusion because the measurement technique is relatively new; this is the\nfirst time it has been used in a large-scale test facility.\n\n\n\n\n          Figure 38: Luna fiber setup, near base mount and fed from inlet plenum\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47                                      94\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n   Inherent in their design, these sensors are unable to distinguish between strain and tem-\nperature: either will influence the measured signal. To overcome this, fibers were installed\nwithin 1/16” OD x 0.030 ID stainless steel capillaries, and secured (via heat shrink tubing)\nto only the head, nearest the insertion point, Figure 39.\n\n\n\n\n    Figure 39: Method of Luna fiber optic cables securement to capillary support tubes\n\n   This configuration allows the fiber to freely expand up the capillary when heated, thus\npreventing any internal strain. Two riser ducts, #6 and #9, have been outfitted with these\nfibers: 6 on the outside wall and 5 within the gas space. These capillaries have been secured\nto the duct wall with spot welded bands, and within the gas space by routing through 8-32\nbrass fillister head screws.\n\n   The Luna fiber optic temperature measurement system requires a baseline calibration, as\nthe actual measurements are in the form of a temperature difference from a known baseline,\nand not an absolute value themselves. Thus, sixteen (x16) NIST-calibrated Type-K wall\nthermocouples have been positioned along the duct walls for purposes of calibrating the\nLUNA fiber optic cables during baselines. These have been placed in a similar fashion to the\nwall capillaries - they extend along the length and are secured with spot welded bands to the\nriser tubes. Furthermore, an in-house calibration was performed to derive a polynomial fit for\nas-measured LUNA temperature to actual physical temperatures (as reference to a calibrated\nthermocouple), Figure 40. Details of this calibration procedure have been published in earlier\nworks by the authors [19].\n\n                                               95                                 ANL-ART-47\n\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                      August 2016\n\n\n   Given the relatively recent introduction of these sensors to the industry, they cannot be\ntreated with the same maturity and reliability as conventional thermocouples. The successful\ninstallation and use requires a number of unique considerations. These are discussed briefly\nin Table 19, with further details available in other works by the authors [20].\n\n\n                      Table 19: Unique requirements for LUNA fibers\n\n       Practice              Remarks\n\n       Thermal expansion     For measurement of temperature, the installation\n                             method shall be free from mechanical induced strain\n                             caused by thermal expansion. Thus, the fibers must be\n                             positioned in a manner that allows free expansion and\n                             contraction without restriction\n       Calibration           A representative sample fiber, construction from the\n                             same fiber type and termination connectors, must be\n                             calibrated against a known reference to obtain reference\n                             curves\n       Humidity              Changes in humidity influence fiber performance, and\n                             must be accounted for during post-processing. Observa-\n                             tions from the NSTF testing program found, on average,\n                             a 0.15◦ C shift per % change in RH. This influence can\n                             be avoided if the fibers are housed in capillaries, purged\n                             with an inert gas and then sealed\n       Annealing             Upon final installation, the fibers must be annealed or\n                             cycled from room temperature, to the maximum antic-\n                             ipated operating point, and back to room temperature.\n                             This step is critical for collection of reliable, repeatable,\n                             and accurate data\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47                                    96\n\f                                                                                                          Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                                          August 2016\n97\n\n\n\n\n             Figure 40: Calibration curve for polyimide LUNA fibers, reference to thermocouple standard\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47\n\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                               August 2016\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47             98\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n\n                                               99              ANL-ART-47\n\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                               August 2016\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47            100\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n4.3      Heater Power Control\n\nThe heated section can be operated in one of three different modes: i) constant heat flux\n(21.6 kW/m2 maximum), ii) constant temperature (677◦ C maximum), or iii) an arbitrary\ncombination of these two modes. The 220 radiant heaters have been zoned into 40 control\nzones, 20 designated as the main and 20 as the guard zones, and produce a power distribution\nthat provides 80% of the total from the main and the remaining 20% from the guard zones.\nThe temperature and/or heat flux can be spatially controlled due to the fact that the heaters\nare zoned; the overall height is broken down into ten 67-cm long axial segments, while there\nare four azimuthal control zones at each axial elevation (two central zones plus two guard\nheater zones) yielding 40 control zones in total.\n\n   The zones are powered by 40 Eurotherm EPower controllers, rated for 600 VAC at 50A.\nThe units maintain target power within ±1% of full scale during any moderate variations\nin line voltage, load impedance, and ambient temperature. Controllers perform real time\nmeasurements of actual delivered power via internal measurements of supply voltage and\ncurrent, which are both accurate to within ±1%. These have been configured in 5 primary\nbanks, each with 4 substations, and communicate directly with the central control station via\nthe iTools control software. Each of the 40 Eurotherm controllers and accompanying heated\nzones is hard wired to a Mini8 temperature controller that is programmed to a prescribed\ntemperature set point. Should the thermocouple at this zone reach the safety trip set points\nit will automatically trigger a signal to deactivate the related contactor and thus shut off all\nmain power to the individual zone. A top-level wiring diagram of the heater power system\nand control is provided in Figure 42.\n\n   The forty Eurotherm power controllers were initially configured for a Phase Angle mode\nof power control, which varies the amount of each cycle which is applied to the load by\nswitching the controller thermistor on part-way through the cycle. However, this method\ncomes with a number of drawbacks. First, high order harmonics are often introduced that\n\n                                               101                                 ANL-ART-47\n\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                      August 2016\n\n\ncan create noise on nearby signals. Furthermore, it can deliver high dI/dt (current spikes)\nwhich may reduce the life of a heater. Thus, later portions of the testing program switched\nto a Burst Firing mode of power control. This is the ideal mode of control since it provides a\nstable and smooth means of power delivery. To allow accurate measurement and calibrated\nverification of the power controllers, a NIST calibrated oscilloscope was procured as part\nof the testing program. Modifications were made to the heater calibration panel which\nallows measurement of each of the forty circuits and monitoring of the waveform by the\noscilloscope, Figure 41. These waveforms can be readily read into LabVIEW and true power\nmeasurements calculated. The oscilloscope is Keysight model DSOX2004A, and features\n4-channels capable of sampling at rates up to 70MHz. The AC/DC current probe, model\nKeysight 1146B, allows measurement of amperage ranging from 0.5 - 40 amp, while the\nvoltage probe, model Keysight N2791A, allows measurement of voltages up to 700VAC.\n\n\n\n\n    Figure 41: Voltage (yellow) and current (green) phases from 480VAC heater circuit\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47                                   102\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n                                                               Figure 42: Eurotherm power and Mini electrical wiring\n                                               103                                                                     ANL-ART-47\n\fThis page was intentionally left blank.\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n\nChapter 5\n\nTest Assembly Characterization","numLines":200,"startLine":2629,"totalLines":8102}}}
