{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01G3LXyMVfxqqXwDgDChwvwL","type":"tool_result","content":"3931\t6.4      Prototypic Testing Conditions\n3932\t\n3933\t6.4.1     GA-MHTGR Accident Scenario\n3934\t\n3935\tThe ability to accurately mimic the heat flux profile from the walls of a prototypic reactor\n3936\tpressure vessel (RPV) during an accident scenario is of high interest for the NSTF. Of\n3937\tthe proposed test series, one specific subset calls for a hypothetical accident scenario. The\n3938\tfollowing sections provide an overview of the methods used to determine the experimental\n3939\tboundary conditions in the NSTF.\n3940\t\n3941\tReference Basis\n3942\t\n3943\tThe full scale design for the NSTF is based off the General Atomics (GA) Modular High\n3944\tTemperature Gas Reactor (MHTGR), which has published openly available literature on\n3945\tthe heat removal specifications of their reactor cavity cooling system (RCCS). Section 5.5-\n3946\t16 in Amendment 13 of the Preliminary Safety Evaluation [10], provides details of these\n3947\toperating conditions, Figure 67. They specify that the RCCS steady-state performance\n3948\tduring normal plant operation imposes 700 kWt heat loss onto the RCCS. Then, during a\n3949\tDepressurized Conduction Cooldown (DCC) with Small Primary Leak, the time history of\n3950\tconditions imposed onto the RCCS are shown in Figure 68:\n3951\t\n3952\tIntegration to the NSTF\n3953\t\n3954\tThe data set for ‘RCCS Removal’ in Figure 68 was digitized, normalized to values of unity\n3955\talong the y-axis for peak values of 1.5 MWt , and fitted to a 10th order polynomial curve\n3956\tfit. The fitted coefficients are provided below, which require a power factor, Pscale , to yield\n3957\tengineering units in Watts. This data was then scaled according to the similarity parameters\n3958\tderived in earlier works [11], Table 25.\n3959\t\n3960\t\n3961\t Pwatt,electric = [C(00) + C(01)×tmin + . . . + C(10)×tmin 10 ]×Pscale\n3962\t Pscale = 90 (estimated to yield 56 kWt )\n3963\t\n3964\t\n3965\t\n3966\tANL-ART-47                                    152\n3967\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n3968\tAugust 2016\n3969\t\n3970\t\n3971\t\n3972\t\n3973\t  Figure 67: GA documented decay heat load during DCC with small primary leak [10]\n3974\t\n3975\t\n3976\t\n3977\t\n3978\t  Figure 68: Heat rate for RPV generation and RCCS removal, GA-MHTGR DCC [10]\n3979\t\n3980\t\n3981\t\n3982\t\n3983\t                                               153                       ANL-ART-47\n3984\t\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n3985\t                                                                                      August 2016\n3986\t\n3987\t\n3988\t\n3989\t     C(00) = 466.531039994;                        C(05) = -1.27606140005e-014;\n3990\t     C(01) = 0.078631095079;                       C(06) = 2.04789514471e-018;\n3991\t     C(02) = 0.000170562320568;                    C(07) = -2.08318254453e-022;\n3992\t     C(03) = -1.28449427566e-007;                  C(08) = 1.29530038954e-026;\n3993\t     C(04) = 5.09424812301e-011;                   C(09) = -4.48601180685e-031;\n3994\t Correlation coefficient is 0.999958043125\n3995\t Standard error about the line = 1.46350115015\n3996\t\n3997\t\n3998\t\n3999\t          Table 25: Scaling ratios and resulting values for full and NSTF scales\n4000\t               Parameter      Scaling Ratio            Full Scale    ANL 1/2 scale\n4001\t                                      √\n4002\t         Power (normal)         Q̇R = √lR                700 kWt        26.16 kWt\n4003\t         Power (DCC accident)   Q̇R = √ lR              1,500 kWt       56.07 kWt\n4004\t         Time                   TR∗ = lR                  120 hr         84.85 hr\n4005\t\n4006\t\n4007\t   Thus, the final resulting power profile that will be programmatically supplied by Lab-\n4008\tVIEW is shown below in Figure 69. A comparison of the digitized GA-MHTGR decay heat\n4009\tcurve (in black, left Y-axis) and the resulting NSTF decay heat curve (in red, right Y-axis)\n4010\tis shown as an overlay in Figure 70.\n4011\t\n4012\t\n4013\t\n4014\t\n4015\tANL-ART-47                                   154\n4016\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n4017\tAugust 2016\n4018\t\n4019\t\n4020\t\n4021\t\n4022\t                   Figure 69: Decay heat curve scaled for NSTF operation\n4023\t\n4024\t\n4025\t\n4026\t\n4027\t                 Figure 70: Overlay of GA-MHTGR and NSTF decay heat\n4028\t\n4029\t\n4030\t\n4031\t\n4032\t                                               155                         ANL-ART-47\n4033\t\f                                     Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n4034\t                                                                                       August 2016\n4035\t\n4036\t\n4037\t6.4.2     Cosine Power Profile\n4038\t\n4039\tThe ability to accurately mimic the heat flux profile from the walls of a prototypic reactor\n4040\tpressure vessel (RPV) is of high interest for the NSTF. Of the proposed test series, one\n4041\tspecific subset calls for a cosine power shaping profile along the axial direction.\n4042\t\n4043\t   Since the accident scenario specifies a depressurized condition with heat transfer primarily\n4044\tin the horizontal direction, the power density within the core can serve as a valid surrogate\n4045\tfor the heat flux distribution off the walls of the pressure vessel. Since the GA literature\n4046\tdoes not quantify the exact power profile, other available references provide information for\n4047\ta generic high temperature reactor (HTR). J.P. Simoneau [34] gives the axial distribution\n4048\tas a function of peak power for a HTR and H. Haque [35] provides a typical axial power\n4049\tdensity in the core for a generic MHTGR, Figure 71. Furthermore, to examine variations\n4050\tin the axial power profile during early life stages of a reactor core, an additional profile was\n4051\tdeveloped that featured a skew peaked near the bottom.\n4052\t\n4053\t\n4054\t\n4055\t\n4056\t                   Figure 71: Axial distribution for an typical HTR [42]\n4057\t\n4058\t\n4059\t\n4060\t   Each of these data sets was normalized to values of unity for both x- and y-scales,\n4061\tverified that their integration summed to unity, and compared against the curve of a true\n4062\tcosine distribution, Figure 72. The peak occurs at exactly the mid-point for the true cosine,\n4063\t0.575 for the MHTGR, which is similar to the suggested GA position of “just above the core\n4064\tmidplane” [10], and 0.25 for the bottom peaked cosine, a position that provides an lower\n4065\t\n4066\tANL-ART-47                                    156\n4067\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n4068\tAugust 2016\n4069\t\n4070\t\n4071\tbound on early life RPV power profiles. To apply these skews to the NSTF test operations,\n4072\tthe forty available control zones were fitted to this skewed cosine distribution by iterating\n4073\tover the available power levels while ensuring that the summation matched the expected\n4074\tintegral power. A summary of the as-tested peaking factors is provided in Table 26.\n4075\t\n4076\t\n4077\t\n4078\t                     Table 26: Peaking factors for cosine power profiles\n4079\t\n4080\t                     NSTF Zone         Peaking Factor (Pn / Plinear )\n4081\t                         -            Linear Bottom Peak Mid-Plane\n4082\t                         Zone1          1.0          1.225      0.498\n4083\t                         Zone2          1.0          1.325      0.831\n4084\t                         Zone3          1.0          1.425      1.010\n4085\t                         Zone4          1.0          1.375      1.140\n4086\t                         Zone5          1.0          1.275      1.248\n4087\t                         Zone6          1.0          1.150      1.313\n4088\t                         Zone7          1.0          0.900      1.294\n4089\t                         Zone8          1.0          0.650      1.157\n4090\t                         Zone9          1.0          0.450      0.904\n4091\t                         Zone10         1.0          0.225      0.605\n4092\t\n4093\t\n4094\t\n4095\t\n4096\t                                               157                               ANL-ART-47\n4097\t\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n4098\t                                                               August 2016\n4099\t                                                            Figure 72: Cosine power skews with linear reference, GA mid-plane and bottom peaked\n4100\tANL-ART-47            158\n4101\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n4102\tAugust 2016\n4103\t\n4104\t\n4105\t6.4.3     Azimuthal Power Skew\n4106\t\n4107\tDuring the air-based data review meeting, a discussion was made on the most probably\n4108\tfull-scale temperature effects on riser ducts within an reactor containment cavity with influ-\n4109\tences from skewed radiation view factors. Corner mounted riser tubes, along with physical\n4110\tobstructions such as RPV support mounts and steam lines, would cause a real RCCS to\n4111\texperience some level of power skew in the azimuthal direction. To examine this experimen-\n4112\ttally, an analyses of the radiation heat transfer view factors was performed for both MHTGR\n4113\tand NSTF cavities. The simulations were performed with the CFD software STAR-CCM+,\n4114\twhich includes a ray-tracing model to calculate the surface-to-surface view factors. As the\n4115\tobjective is to find the peak view factor per riser duct, all the surfaces (front, side, and back\n4116\tsurfaces) are combined for each riser. Based on STAR-CCM+ results, the view factors from\n4117\tthe vessel wall to the riser ducts are very non-uniform. The normalized peak view factor is\n4118\t∼1.84 for the peak riser duct, which is highlighted in Figure 73. However, it was found that\n4119\tone sidewall of this peak riser duct has a very large view factor facing the vessel wall, and\n4120\tlarge gaps exist in the array of riser ducts due to the vessel support structures and piping.\n4121\tBanks of riser ducts extend the length of the heated cavity, and are separate by gaps to\n4122\tavoid interfacing with RPV support structures. In consultation with industry experts [21],\n4123\tit was emphasized that the MHTGR and NGNP designs were only pursued to conceptual\n4124\tlevel, and therefore detailed design around cross ducts have not been addressed. In order\n4125\tto minimize azimuthal variation on vessel temperatures, it is necessary to have RCCS cool-\n4126\ting panels above the structures and would have been addressed during the preliminary and\n4127\tfinal phases of the designs. One likely approach is illustrated in Figure 75, which uses an\n4128\toctagonal plenum around the structures to connect the riser ducts from the bottom plenum\n4129\tto top plenum. Given that a full scale RCCS was never constructed by GA, this approach\n4130\tis a best-attempt guess and likely would exhibit some amount of differences from an actual\n4131\tinstallation.\n4132\t\n4133\t\n4134\t\n4135\t                                               159                                  ANL-ART-47\n4136\t\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n4137\t                                                               August 2016\n4138\t                                                             Figure 74: Group II\n4139\t                                                             Figure 73: Group I\n4140\tANL-ART-47            160\n4141\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n4142\tAugust 2016\n4143\t\n4144\t\n4145\t\n4146\t\n4147\t                 Figure 75: Schematic for air risers behind cross ducts [21]\n4148\t\n4149\t\n4150\t\n4151\t   Assuming that RCCS cooling panels will be more evenly distributed in the later phases\n4152\tof the design, the focus was then shifted towards the riser ducts with high view factors but\n4153\tnot next to those cross-duct structures. The top ten riser ducts with high view factors (but\n4154\taway from the cross-duct structures) are the closest bank immediately adjacent to the RPV,\n4155\tand exhibit normalized view factors ranging between 1.29 and 1.31. Note that this peaking\n4156\tfactor would be reduced if additional risers were placed in the current gap space.\n4157\t\n4158\t   The view factors in NSTF between the heated surface and the riser surfaces are also\n4159\tcalculated using the STAR-CCM+ ray-tracing model. It is found the peak normalized view\n4160\tfactors are 1.13 for the two central riser ducts (#6 and #7). However, the cavity sidewalls\n4161\t\n4162\t                                               161                              ANL-ART-47\n4163\t\f                                   Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n4164\t                                                                                     August 2016\n4165\t\n4166\t\n4167\t(with emissivity at 0.2 and not existing in the full-scale MHRGR cavity) in NSTF may\n4168\thave significant impacts on the actual power distribution among all the risers. The power\n4169\tdistributions among all the risers were calculated in the CFD simulation of one NSTF baseline\n4170\ttest, and the edge riser duct has a peaking factor ∼1.06.\n4171\t   NSTF only has two azimuthal zones to control the power distribution. To mimic the\n4172\tazimuthal power skew of the MHTGR cavity in NSTF, the needed power peaking would\n4173\tbe 1.31/1.06=1.24. A power peaking of 125% vs. 75% was thus used for the two zones of\n4174\theaters in NSTF.\n4175\t\n4176\t\n4177\t\n4178\t\n4179\tANL-ART-47                                   162\n4180\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n4181\tAugust 2016\n4182\t\n4183\t\n4184\t\n4185\t\n4186\tChapter 7\n4187\t\n4188\tTesting Results\n4189\tThe following chapter details the tests completed within the air-based NSTF program at\n4190\tArgonne. Spanning a 33-month period, a total of 2,250 hours of active test operations were"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"47d9ec1e-27f2-4086-90f4-79a8199340a9","uuid":"33f9eb36-e456-468a-9b13-c09b4da69c97","timestamp":"2026-07-02T09:34:24.071Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/root/curator/source/report_full_text.txt","content":"6.4      Prototypic Testing Conditions\n\n6.4.1     GA-MHTGR Accident Scenario\n\nThe ability to accurately mimic the heat flux profile from the walls of a prototypic reactor\npressure vessel (RPV) during an accident scenario is of high interest for the NSTF. Of\nthe proposed test series, one specific subset calls for a hypothetical accident scenario. The\nfollowing sections provide an overview of the methods used to determine the experimental\nboundary conditions in the NSTF.\n\nReference Basis\n\nThe full scale design for the NSTF is based off the General Atomics (GA) Modular High\nTemperature Gas Reactor (MHTGR), which has published openly available literature on\nthe heat removal specifications of their reactor cavity cooling system (RCCS). Section 5.5-\n16 in Amendment 13 of the Preliminary Safety Evaluation [10], provides details of these\noperating conditions, Figure 67. They specify that the RCCS steady-state performance\nduring normal plant operation imposes 700 kWt heat loss onto the RCCS. Then, during a\nDepressurized Conduction Cooldown (DCC) with Small Primary Leak, the time history of\nconditions imposed onto the RCCS are shown in Figure 68:\n\nIntegration to the NSTF\n\nThe data set for ‘RCCS Removal’ in Figure 68 was digitized, normalized to values of unity\nalong the y-axis for peak values of 1.5 MWt , and fitted to a 10th order polynomial curve\nfit. The fitted coefficients are provided below, which require a power factor, Pscale , to yield\nengineering units in Watts. This data was then scaled according to the similarity parameters\nderived in earlier works [11], Table 25.\n\n\n Pwatt,electric = [C(00) + C(01)×tmin + . . . + C(10)×tmin 10 ]×Pscale\n Pscale = 90 (estimated to yield 56 kWt )\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47                                    152\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n\n  Figure 67: GA documented decay heat load during DCC with small primary leak [10]\n\n\n\n\n  Figure 68: Heat rate for RPV generation and RCCS removal, GA-MHTGR DCC [10]\n\n\n\n\n                                               153                       ANL-ART-47\n\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                      August 2016\n\n\n\n     C(00) = 466.531039994;                        C(05) = -1.27606140005e-014;\n     C(01) = 0.078631095079;                       C(06) = 2.04789514471e-018;\n     C(02) = 0.000170562320568;                    C(07) = -2.08318254453e-022;\n     C(03) = -1.28449427566e-007;                  C(08) = 1.29530038954e-026;\n     C(04) = 5.09424812301e-011;                   C(09) = -4.48601180685e-031;\n Correlation coefficient is 0.999958043125\n Standard error about the line = 1.46350115015\n\n\n\n          Table 25: Scaling ratios and resulting values for full and NSTF scales\n               Parameter      Scaling Ratio            Full Scale    ANL 1/2 scale\n                                      √\n         Power (normal)         Q̇R = √lR                700 kWt        26.16 kWt\n         Power (DCC accident)   Q̇R = √ lR              1,500 kWt       56.07 kWt\n         Time                   TR∗ = lR                  120 hr         84.85 hr\n\n\n   Thus, the final resulting power profile that will be programmatically supplied by Lab-\nVIEW is shown below in Figure 69. A comparison of the digitized GA-MHTGR decay heat\ncurve (in black, left Y-axis) and the resulting NSTF decay heat curve (in red, right Y-axis)\nis shown as an overlay in Figure 70.\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47                                   154\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n\n                   Figure 69: Decay heat curve scaled for NSTF operation\n\n\n\n\n                 Figure 70: Overlay of GA-MHTGR and NSTF decay heat\n\n\n\n\n                                               155                         ANL-ART-47\n\f                                     Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                       August 2016\n\n\n6.4.2     Cosine Power Profile\n\nThe ability to accurately mimic the heat flux profile from the walls of a prototypic reactor\npressure vessel (RPV) is of high interest for the NSTF. Of the proposed test series, one\nspecific subset calls for a cosine power shaping profile along the axial direction.\n\n   Since the accident scenario specifies a depressurized condition with heat transfer primarily\nin the horizontal direction, the power density within the core can serve as a valid surrogate\nfor the heat flux distribution off the walls of the pressure vessel. Since the GA literature\ndoes not quantify the exact power profile, other available references provide information for\na generic high temperature reactor (HTR). J.P. Simoneau [34] gives the axial distribution\nas a function of peak power for a HTR and H. Haque [35] provides a typical axial power\ndensity in the core for a generic MHTGR, Figure 71. Furthermore, to examine variations\nin the axial power profile during early life stages of a reactor core, an additional profile was\ndeveloped that featured a skew peaked near the bottom.\n\n\n\n\n                   Figure 71: Axial distribution for an typical HTR [42]\n\n\n\n   Each of these data sets was normalized to values of unity for both x- and y-scales,\nverified that their integration summed to unity, and compared against the curve of a true\ncosine distribution, Figure 72. The peak occurs at exactly the mid-point for the true cosine,\n0.575 for the MHTGR, which is similar to the suggested GA position of “just above the core\nmidplane” [10], and 0.25 for the bottom peaked cosine, a position that provides an lower\n\nANL-ART-47                                    156\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\nbound on early life RPV power profiles. To apply these skews to the NSTF test operations,\nthe forty available control zones were fitted to this skewed cosine distribution by iterating\nover the available power levels while ensuring that the summation matched the expected\nintegral power. A summary of the as-tested peaking factors is provided in Table 26.\n\n\n\n                     Table 26: Peaking factors for cosine power profiles\n\n                     NSTF Zone         Peaking Factor (Pn / Plinear )\n                         -            Linear Bottom Peak Mid-Plane\n                         Zone1          1.0          1.225      0.498\n                         Zone2          1.0          1.325      0.831\n                         Zone3          1.0          1.425      1.010\n                         Zone4          1.0          1.375      1.140\n                         Zone5          1.0          1.275      1.248\n                         Zone6          1.0          1.150      1.313\n                         Zone7          1.0          0.900      1.294\n                         Zone8          1.0          0.650      1.157\n                         Zone9          1.0          0.450      0.904\n                         Zone10         1.0          0.225      0.605\n\n\n\n\n                                               157                               ANL-ART-47\n\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                               August 2016\n                                                            Figure 72: Cosine power skews with linear reference, GA mid-plane and bottom peaked\nANL-ART-47            158\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n6.4.3     Azimuthal Power Skew\n\nDuring the air-based data review meeting, a discussion was made on the most probably\nfull-scale temperature effects on riser ducts within an reactor containment cavity with influ-\nences from skewed radiation view factors. Corner mounted riser tubes, along with physical\nobstructions such as RPV support mounts and steam lines, would cause a real RCCS to\nexperience some level of power skew in the azimuthal direction. To examine this experimen-\ntally, an analyses of the radiation heat transfer view factors was performed for both MHTGR\nand NSTF cavities. The simulations were performed with the CFD software STAR-CCM+,\nwhich includes a ray-tracing model to calculate the surface-to-surface view factors. As the\nobjective is to find the peak view factor per riser duct, all the surfaces (front, side, and back\nsurfaces) are combined for each riser. Based on STAR-CCM+ results, the view factors from\nthe vessel wall to the riser ducts are very non-uniform. The normalized peak view factor is\n∼1.84 for the peak riser duct, which is highlighted in Figure 73. However, it was found that\none sidewall of this peak riser duct has a very large view factor facing the vessel wall, and\nlarge gaps exist in the array of riser ducts due to the vessel support structures and piping.\nBanks of riser ducts extend the length of the heated cavity, and are separate by gaps to\navoid interfacing with RPV support structures. In consultation with industry experts [21],\nit was emphasized that the MHTGR and NGNP designs were only pursued to conceptual\nlevel, and therefore detailed design around cross ducts have not been addressed. In order\nto minimize azimuthal variation on vessel temperatures, it is necessary to have RCCS cool-\ning panels above the structures and would have been addressed during the preliminary and\nfinal phases of the designs. One likely approach is illustrated in Figure 75, which uses an\noctagonal plenum around the structures to connect the riser ducts from the bottom plenum\nto top plenum. Given that a full scale RCCS was never constructed by GA, this approach\nis a best-attempt guess and likely would exhibit some amount of differences from an actual\ninstallation.\n\n\n\n                                               159                                  ANL-ART-47\n\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                               August 2016\n                                                             Figure 74: Group II\n                                                             Figure 73: Group I\nANL-ART-47            160\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n\n                 Figure 75: Schematic for air risers behind cross ducts [21]\n\n\n\n   Assuming that RCCS cooling panels will be more evenly distributed in the later phases\nof the design, the focus was then shifted towards the riser ducts with high view factors but\nnot next to those cross-duct structures. The top ten riser ducts with high view factors (but\naway from the cross-duct structures) are the closest bank immediately adjacent to the RPV,\nand exhibit normalized view factors ranging between 1.29 and 1.31. Note that this peaking\nfactor would be reduced if additional risers were placed in the current gap space.\n\n   The view factors in NSTF between the heated surface and the riser surfaces are also\ncalculated using the STAR-CCM+ ray-tracing model. It is found the peak normalized view\nfactors are 1.13 for the two central riser ducts (#6 and #7). However, the cavity sidewalls\n\n                                               161                              ANL-ART-47\n\f                                   Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                     August 2016\n\n\n(with emissivity at 0.2 and not existing in the full-scale MHRGR cavity) in NSTF may\nhave significant impacts on the actual power distribution among all the risers. The power\ndistributions among all the risers were calculated in the CFD simulation of one NSTF baseline\ntest, and the edge riser duct has a peaking factor ∼1.06.\n   NSTF only has two azimuthal zones to control the power distribution. To mimic the\nazimuthal power skew of the MHTGR cavity in NSTF, the needed power peaking would\nbe 1.31/1.06=1.24. A power peaking of 125% vs. 75% was thus used for the two zones of\nheaters in NSTF.\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47                                   162\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n\nChapter 7\n\nTesting Results\nThe following chapter details the tests completed within the air-based NSTF program at\nArgonne. Spanning a 33-month period, a total of 2,250 hours of active test operations were","numLines":260,"startLine":3931,"totalLines":8102}}}
