{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01A16j9nNtGdZ3Cm2BDigCQS","type":"tool_result","content":"4736\t7.3.1     Accident Scenario Testing - Run014\n4737\t\n4738\tThe following provides a summary of the operating parameters including results of NSTF’s\n4739\tRun014. The test objective was to simulate an accident scenario for the full scale GA-\n4740\tMHTGR. The test began by establishing steady-state at the normal operating heat load,\n4741\twhich defines a full scale power of 700 kWt , or 26.16 kWt in the 1/2 scale NSTF.\n4742\t\n4743\t   Upon reaching stable operation and meeting the acceptance criteria, the accident se-\n4744\tquence was initiated and the power followed a varying time history representative of the\n4745\tGA-MHTGR decay heat curve. The test was concluded after reaching the peak power,\n4746\twhich occured after 120 hours at 1.5 MWt in the full scale, or 84.85 hours at 56.07 kWt in\n4747\tthe NSTF. A dated log of the primary procedural test events is provided below in Table 34.\n4748\tNo unusual or unplanned events that occurred throughout the duration of the test.\n4749\t\n4750\t                   Table 34: Test log for Run014 - GA-MHTGR summer\n4751\t   Date            Time                                        Action\n4752\t 4/6/2015        12h10      Zero flow verification, saved LabVIEW acquisition\n4753\t 4/6/2015        12h23      LUNA baseline calibration, saved LabVIEW acquisition\n4754\t 4/6/2015        12h29      Began data logging on LabVIEW, start of test operations\n4755\t 4/6/2015     12h31 - 14h26 Power ramp from 0 to 42.00 kWe\n4756\t 4/7/2015     05h28 - 9h28 First steady-state period, 25.06 kWt measured in test section\n4757\t 4/7/2015        09h57      Accident sequence initiation, reset clock to taccident = 0\n4758\t 4/11/2015       00h28      Peak power condition reached, taccident = 91.9hr, P = 54.45 kWt\n4759\t 4/11/2015       18h40      Accident conclusion, taccident = 110.1hr, ttotal = 127.1 hr\n4760\t 4/11/2015    18h40 - 22h46 Power ramp from 89.15 to 0 kWe\n4761\t 4/11/2015       22h51      Test conclusion. taccident of 114.27hr, ttotal = 130.37hr\n4762\t\n4763\t\n4764\t   Acceptance criteria were established both pre-accident steady-state and mid-accident\n4765\tpeak power. Both were met upon review of immediately recent data, which showed a stable\n4766\tthermal energy balance within the heated test section for a period that did not change more\n4767\tthan ±5%. A summary is provided in Table 35.\n4768\t\n4769\t   Overall, the facility was able to follow the full decay heat curve while successfully main-\n4770\t\n4771\t                                               183                                ANL-ART-47\n4772\t\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n4773\t                                                                                      August 2016\n4774\t\n4775\t             Table 35: Summary of steady parameters for GA-MHTGR Run014\n4776\t                                           Steady-State      Peak Accident\n4777\t                 Span                        17 - 23 hr        100 - 116 hr\n4778\t                 Electric power, kWe           42.08               90.07\n4779\t                 Test sect. power, kWt         25.06               54.49\n4780\t                 System flow rate, kg/s        0.499               0.585\n4781\t                 Riser ∆T, ◦ C                 49.44               90.32\n4782\t                 Front heated plate, ◦ C      275.32              408.72\n4783\t                 Ceramic heaters, ◦ C          404.13             591.26\n4784\t\n4785\t\n4786\ttaining the vessel wall at safe temperatures (408 ◦ C at peak decay heat removal as measured\n4787\tin the NSTF). Due to the long time scales of the power profile, heat removal by the RCCS\n4788\tfollowed closely the decay power from the heated source. Perturbations in the system flow\n4789\twere observed due to meteorological fluctuations, which were most pronounced in the system\n4790\tflow rate and heated temperature rise. Furthermore, the test window saw dominating winds\n4791\tin the NE direction during the first half, which then shifted to westward in the second half.\n4792\tThe impact on the test facility was an asymmetric flow among the parallel chimney ducts,\n4793\twhich required the operators to use engineering controls (i.e. dampers along the chimney\n4794\tstacks) to maintain stable air flow out of the dual exhaust chimneys. Wind gusts, measured\n4795\tat speeds up to 21.9 m/s, or 49 mph, created strong perturbations near the outlet chim-\n4796\tneys. If manual intervention was not made, experience from operating the NSTF suggests\n4797\twith high confidence that flow reversals would have occurred and resulted in degraded heat\n4798\tremoval performance. All modifications via the duct dampers were logged and included in\n4799\tthe formal data suite.\n4800\t   With completion of post-test data verification procedures and review of generated data\n4801\tsets, the test was found to be fully within the defined scope and set of procedures and thus\n4802\tis classified as successful and will be submitted for qualification for Type-A data.\n4803\t\n4804\t\n4805\t\n4806\t\n4807\tANL-ART-47                                   184\n4808\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n4809\tAugust 2016\n4810\t\n4811\t\n4812\t7.3.2     Accident Weather Influences - Run018\n4813\t\n4814\tThe GA-MHTGR accident scenario was first performed during Run014 during winter con-\n4815\tditions, which saw temperatures averaging near 10 ◦ C (span of 2.9 - 22.5 ◦ C). To examine\n4816\tthe influences from weather, this test was repeated in Run018 during hot summer weather\n4817\twhich saw temperatures averaging 25 ◦ C (span of 19.1 - 32.1 ◦ C). A detailed summary of the\n4818\toperating meteorological conditions over the course of both testing windows is provided in\n4819\tTable 36. Examining the system thermal hydraulic behavior, they performed and exhibited\n4820\tvery similar trends. However, while the electric and thermal powers were nearly identical,\n4821\tthe elevated ambient temperatures had a strong impact on absolute values of the system\n4822\tflow rates and gas temperatures. A summary is provided in Table 37.\n4823\t\n4824\t\n4825\tTable 36: Summary of weather conditions for two GA-MHTGR tests, winter and summer\n4826\t                                             Run014 - Winter        Run018 - Summer\n4827\t                                             Average     Span       Average     Span\n4828\t                    Rain fall      mm         0.00       0-1.02      0.00       0-0.76\n4829\t                Rain fall rate   mm/hr        0.25        0-63       0.17       0-41.4\n4830\t\n4831\t         Barometric pressure        mm       760.06    748-769.5    762.32    754.8-765.2\n4832\t          Outdoor humidity           %        81.48      29-98      79.05        46-96\n4833\t\n4834\t                                     ◦\n4835\t         Indoor temperature              C    22.58    20.4-28.2     29.23     25.2-33.9"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"47d9ec1e-27f2-4086-90f4-79a8199340a9","uuid":"7e4f5fa0-c217-43c3-8523-10ac3d1e8bea","timestamp":"2026-07-02T09:35:15.802Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/root/curator/source/report_full_text.txt","content":"7.3.1     Accident Scenario Testing - Run014\n\nThe following provides a summary of the operating parameters including results of NSTF’s\nRun014. The test objective was to simulate an accident scenario for the full scale GA-\nMHTGR. The test began by establishing steady-state at the normal operating heat load,\nwhich defines a full scale power of 700 kWt , or 26.16 kWt in the 1/2 scale NSTF.\n\n   Upon reaching stable operation and meeting the acceptance criteria, the accident se-\nquence was initiated and the power followed a varying time history representative of the\nGA-MHTGR decay heat curve. The test was concluded after reaching the peak power,\nwhich occured after 120 hours at 1.5 MWt in the full scale, or 84.85 hours at 56.07 kWt in\nthe NSTF. A dated log of the primary procedural test events is provided below in Table 34.\nNo unusual or unplanned events that occurred throughout the duration of the test.\n\n                   Table 34: Test log for Run014 - GA-MHTGR summer\n   Date            Time                                        Action\n 4/6/2015        12h10      Zero flow verification, saved LabVIEW acquisition\n 4/6/2015        12h23      LUNA baseline calibration, saved LabVIEW acquisition\n 4/6/2015        12h29      Began data logging on LabVIEW, start of test operations\n 4/6/2015     12h31 - 14h26 Power ramp from 0 to 42.00 kWe\n 4/7/2015     05h28 - 9h28 First steady-state period, 25.06 kWt measured in test section\n 4/7/2015        09h57      Accident sequence initiation, reset clock to taccident = 0\n 4/11/2015       00h28      Peak power condition reached, taccident = 91.9hr, P = 54.45 kWt\n 4/11/2015       18h40      Accident conclusion, taccident = 110.1hr, ttotal = 127.1 hr\n 4/11/2015    18h40 - 22h46 Power ramp from 89.15 to 0 kWe\n 4/11/2015       22h51      Test conclusion. taccident of 114.27hr, ttotal = 130.37hr\n\n\n   Acceptance criteria were established both pre-accident steady-state and mid-accident\npeak power. Both were met upon review of immediately recent data, which showed a stable\nthermal energy balance within the heated test section for a period that did not change more\nthan ±5%. A summary is provided in Table 35.\n\n   Overall, the facility was able to follow the full decay heat curve while successfully main-\n\n                                               183                                ANL-ART-47\n\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                      August 2016\n\n             Table 35: Summary of steady parameters for GA-MHTGR Run014\n                                           Steady-State      Peak Accident\n                 Span                        17 - 23 hr        100 - 116 hr\n                 Electric power, kWe           42.08               90.07\n                 Test sect. power, kWt         25.06               54.49\n                 System flow rate, kg/s        0.499               0.585\n                 Riser ∆T, ◦ C                 49.44               90.32\n                 Front heated plate, ◦ C      275.32              408.72\n                 Ceramic heaters, ◦ C          404.13             591.26\n\n\ntaining the vessel wall at safe temperatures (408 ◦ C at peak decay heat removal as measured\nin the NSTF). Due to the long time scales of the power profile, heat removal by the RCCS\nfollowed closely the decay power from the heated source. Perturbations in the system flow\nwere observed due to meteorological fluctuations, which were most pronounced in the system\nflow rate and heated temperature rise. Furthermore, the test window saw dominating winds\nin the NE direction during the first half, which then shifted to westward in the second half.\nThe impact on the test facility was an asymmetric flow among the parallel chimney ducts,\nwhich required the operators to use engineering controls (i.e. dampers along the chimney\nstacks) to maintain stable air flow out of the dual exhaust chimneys. Wind gusts, measured\nat speeds up to 21.9 m/s, or 49 mph, created strong perturbations near the outlet chim-\nneys. If manual intervention was not made, experience from operating the NSTF suggests\nwith high confidence that flow reversals would have occurred and resulted in degraded heat\nremoval performance. All modifications via the duct dampers were logged and included in\nthe formal data suite.\n   With completion of post-test data verification procedures and review of generated data\nsets, the test was found to be fully within the defined scope and set of procedures and thus\nis classified as successful and will be submitted for qualification for Type-A data.\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47                                   184\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n7.3.2     Accident Weather Influences - Run018\n\nThe GA-MHTGR accident scenario was first performed during Run014 during winter con-\nditions, which saw temperatures averaging near 10 ◦ C (span of 2.9 - 22.5 ◦ C). To examine\nthe influences from weather, this test was repeated in Run018 during hot summer weather\nwhich saw temperatures averaging 25 ◦ C (span of 19.1 - 32.1 ◦ C). A detailed summary of the\noperating meteorological conditions over the course of both testing windows is provided in\nTable 36. Examining the system thermal hydraulic behavior, they performed and exhibited\nvery similar trends. However, while the electric and thermal powers were nearly identical,\nthe elevated ambient temperatures had a strong impact on absolute values of the system\nflow rates and gas temperatures. A summary is provided in Table 37.\n\n\nTable 36: Summary of weather conditions for two GA-MHTGR tests, winter and summer\n                                             Run014 - Winter        Run018 - Summer\n                                             Average     Span       Average     Span\n                    Rain fall      mm         0.00       0-1.02      0.00       0-0.76\n                Rain fall rate   mm/hr        0.25        0-63       0.17       0-41.4\n\n         Barometric pressure        mm       760.06    748-769.5    762.32    754.8-765.2\n          Outdoor humidity           %        81.48      29-98      79.05        46-96\n\n                                     ◦\n         Indoor temperature              C    22.58    20.4-28.2     29.23     25.2-33.9","numLines":100,"startLine":4736,"totalLines":8102}}}
