{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_018f8wJXKdF7hDz6LGFqtmn8","type":"tool_result","content":"5168\t7.4      Off-normal Scenarios\n5169\t\n5170\t7.4.1     Blocked Riser Channels - Run015\n5171\t\n5172\tThe following provides a summary of the operating parameters and test conditions of NSTF’s\n5173\tRun015. The test objective was to examine system response and heat removal performance\n5174\twith blocked riser channels. The test began by establishing steady-state at the normal\n5175\toperating heat load, which defines a full scale power of 700 kWt , or 26.16 kWt in the 1/2\n5176\tscale NSTF. Then, three stages of degraded operation were initiated at 16.6%, 33.3%, and\n5177\t50% blockage, which were accomplished by physically closing 2, 4, and 6 riser channels,\n5178\trespectively. The closures were done via mechanical flaps positioned at the inlet of each riser.\n5179\tThe four stages are visually depicted in Figure 95, and the physical means for achieving the\n5180\tblockages is shown in Figure 96.\n5181\t\n5182\t\n5183\t\n5184\t\n5185\tFigure 95: Four stages of riser blockages during Run015, red arrows indicate heated surface\n5186\t\n5187\t\n5188\t\n5189\t\n5190\tANL-ART-47                                    196\n5191\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n5192\tAugust 2016\n5193\t\n5194\t\n5195\t\n5196\t\n5197\t             Figure 96: Closure flaps used to remotely actuate a riser blockage\n5198\t\n5199\t\n5200\t\n5201\t\n5202\t   Each stage was allowed to reach stable, steady-state flow conditions for a minimum period\n5203\tof 6 hours. Time averaged values over these 6 hours were then used to meet established\n5204\tacceptance criteria, which defined system parameters that did not vary more than 5% over\n5205\tthe 6 hour period. A dated log of the primary procedural test events is provided below in\n5206\tTable 44. No unusual or unplanned events occurred throughout the duration of the test.\n5207\tAcceptance criteria were established for each of the four steady state periods: full open,\n5208\t2 risers blocked, 4 risers blocked, and 6 riser blocked. These criteria were verified with\n5209\tobservations of live test data by the test operator (later confirmed by raw data processing),\n5210\twhich showed a stable thermal energy balance within the heated test section for a period\n5211\tthat did not change more than ±5% over a 6 hour window. A summary is provided in Table\n5212\t45. The results are also shown as trends for the response of the system flow rate, both\n5213\tabsolute as a function in time, Figure 97, and per step change, or percent change from one\n5214\tstage to the next, Figure 98. With completion of post-test data verification procedures and\n5215\treview of generated data sets, the test was found to be fully within the defined scope and\n5216\tset of procedures and thus is classified as successful.\n5217\t\n5218\t                                               197                                ANL-ART-47\n5219\t\f                                   Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n5220\t                                                                                     August 2016\n5221\t\n5222\t\n5223\t   While the total system flow rate was dramatically reduced at each stage, the facility’s\n5224\tperformance remained robust and continued to perform its heat removal function well. The\n5225\theated plate temperature, simulating the walls of a RPV, averaged 279 ◦ C for the normal,\n5226\tfully open operation, and only increased to 282, 288, and 292 ◦ C at each respective stage.\n5227\tThese minor rises in RPV temperature suggest high confidence in the system’s ability to\n5228\tmaintain high heat removal performance even in the event of blocked riser channels.\n5229\t\n5230\t        Table 44: Test log for Run015 - Performance testing with block riser tubes\n5231\t    Date           Time                                  Action\n5232\t  5/19/2015    10h32      Zero flow verification, saved LabVIEW acquisition\n5233\t  5/19/2015    10h48      LUNA baseline calibration, saved LabVIEW acquisition\n5234\t  5/19/2015    10h55      Began data logging on LabVIEW, start of test operations\n5235\t  5/19/2015 11h00 - 13h00 Power ramp from 0 to 42.00 kWe\n5236\t  5/20/2015    13h43      Closure of Risers #2 & #3\n5237\t  5/21/2015    09h46      Closure of Risers #10 & #12\n5238\t  5/22/2015    09h02      Closure of Risers #5 & #8\n5239\t  5/22/2015 18h55 - 21h25 Power ramp from 42.00 to 0 kWe\n5240\t  5/22/2015    21h48      Test conclusion, ttotal = 82.88 hr\n5241\t\n5242\t\n5243\tTable 45: Acceptance criteria and system parameter summary over four stages in Run015\n5244\t                              Stage #0    Stage #1       Stage #2           Stage #3\n5245\t    Riser Blockage, %            0%         16.60%         33.30%               50%\n5246\t    Risers Blocked                 -          2,3       (2,3) + 10,12    (2,3,10,12) + 5,8\n5247\t    Span, run time hr          20 - 26      32 - 46        52 - 65            74 - 80\n5248\t    Electric power, kWe           42           42            41.99               42\n5249\t    Test sect. power, kWt       24.78        26.68          26.16               25.17\n5250\t    Sys. flow rate, kg/s        0.459         0.42           0.342              0.287\n5251\t    Riser ∆T, ◦ C                53.6        54.92           59.41              63.49\n5252\t    Front heated plate, ◦ C    278.93       282.32          288.17             291.96\n5253\t    Ceramic heaters, ◦ C       405.96       408.27          412.34             414.88\n5254\t\n5255\t\n5256\t\n5257\t\n5258\tANL-ART-47                                  198\n5259\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n5260\tAugust 2016\n5261\t                                                               Figure 97: Time history of system flow rate with various blockage stages indicated\n5262\t                                               199                                                                                                  ANL-ART-47\n5263\t\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n5264\t                                                               August 2016\n5265\t                                                    Figure 98: Step change in flow rate as a function of riser blockage\n5266\tANL-ART-47            200\n5267\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n5268\tAugust 2016\n5269\t\n5270\t\n5271\t7.4.2     Heavy-gas Ingress - Run027\n5272\t\n5273\tOne hypothetical accident scenario is the ingress of a non-air gas into an operating RCCS.\n5274\tSuch an event must be considered given the proximity of planned HTGR installations to\n5275\tchemical processing plants. To examine the performance of an RCCS under such a scenario,\n5276\ta test was devised and performed with the NSTF at Argonne. The objective of this test was\n5277\tto first establish steady-state, normal operating conditions in the NSTF with air and then\n5278\tintroduce a transition of the inlet gas from air to a non-air gas, while observing the impact\n5279\ton the system behavior.\n5280\t\n5281\t   Carbon dioxide (CO2) was initially proposed as a candidate for the non-air gas, however\n5282\tdangers of hypercapnia posed an unnecessary risk to involved personnel and ultimately argon\n5283\twas selected for use during the test. The risk of asphyxiation was still present however, and\n5284\trequired laboratory specific attention to safety and oxygen monitoring, which were addressed\n5285\tby a revision to the projects WPC for testing operations.\n5286\t\n5287\t   The acceptance criteria defined by the testing team, established prior to testing execution,\n5288\tdefined a minimum available gas volume of 1,000 cu-ft, at an average bulk concentration of\n5289\tless than 1% oxygen (95+% argon). A comparison of physical properties between ultra-high\n5290\tpurity argon (the gas used for the NSTF testing) and dry air, at both STP (0 ◦ C and 101.325\n5291\tkPa) and elevated temperatures (100 ◦ C, 101.325 kPa) is provided below in Tables 46 and\n5292\t47, respectively.\n5293\t\n5294\t     Table 46: Physical Properties of Dry Air and Argon at STP (0 ◦ C, 101.325 kPa)\n5295\t\n5296\t                                                      Air (dry)   Argon     % diff.\n5297\t          Ar Molecular weight       g/mol                28.970    39.948    31.9%\n5298\t          ρ  Density                kg/m3                 1.292    1.784     31.9%\n5299\t          Cp Heat capacity         kJ/kg-K               1.005      0.522    63.3%\n5300\t          k  Thermal conductivity  W/m-K                 0.024      0.016    38.6%\n5301\t          Pr Prandtl                   -                  0.711     0.665     6.7%\n5302\t          µ  Dynamic viscosity    106 Ns/m2              17.220    21.020    19.9%\n5303\t\n5304\t\n5305\t\n5306\t\n5307\t                                               201                                ANL-ART-47\n5308\t\f                                     Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n5309\t                                                                                       August 2016\n5310\t\n5311\t        Table 47: Physical Properties of Elevated Temperature Dry Air and Argon\n5312\t                                               Air (dry)                     Argon\n5313\t                                       0 ◦C    100 ◦ C change      0 ◦C    100 ◦ C % change\n5314\t Ar   Molecular weight g/mol          28.970   28.970      0.0% 39.948     39.948          0.0%\n5315\t ρ    Density           kg/m3         1.292     0.946    -26.8% 1.784       1.305        -26.8%\n5316\t Cp   Heat capacity     kJ/kg-K       1.005     1.012      0.7% 0.522       0.521         -0.2%\n5317\t k    Thermal conduct. W/m-K           0.024    0.032     29.8% 0.016       0.021         29.3%\n5318\t Pr   Prandtl           -              0.711    0.701     -1.5% 0.665       0.664         -0.2%\n5319\t µ    Dynamic viscosity 106 N s/m2    17.220   21.900     27.2% 21.020     27.170         29.3%\n5320\t\n5321\t\n5322\t\n5323\tGas Enclosure Design\n5324\t\n5325\tA successful execution of the proposed testing plan required unique considerations to ensure\n5326\tthe introduction of only a single variable: gas composition. Due to the sensitivity of natural\n5327\tcirculation systems, changes in parameters such as pressure, temperature, geometry, among\n5328\tothers, would introduce unwanted influences that would reduce the clarity of the observed\n5329\tbehavior and confidence in the results. Thus, significant attention was given to the design\n5330\tof the apparatus and procedure of the transition sequence. An enclosure was constructed on\n5331\tthe Bldg. 308 floor, directly above the downcomer inlet of the NSTF, that had the following\n5332\tfeatures:\n5333\t\n5334\t  1. Contained a non-air gas volume of approximately 1,000 cu-ft\n5335\t  2. Ability to operate in ‘air by-pass’ and ‘argon ingress’ modes\n5336\t  3. Identical inlet flow areas for both modes\n5337\t  4. Transition between modes would not, even in a transient, cut-off air or gas flow\n5338\t\n5339\t   The enclosure itself measured 7x10x15 feet, and was constructed from a uni-strut frame\n5340\tand wrapped in two-layers of 6-mil (0.006-inch), moisture-resistance low-density polyethlyene\n5341\t(LDPE) film. A normal-operation air duct (24-inch diameter) was positioned within the\n5342\tcenter of the enclosure, while four by-pass valves (12-inch diameter each) were positioned\n5343\tat each of the four top corners. The 24-inch air-duct featured a mating seal at the base\n5344\tof the enclosure, and under normal-operation allowed the NSTF to draw in fresh ambient\n5345\tair without introducing argon into the facility. During the transition sequence, the four\n5346\t\n5347\tANL-ART-47                                     202"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"47d9ec1e-27f2-4086-90f4-79a8199340a9","uuid":"4f216c5d-083b-4250-8a04-e3ce885bd48e","timestamp":"2026-07-02T09:35:54.588Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/root/curator/source/report_full_text.txt","content":"7.4      Off-normal Scenarios\n\n7.4.1     Blocked Riser Channels - Run015\n\nThe following provides a summary of the operating parameters and test conditions of NSTF’s\nRun015. The test objective was to examine system response and heat removal performance\nwith blocked riser channels. The test began by establishing steady-state at the normal\noperating heat load, which defines a full scale power of 700 kWt , or 26.16 kWt in the 1/2\nscale NSTF. Then, three stages of degraded operation were initiated at 16.6%, 33.3%, and\n50% blockage, which were accomplished by physically closing 2, 4, and 6 riser channels,\nrespectively. The closures were done via mechanical flaps positioned at the inlet of each riser.\nThe four stages are visually depicted in Figure 95, and the physical means for achieving the\nblockages is shown in Figure 96.\n\n\n\n\nFigure 95: Four stages of riser blockages during Run015, red arrows indicate heated surface\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47                                    196\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n\n             Figure 96: Closure flaps used to remotely actuate a riser blockage\n\n\n\n\n   Each stage was allowed to reach stable, steady-state flow conditions for a minimum period\nof 6 hours. Time averaged values over these 6 hours were then used to meet established\nacceptance criteria, which defined system parameters that did not vary more than 5% over\nthe 6 hour period. A dated log of the primary procedural test events is provided below in\nTable 44. No unusual or unplanned events occurred throughout the duration of the test.\nAcceptance criteria were established for each of the four steady state periods: full open,\n2 risers blocked, 4 risers blocked, and 6 riser blocked. These criteria were verified with\nobservations of live test data by the test operator (later confirmed by raw data processing),\nwhich showed a stable thermal energy balance within the heated test section for a period\nthat did not change more than ±5% over a 6 hour window. A summary is provided in Table\n45. The results are also shown as trends for the response of the system flow rate, both\nabsolute as a function in time, Figure 97, and per step change, or percent change from one\nstage to the next, Figure 98. With completion of post-test data verification procedures and\nreview of generated data sets, the test was found to be fully within the defined scope and\nset of procedures and thus is classified as successful.\n\n                                               197                                ANL-ART-47\n\f                                   Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                     August 2016\n\n\n   While the total system flow rate was dramatically reduced at each stage, the facility’s\nperformance remained robust and continued to perform its heat removal function well. The\nheated plate temperature, simulating the walls of a RPV, averaged 279 ◦ C for the normal,\nfully open operation, and only increased to 282, 288, and 292 ◦ C at each respective stage.\nThese minor rises in RPV temperature suggest high confidence in the system’s ability to\nmaintain high heat removal performance even in the event of blocked riser channels.\n\n        Table 44: Test log for Run015 - Performance testing with block riser tubes\n    Date           Time                                  Action\n  5/19/2015    10h32      Zero flow verification, saved LabVIEW acquisition\n  5/19/2015    10h48      LUNA baseline calibration, saved LabVIEW acquisition\n  5/19/2015    10h55      Began data logging on LabVIEW, start of test operations\n  5/19/2015 11h00 - 13h00 Power ramp from 0 to 42.00 kWe\n  5/20/2015    13h43      Closure of Risers #2 & #3\n  5/21/2015    09h46      Closure of Risers #10 & #12\n  5/22/2015    09h02      Closure of Risers #5 & #8\n  5/22/2015 18h55 - 21h25 Power ramp from 42.00 to 0 kWe\n  5/22/2015    21h48      Test conclusion, ttotal = 82.88 hr\n\n\nTable 45: Acceptance criteria and system parameter summary over four stages in Run015\n                              Stage #0    Stage #1       Stage #2           Stage #3\n    Riser Blockage, %            0%         16.60%         33.30%               50%\n    Risers Blocked                 -          2,3       (2,3) + 10,12    (2,3,10,12) + 5,8\n    Span, run time hr          20 - 26      32 - 46        52 - 65            74 - 80\n    Electric power, kWe           42           42            41.99               42\n    Test sect. power, kWt       24.78        26.68          26.16               25.17\n    Sys. flow rate, kg/s        0.459         0.42           0.342              0.287\n    Riser ∆T, ◦ C                53.6        54.92           59.41              63.49\n    Front heated plate, ◦ C    278.93       282.32          288.17             291.96\n    Ceramic heaters, ◦ C       405.96       408.27          412.34             414.88\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47                                  198\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n                                                               Figure 97: Time history of system flow rate with various blockage stages indicated\n                                               199                                                                                                  ANL-ART-47\n\f             Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                               August 2016\n                                                    Figure 98: Step change in flow rate as a function of riser blockage\nANL-ART-47            200\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n7.4.2     Heavy-gas Ingress - Run027\n\nOne hypothetical accident scenario is the ingress of a non-air gas into an operating RCCS.\nSuch an event must be considered given the proximity of planned HTGR installations to\nchemical processing plants. To examine the performance of an RCCS under such a scenario,\na test was devised and performed with the NSTF at Argonne. The objective of this test was\nto first establish steady-state, normal operating conditions in the NSTF with air and then\nintroduce a transition of the inlet gas from air to a non-air gas, while observing the impact\non the system behavior.\n\n   Carbon dioxide (CO2) was initially proposed as a candidate for the non-air gas, however\ndangers of hypercapnia posed an unnecessary risk to involved personnel and ultimately argon\nwas selected for use during the test. The risk of asphyxiation was still present however, and\nrequired laboratory specific attention to safety and oxygen monitoring, which were addressed\nby a revision to the projects WPC for testing operations.\n\n   The acceptance criteria defined by the testing team, established prior to testing execution,\ndefined a minimum available gas volume of 1,000 cu-ft, at an average bulk concentration of\nless than 1% oxygen (95+% argon). A comparison of physical properties between ultra-high\npurity argon (the gas used for the NSTF testing) and dry air, at both STP (0 ◦ C and 101.325\nkPa) and elevated temperatures (100 ◦ C, 101.325 kPa) is provided below in Tables 46 and\n47, respectively.\n\n     Table 46: Physical Properties of Dry Air and Argon at STP (0 ◦ C, 101.325 kPa)\n\n                                                      Air (dry)   Argon     % diff.\n          Ar Molecular weight       g/mol                28.970    39.948    31.9%\n          ρ  Density                kg/m3                 1.292    1.784     31.9%\n          Cp Heat capacity         kJ/kg-K               1.005      0.522    63.3%\n          k  Thermal conductivity  W/m-K                 0.024      0.016    38.6%\n          Pr Prandtl                   -                  0.711     0.665     6.7%\n          µ  Dynamic viscosity    106 Ns/m2              17.220    21.020    19.9%\n\n\n\n\n                                               201                                ANL-ART-47\n\f                                     Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                       August 2016\n\n        Table 47: Physical Properties of Elevated Temperature Dry Air and Argon\n                                               Air (dry)                     Argon\n                                       0 ◦C    100 ◦ C change      0 ◦C    100 ◦ C % change\n Ar   Molecular weight g/mol          28.970   28.970      0.0% 39.948     39.948          0.0%\n ρ    Density           kg/m3         1.292     0.946    -26.8% 1.784       1.305        -26.8%\n Cp   Heat capacity     kJ/kg-K       1.005     1.012      0.7% 0.522       0.521         -0.2%\n k    Thermal conduct. W/m-K           0.024    0.032     29.8% 0.016       0.021         29.3%\n Pr   Prandtl           -              0.711    0.701     -1.5% 0.665       0.664         -0.2%\n µ    Dynamic viscosity 106 N s/m2    17.220   21.900     27.2% 21.020     27.170         29.3%\n\n\n\nGas Enclosure Design\n\nA successful execution of the proposed testing plan required unique considerations to ensure\nthe introduction of only a single variable: gas composition. Due to the sensitivity of natural\ncirculation systems, changes in parameters such as pressure, temperature, geometry, among\nothers, would introduce unwanted influences that would reduce the clarity of the observed\nbehavior and confidence in the results. Thus, significant attention was given to the design\nof the apparatus and procedure of the transition sequence. An enclosure was constructed on\nthe Bldg. 308 floor, directly above the downcomer inlet of the NSTF, that had the following\nfeatures:\n\n  1. Contained a non-air gas volume of approximately 1,000 cu-ft\n  2. Ability to operate in ‘air by-pass’ and ‘argon ingress’ modes\n  3. Identical inlet flow areas for both modes\n  4. Transition between modes would not, even in a transient, cut-off air or gas flow\n\n   The enclosure itself measured 7x10x15 feet, and was constructed from a uni-strut frame\nand wrapped in two-layers of 6-mil (0.006-inch), moisture-resistance low-density polyethlyene\n(LDPE) film. A normal-operation air duct (24-inch diameter) was positioned within the\ncenter of the enclosure, while four by-pass valves (12-inch diameter each) were positioned\nat each of the four top corners. The 24-inch air-duct featured a mating seal at the base\nof the enclosure, and under normal-operation allowed the NSTF to draw in fresh ambient\nair without introducing argon into the facility. During the transition sequence, the four\n\nANL-ART-47                                     202","numLines":180,"startLine":5168,"totalLines":8102}}}
