{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01BEH3h7EQsxD7qsE4eHGi44","type":"tool_result","content":"5041\t7.3.4    INERI Test Case - Run023\n5042\t\n5043\tAs part of a formal collaboration initiative with Korea Atomic Energy Institute (KAERI), a\n5044\ttest series was drafted to examine differences in scaling philosophy. The testing was designed\n5045\tto be performed on three experimental test facilities: 1) Argonne 1/2 scale, 2) UW 1/4 scale,\n5046\tand 3) KAERI 1/4 scale. A high-level summary detailing the major differences provided in\n5047\tTable 41. All test facilities were based on the air-cooled RCCS design for the GA-MHTGR,\n5048\thowever the KAERI facility used a PMR200 as their full scale RPV reference and thus used\n5049\ta different basis for determining their normal testing conditions [43].\n5050\t\n5051\t           Table 41: Summary of scale test facilities at collaborating institutions\n5052\t\n5053\t                                       Argonne              KAERI               UW\n5054\t      Facility Name           -         NSTF               NACEF             -\n5055\t      Scale                   -           1/2                 1/4           1/4\n5056\t      Design Basis            -      GA-MHTGR              PMR200       GA-MHTGR\n5057\t      Heated surface type     -     Heaters + Plate     Heaters + Plate Heaters only\n5058\t      Total riser height     m            7.2                  4.5         3.76\n5059\t      Heated length of riser m           6.82                 4.05         3.51\n5060\t      Number ducts           #             12                   6            6\n5061\t      Heated area            m2          8.820               2.600         3.030\n5062\t\n5063\t\n5064\t\n5065\t   Earlier numerical work performed by KAERI suggested that the Planck number, a di-\n5066\tmensionless group describing the ratio of radiation to conduction, dominates heat transfer\n5067\tin the reactor cavity, while the Richardson number dominates the modes of heat transfer\n5068\twithin the risers. Preservation of the Richardson number was the basis for integral scaling\n5069\tof the NSTF, a scaling decision that favored heat transfer within the risers. Given that\n5070\tscaling distortions are unavoidable, e.g. the Richardson approach does not consider radi-\n5071\tation within the cavity, it is of significant interest to perform experimental studies of the\n5072\talternative philosophies. To compare and examine the differences in these two approaches, a\n5073\ttest series was drafted in collaboration between KAERI, Argonne, and UW. The series was\n5074\tsplit into two parts, the first, ‘Case I’, preserves the Richardson number (RiR = 1.0), while\n5075\t\n5076\tANL-ART-47                                   192\n5077\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n5078\tAugust 2016\n5079\t\n5080\t\n5081\tthe second, ‘Case II’, preserves the heat flux (q”R = 1.0). A table summarizing the target\n5082\tsteady-state operating conditions is provided below in Table 42.\n5083\t\n5084\t        Table 42: Target testing conditions, INERI testing series Case I and Case II\n5085\t\n5086\t                              Reference      Case 1, RiR = 1          Case 2, q”1 = 1\n5087\t Facility                 -   PMR200         ANL KAERI UW ANL KAERI UW\n5088\t Scale                    -       1           1/2   1/4   1/4   1/2   1/4   1/4\n5089\t No. Risers             #        220           12    6     6    12     6      6\n5090\t Flow rate, system     kg/s     10.39        0.359 0.138 0.129 0.227 0.067 0.058\n5091\t                        ◦\n5092\t Heated ∆T                C      98.0        98.0  98.0   98.0 98.0  98.0   98.0\n5093\t Q, system             kWt      1,027        35.47 16.67 12.72 22.47 6.67   5.78\n5094\t\n5095\t\n5096\t\n5097\t   The test cases, as performed on the NSTF, were completed as part of DataQuality023.\n5098\tThe operating window for active test operations (powered heaters) began at 14h04 on Febru-\n5099\tary 15th 2016 and spanned a period of 191 hours and 19 minutes. The facility was configured\n5100\tfor a forced flow configuration, which utilized exhaust flow out of the horizontal lofts and use\n5101\tof the forced fan blowers. Natural flow would have exceeded the target values for system flow\n5102\trate, thus additional resistance was required along the system ductwork. This was accom-\n5103\tplished by dampening the valves after the outlet plenum and immediately prior to the fan\n5104\tlofts. Two steady-state periods were maintained for the I-NERI objectives, the first at Case\n5105\tI conditions, and the second at Case II conditions. A summary of measured parameters\n5106\tduring the steady-state, along with their difference from the target values, is provided in\n5107\tTable 43. With completion of post-test data verification procedures and review of generated\n5108\tdata sets, the test was successfully able to meet acceptance criteria for both I-NERI cases.\n5109\t   The testing procedure specified an initial guess at the necessary electric power to obtain\n5110\tthe desired thermal power. Based on characteristic NSTF performance from earlier testing, it\n5111\twas assumed that approximately 65% efficiency could be expected. For Case I, this prescribed\n5112\tinitial estimates of 34.17 kWe to obtain 22.2 kWt , and for Case II initial estimates of 52.49\n5113\tkWe to obtain 34.1 kWt . However, difficulties were encountered while attempting to meet the\n5114\tdual requirements for system flow rate and heated section temperature rise. Ultimately, only\n5115\t\n5116\t                                               193                                 ANL-ART-47\n5117\t\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n5118\t                                                                                      August 2016\n5119\t\n5120\t          Table 43: Acceptance criteria and results for INERI test cases, Run023\n5121\t\n5122\t                                    Case 1, RiR = 1.0              Case 2,q”R = 1.0\n5123\t                                Planned Actual % diff.         Planned Actual % diff.\n5124\t    Run Time       hr               -      83 - 89       -         -      58 - 64       -\n5125\t    Electric Power kWe              -       65.99        -         -       51.99        -\n5126\t                   ◦\n5127\t    Riser Inlet      C              -       22.32        -         -       17.61        -\n5128\t                   ◦\n5129\t    Riser Outlet     C              -      114.55        -         -       93.34        -\n5130\t    Chimney Inlet ◦ C               -      116.68        -         -      114.82        -\n5131\t    Flow Rate      kg/min         21.52     21.50     0.09%      13.63     13.60     0.25%\n5132\t    Thermal Power kWt             35.47     34.12     3.79%      22.47     22.21     0.82%\n5133\t                   ◦\n5134\t    ∆T               C             98.0     94.36     3.90%       98.0     97.2      1.28%\n5135\t\n5136\t\n5137\t\n5138\t42.7% efficiency was achieved during Case II, while 52% was archived during Case I. This low\n5139\tthermal efficiency stem from the significantly reduced system flow rates and elevated system\n5140\ttemperatures and subsequent increased heat loss, but also due to degraded heat transfer\n5141\twithin the riser ducts. LUNA fibers installed at the outlet face of the risers provide insight\n5142\tinto the temperature profile, Figure 94. Visible is the flattened temperature gradient along\n5143\tthe core of the risers, along with sharp rises near the wall of Case II. The references cases,\n5144\tincluding Case I and baseline cases, exhibit a more gradual gradient that follows a relatively\n5145\tsmooth transition from the core to the walls.\n5146\t\n5147\t\n5148\t\n5149\t\n5150\tANL-ART-47                                   194\n5151\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n5152\tAugust 2016\n5153\t\n5154\t\n5155\t\n5156\t\n5157\t       Figure 94: Temperature profile across outlet face of riser ducts, LUNA fibers\n5158\t\n5159\t\n5160\t\n5161\t\n5162\t                                               195                             ANL-ART-47\n5163\t\f                                     Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n5164\t                                                                                       August 2016\n5165\t\n5166\t\n5167\t\n5168\t7.4      Off-normal Scenarios\n5169\t\n5170\t7.4.1     Blocked Riser Channels - Run015"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"47d9ec1e-27f2-4086-90f4-79a8199340a9","uuid":"e7c909e7-1423-4698-980a-65de89e6d0ae","timestamp":"2026-07-02T09:36:24.310Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/root/curator/source/report_full_text.txt","content":"7.3.4    INERI Test Case - Run023\n\nAs part of a formal collaboration initiative with Korea Atomic Energy Institute (KAERI), a\ntest series was drafted to examine differences in scaling philosophy. The testing was designed\nto be performed on three experimental test facilities: 1) Argonne 1/2 scale, 2) UW 1/4 scale,\nand 3) KAERI 1/4 scale. A high-level summary detailing the major differences provided in\nTable 41. All test facilities were based on the air-cooled RCCS design for the GA-MHTGR,\nhowever the KAERI facility used a PMR200 as their full scale RPV reference and thus used\na different basis for determining their normal testing conditions [43].\n\n           Table 41: Summary of scale test facilities at collaborating institutions\n\n                                       Argonne              KAERI               UW\n      Facility Name           -         NSTF               NACEF             -\n      Scale                   -           1/2                 1/4           1/4\n      Design Basis            -      GA-MHTGR              PMR200       GA-MHTGR\n      Heated surface type     -     Heaters + Plate     Heaters + Plate Heaters only\n      Total riser height     m            7.2                  4.5         3.76\n      Heated length of riser m           6.82                 4.05         3.51\n      Number ducts           #             12                   6            6\n      Heated area            m2          8.820               2.600         3.030\n\n\n\n   Earlier numerical work performed by KAERI suggested that the Planck number, a di-\nmensionless group describing the ratio of radiation to conduction, dominates heat transfer\nin the reactor cavity, while the Richardson number dominates the modes of heat transfer\nwithin the risers. Preservation of the Richardson number was the basis for integral scaling\nof the NSTF, a scaling decision that favored heat transfer within the risers. Given that\nscaling distortions are unavoidable, e.g. the Richardson approach does not consider radi-\nation within the cavity, it is of significant interest to perform experimental studies of the\nalternative philosophies. To compare and examine the differences in these two approaches, a\ntest series was drafted in collaboration between KAERI, Argonne, and UW. The series was\nsplit into two parts, the first, ‘Case I’, preserves the Richardson number (RiR = 1.0), while\n\nANL-ART-47                                   192\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\nthe second, ‘Case II’, preserves the heat flux (q”R = 1.0). A table summarizing the target\nsteady-state operating conditions is provided below in Table 42.\n\n        Table 42: Target testing conditions, INERI testing series Case I and Case II\n\n                              Reference      Case 1, RiR = 1          Case 2, q”1 = 1\n Facility                 -   PMR200         ANL KAERI UW ANL KAERI UW\n Scale                    -       1           1/2   1/4   1/4   1/2   1/4   1/4\n No. Risers             #        220           12    6     6    12     6      6\n Flow rate, system     kg/s     10.39        0.359 0.138 0.129 0.227 0.067 0.058\n                        ◦\n Heated ∆T                C      98.0        98.0  98.0   98.0 98.0  98.0   98.0\n Q, system             kWt      1,027        35.47 16.67 12.72 22.47 6.67   5.78\n\n\n\n   The test cases, as performed on the NSTF, were completed as part of DataQuality023.\nThe operating window for active test operations (powered heaters) began at 14h04 on Febru-\nary 15th 2016 and spanned a period of 191 hours and 19 minutes. The facility was configured\nfor a forced flow configuration, which utilized exhaust flow out of the horizontal lofts and use\nof the forced fan blowers. Natural flow would have exceeded the target values for system flow\nrate, thus additional resistance was required along the system ductwork. This was accom-\nplished by dampening the valves after the outlet plenum and immediately prior to the fan\nlofts. Two steady-state periods were maintained for the I-NERI objectives, the first at Case\nI conditions, and the second at Case II conditions. A summary of measured parameters\nduring the steady-state, along with their difference from the target values, is provided in\nTable 43. With completion of post-test data verification procedures and review of generated\ndata sets, the test was successfully able to meet acceptance criteria for both I-NERI cases.\n   The testing procedure specified an initial guess at the necessary electric power to obtain\nthe desired thermal power. Based on characteristic NSTF performance from earlier testing, it\nwas assumed that approximately 65% efficiency could be expected. For Case I, this prescribed\ninitial estimates of 34.17 kWe to obtain 22.2 kWt , and for Case II initial estimates of 52.49\nkWe to obtain 34.1 kWt . However, difficulties were encountered while attempting to meet the\ndual requirements for system flow rate and heated section temperature rise. Ultimately, only\n\n                                               193                                 ANL-ART-47\n\f                                    Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                      August 2016\n\n          Table 43: Acceptance criteria and results for INERI test cases, Run023\n\n                                    Case 1, RiR = 1.0              Case 2,q”R = 1.0\n                                Planned Actual % diff.         Planned Actual % diff.\n    Run Time       hr               -      83 - 89       -         -      58 - 64       -\n    Electric Power kWe              -       65.99        -         -       51.99        -\n                   ◦\n    Riser Inlet      C              -       22.32        -         -       17.61        -\n                   ◦\n    Riser Outlet     C              -      114.55        -         -       93.34        -\n    Chimney Inlet ◦ C               -      116.68        -         -      114.82        -\n    Flow Rate      kg/min         21.52     21.50     0.09%      13.63     13.60     0.25%\n    Thermal Power kWt             35.47     34.12     3.79%      22.47     22.21     0.82%\n                   ◦\n    ∆T               C             98.0     94.36     3.90%       98.0     97.2      1.28%\n\n\n\n42.7% efficiency was achieved during Case II, while 52% was archived during Case I. This low\nthermal efficiency stem from the significantly reduced system flow rates and elevated system\ntemperatures and subsequent increased heat loss, but also due to degraded heat transfer\nwithin the riser ducts. LUNA fibers installed at the outlet face of the risers provide insight\ninto the temperature profile, Figure 94. Visible is the flattened temperature gradient along\nthe core of the risers, along with sharp rises near the wall of Case II. The references cases,\nincluding Case I and baseline cases, exhibit a more gradual gradient that follows a relatively\nsmooth transition from the core to the walls.\n\n\n\n\nANL-ART-47                                   194\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n\n       Figure 94: Temperature profile across outlet face of riser ducts, LUNA fibers\n\n\n\n\n                                               195                             ANL-ART-47\n\f                                     Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                       August 2016\n\n\n\n7.4      Off-normal Scenarios\n\n7.4.1     Blocked Riser Channels - Run015","numLines":130,"startLine":5041,"totalLines":8102}}}
