{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RNRipfcKWexxKebFPeHQE3","type":"tool_result","content":"6255\t\n6256\t8.3.2     Full Scale Application\n6257\t\n6258\tBest attempts were made to accurately capture the primary features of the GA RCCS\n6259\tinstallation, however a select number of differences remain between the scaled NSTF and a\n6260\tconceptual full size installation. Thermal hydraulic distortions have been reduced by scaling\n6261\tstudies and similarity relationships, e.g. ∆TR = 1, however these were focused to the heated\n6262\tlength and areas near the RPV. The geometry and mechanics of isothermal segments remain\n6263\tunique to a full scale installation, however several of the tests performed in the NSTF provide\n6264\tvaluable insight into their influences and most probable system response.\n6265\t\n6266\t   Readily apparent is the difference between the NSTF and full GA RCCS inlet or down-\n6267\tcomer ductwork. The GA downcomers run the full length of the heated cavity and are\n6268\tpositioned between the concrete containment and the heated riser ducts. This installation\n6269\tintroduces two considerations: 1) concrete containment (NSTF cold wall) surface temper-\n6270\tatures, and 2) riser gas inlet temperatures. The first would not influence the overall heat\n6271\tremoval performance of the RCCS, however the concrete temperature is one area of interest\n6272\tfor reactor designers and would require further work to accurately predict. The second would\n6273\t\n6274\tANL-ART-47                                   240\n6275\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n6276\tAugust 2016\n6277\t\n6278\t\n6279\thave strong influences on the RCCS performance; co-located downcomers would create ele-\n6280\tvated riser inlet temperatures to near 40 ◦ C, analogous to the studied hot-weather testing\n6281\tperformed on the NSTF, e.g. Run020. Based on the observations and results of this test,\n6282\televated inlet temperatures reduced the overall efficiency of the stack effect and induced\n6283\tdeteriorated system performance due to the lower values of ∆ρ/∆T. Thus, the NSTF repre-\n6284\tsented a best case scenario and it can be expected that performance would be reduced with\n6285\ta containment housed downcomer ductwork.\n6286\t\n6287\t   The second difference, stemming from the relative elevations and flow lengths of the inlet\n6288\tand outlet ductwork, are significant contributors to the performance and worthy of discussion.\n6289\tBeginning with the former, the inlet to the NSTF is located within the laboratory space and\n6290\t2.72 feet below the thermal center of the heated cavity. The outlet is positioned above the\n6291\troof line, 64.45-feet above the thermal center, and results in a total elevation delta between\n6292\tinlet and outlet faces of 56.47-feet. The total elevation delta for the full scale GA RCCS,\n6293\tas described in literature [10], reflects a dimension of only 24.67-feet. A summary of the\n6294\tphysical elevations for relevant configurations is provided below in Table 56.\n6295\t\n6296\t          Table 56: Elevations of inlet and exhaust ports, all dimensions in meters\n6297\t\n6298\t                                 Inlet Port [m]            Outlet Port [m]       ∆ [m]\n6299\t                              Rel. Grade Rel. Core       Rel. Grade Rel. Core\n6300\t      NSTF (baseline)            -1.64        -0.83            18.84   19.64     20.47\n6301\t      GA RCCS                    36.88        20.80            44.40   28.31     7.52\n6302\t      NSTF (adj. config.)        18.84        19.64            18.84   19.64     0.00\n6303\t\n6304\t\n6305\t\n6306\t   Moreover, the presence of above-grade inlet ductwork inherently requires additional duct-\n6307\twork to plumb the working fluid from the inlet port to the heated risers. These piping runs\n6308\tadd frictional losses and increase the overall flow restriction from the outside environment\n6309\tto the heated region. It has been shown by previous works [37] that the introduction of a\n6310\tconstricted entry region to a natural circulation system can restrict the laminar upward flow\n6311\tthrough the heated region, altering the pattern of natural convective flow. The boundary\n6312\t\n6313\t                                               241                                ANL-ART-47\n6314\t\f                                     Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n6315\t                                                                                       August 2016\n6316\t\n6317\t\n6318\tlayer nearest the heated wall demands more fluid than the cooler center can provide, result-\n6319\ting in a near zero centerline velocity. The authors defined a key parameter li /l, where li is\n6320\tthe length of the unheated and l is the length of the heated ducts. The length is analogous to\n6321\ta restriction based on frictional losses and can be used to generalize any system with bends,\n6322\tconstrictions, added lengths, etc.. A summary of these parameters, as applied to the NSTF\n6323\tand full scale RCCS designs, is provided by Table 57.\n6324\t\n6325\tTable 57: Geometric ratios of loop segments. `i refers to all inlet ductwork, ` the heated\n6326\tlength, and `exit the exit chimney length\n6327\t\n6328\t                                      Lengths     Flow Area        Wetted Perimeter\n6329\t                                        `i /`     `i /(`+`exit )     `i /(`+`exit )\n6330\t              NSTF (baseline)           0.62          0.10               0.07\n6331\t              GA RCCS                   6.06          2.01               1.20\n6332\t              NSTF (adj. config.)       4.64          1.39               0.70\n6333\t\n6334\t\n6335\t\n6336\t\n6337\t   As shown by Run017, a baseline test case performed with the NSTF in the ‘adjacent\n6338\tchimney’ configuration, the NSTF saw a reduction in both heat removal performance and\n6339\tstability. The observations made were based on a over-representation of the full scale design,\n6340\thowever raises important points on the stability of safety grade natural circulation systems.\n6341\tA stable system should, in an ideal case, reflect a single vertical pipe with a heated length near\n6342\tthe base and a tall adiabatic chimney length. As the requirements of physical installations\n6343\tare often unable to cater to ideal geometry, the closer an installation trends towards a U-\n6344\tloop, and away from a vertical pipe, the less confidence can be had on predictability and\n6345\tsystem stability. This uncertainty manifests itself through a reduced level of confidence in\n6346\tthe flow direction within the network. As shown by the NSTF program, along with similar\n6347\tresearch efforts, a U-shaped network experiencing natural circulation flow can readily shift\n6348\tflow directions in either chaotic (e.g. toroidal thermosiphon [38]) or unstable modes (e.g.\n6349\tminor perturbations as observed in the NSTF).\n6350\t\n6351\t   The third and final difference between the scaled and full size RCCS designs is the\n6352\t\n6353\tANL-ART-47                                      242\n6354\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n6355\tAugust 2016\n6356\t\n6357\t\n6358\tnumber of parallel channels within the overall piping network. As discussed earlier, the dual\n6359\tchimney configuration presented challenges in maintaining as-intended flow direction. With\n6360\tfour parallel chimney paths in the full size design, it is improbable to expect the system\n6361\twill maintain symmetric and equal flow across all legs. A minor increase in air flow rate\n6362\twithin a single chimney lowers the pressure in that region of the chimney, thus increasing\n6363\tthe driving buoyancy force and induced draft. With increased draft the chimney would draw\n6364\tmore air from the plenum region, escalating a self-perpetuating cycle and exacerbate the flow\n6365\tasymmetry. While counter-intuitive, the reduction in total available parallel paths, along\n6366\twith introduction of channel asymmetries, would increase system stability (working against\n6367\tthis philosophy is the consideration for redundancy, a balance that is difficult to define).\n6368\t\n6369\t\n6370\t\n6371\t\n6372\t                                               243                                 ANL-ART-47\n6373\t\fThis page was intentionally left blank.\n6374\t\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n6375\tAugust 2016\n6376\t\n6377\t\n6378\t\n6379\t\n6380\tChapter 9\n6381\t\n6382\tConclusion\n6383\tThe NSTF program at Argonne successfully completed over 2,250 hours of active test op-\n6384\terations across a 33-month period to evaluate the feasibility of the air-based RCCS concept"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"47d9ec1e-27f2-4086-90f4-79a8199340a9","uuid":"5b0a3306-f67d-4c56-a73a-b43eec8c055f","timestamp":"2026-07-02T09:36:42.487Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/root/curator/source/report_full_text.txt","content":"\n8.3.2     Full Scale Application\n\nBest attempts were made to accurately capture the primary features of the GA RCCS\ninstallation, however a select number of differences remain between the scaled NSTF and a\nconceptual full size installation. Thermal hydraulic distortions have been reduced by scaling\nstudies and similarity relationships, e.g. ∆TR = 1, however these were focused to the heated\nlength and areas near the RPV. The geometry and mechanics of isothermal segments remain\nunique to a full scale installation, however several of the tests performed in the NSTF provide\nvaluable insight into their influences and most probable system response.\n\n   Readily apparent is the difference between the NSTF and full GA RCCS inlet or down-\ncomer ductwork. The GA downcomers run the full length of the heated cavity and are\npositioned between the concrete containment and the heated riser ducts. This installation\nintroduces two considerations: 1) concrete containment (NSTF cold wall) surface temper-\natures, and 2) riser gas inlet temperatures. The first would not influence the overall heat\nremoval performance of the RCCS, however the concrete temperature is one area of interest\nfor reactor designers and would require further work to accurately predict. The second would\n\nANL-ART-47                                   240\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\nhave strong influences on the RCCS performance; co-located downcomers would create ele-\nvated riser inlet temperatures to near 40 ◦ C, analogous to the studied hot-weather testing\nperformed on the NSTF, e.g. Run020. Based on the observations and results of this test,\nelevated inlet temperatures reduced the overall efficiency of the stack effect and induced\ndeteriorated system performance due to the lower values of ∆ρ/∆T. Thus, the NSTF repre-\nsented a best case scenario and it can be expected that performance would be reduced with\na containment housed downcomer ductwork.\n\n   The second difference, stemming from the relative elevations and flow lengths of the inlet\nand outlet ductwork, are significant contributors to the performance and worthy of discussion.\nBeginning with the former, the inlet to the NSTF is located within the laboratory space and\n2.72 feet below the thermal center of the heated cavity. The outlet is positioned above the\nroof line, 64.45-feet above the thermal center, and results in a total elevation delta between\ninlet and outlet faces of 56.47-feet. The total elevation delta for the full scale GA RCCS,\nas described in literature [10], reflects a dimension of only 24.67-feet. A summary of the\nphysical elevations for relevant configurations is provided below in Table 56.\n\n          Table 56: Elevations of inlet and exhaust ports, all dimensions in meters\n\n                                 Inlet Port [m]            Outlet Port [m]       ∆ [m]\n                              Rel. Grade Rel. Core       Rel. Grade Rel. Core\n      NSTF (baseline)            -1.64        -0.83            18.84   19.64     20.47\n      GA RCCS                    36.88        20.80            44.40   28.31     7.52\n      NSTF (adj. config.)        18.84        19.64            18.84   19.64     0.00\n\n\n\n   Moreover, the presence of above-grade inlet ductwork inherently requires additional duct-\nwork to plumb the working fluid from the inlet port to the heated risers. These piping runs\nadd frictional losses and increase the overall flow restriction from the outside environment\nto the heated region. It has been shown by previous works [37] that the introduction of a\nconstricted entry region to a natural circulation system can restrict the laminar upward flow\nthrough the heated region, altering the pattern of natural convective flow. The boundary\n\n                                               241                                ANL-ART-47\n\f                                     Final Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\n                                                                                       August 2016\n\n\nlayer nearest the heated wall demands more fluid than the cooler center can provide, result-\ning in a near zero centerline velocity. The authors defined a key parameter li /l, where li is\nthe length of the unheated and l is the length of the heated ducts. The length is analogous to\na restriction based on frictional losses and can be used to generalize any system with bends,\nconstrictions, added lengths, etc.. A summary of these parameters, as applied to the NSTF\nand full scale RCCS designs, is provided by Table 57.\n\nTable 57: Geometric ratios of loop segments. `i refers to all inlet ductwork, ` the heated\nlength, and `exit the exit chimney length\n\n                                      Lengths     Flow Area        Wetted Perimeter\n                                        `i /`     `i /(`+`exit )     `i /(`+`exit )\n              NSTF (baseline)           0.62          0.10               0.07\n              GA RCCS                   6.06          2.01               1.20\n              NSTF (adj. config.)       4.64          1.39               0.70\n\n\n\n\n   As shown by Run017, a baseline test case performed with the NSTF in the ‘adjacent\nchimney’ configuration, the NSTF saw a reduction in both heat removal performance and\nstability. The observations made were based on a over-representation of the full scale design,\nhowever raises important points on the stability of safety grade natural circulation systems.\nA stable system should, in an ideal case, reflect a single vertical pipe with a heated length near\nthe base and a tall adiabatic chimney length. As the requirements of physical installations\nare often unable to cater to ideal geometry, the closer an installation trends towards a U-\nloop, and away from a vertical pipe, the less confidence can be had on predictability and\nsystem stability. This uncertainty manifests itself through a reduced level of confidence in\nthe flow direction within the network. As shown by the NSTF program, along with similar\nresearch efforts, a U-shaped network experiencing natural circulation flow can readily shift\nflow directions in either chaotic (e.g. toroidal thermosiphon [38]) or unstable modes (e.g.\nminor perturbations as observed in the NSTF).\n\n   The third and final difference between the scaled and full size RCCS designs is the\n\nANL-ART-47                                      242\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\nnumber of parallel channels within the overall piping network. As discussed earlier, the dual\nchimney configuration presented challenges in maintaining as-intended flow direction. With\nfour parallel chimney paths in the full size design, it is improbable to expect the system\nwill maintain symmetric and equal flow across all legs. A minor increase in air flow rate\nwithin a single chimney lowers the pressure in that region of the chimney, thus increasing\nthe driving buoyancy force and induced draft. With increased draft the chimney would draw\nmore air from the plenum region, escalating a self-perpetuating cycle and exacerbate the flow\nasymmetry. While counter-intuitive, the reduction in total available parallel paths, along\nwith introduction of channel asymmetries, would increase system stability (working against\nthis philosophy is the consideration for redundancy, a balance that is difficult to define).\n\n\n\n\n                                               243                                 ANL-ART-47\n\fThis page was intentionally left blank.\n\fFinal Project Report on RCCS Testing with the Air-Based NSTF\nAugust 2016\n\n\n\n\nChapter 9\n\nConclusion\nThe NSTF program at Argonne successfully completed over 2,250 hours of active test op-\nerations across a 33-month period to evaluate the feasibility of the air-based RCCS concept","numLines":130,"startLine":6255,"totalLines":8102}}}
